<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Taiwan-China     07-12 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-China,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Eases Ban on Travel From China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Nationalist Party on Tuesday
eased a 39-year-old ban on visits to Taiwan by mainland China
residents and approved expanding indirect trade with Beijing to
include raw materials.
   The new policy toward rival Communist China approved by the 13th
Nationalist Party congress after several days of debate also
suggested Taiwan journalists and athletes may be allowed to go the
mainland.
   Under the new policy, the Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, will
review requests from mainland Chinese to travel to Taiwan if close
relatives are gravely ill or die.
   Intellectuals from mainland China ``who are opposed to
Marxism-Leninism or have fought to maintain academic freedom'' will
be allowed to come to Taiwan if invited.
   Further relaxation will depend on ``whether and how the mainland
responds to our new policy,'' Hsiao Chang-le, head of the
Nationalists' Mainland Operations Department, told a news
conference.
   Last October, the Nationalists ended a longstanding ban on
travel to China so Taiwan residents could visit relatives for
family reunions. More than 100,000 have made the trip since.
   The ban on travel across the Taiwan Straits was imposed when the
Nationalists fled to this island in 1949 after losing a civil war
to the Communists on the Chinese mainland. The Nationalists
government still claims to be the rightful ruler of all China and
refuses all official contact with Beijing.
   Hsiao said that also under the new policy, mainland Chinese
students studying in the United States or Europe can apply to visit
Taiwan through an unidentified private organization beginning in
August or September.
   He said Taiwan athletes may be allowed to compete on mainland
China in events sponsored by private organizations and said the
island's Olympic committee would study the possibility of sending a
team to Beijing for the 1990 Asian Games.
   The party statement also indicated reporters may soon be allowed
to travel to the mainland for news-gathering, but did not propose
relax other travel restrictions opposed by many Taiwanese.
   Although no direct trade links exist between Taiwan and China,
the Nationalists tolerate a flourishing trade through third
countries that could reach a record $2 billion this year.
   Taiwan government officials last year announced 29 items could
be imported from China indirectly but the list did not include raw
materials and agricultural products now to be tolerated.
</TEXT>
