<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Price'sSeat 1stLd-Writethru a0878 07-12 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Price's Seat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0878,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costello Wins Special Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Costello winning. Picks up
4th graf pvs `The five-county...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic candidate in a southern
Illinois congressional race in November won a special primary
Tuesday allowing him to also run to serve out the current term of
the late U.S. Rep. Melvin Price.
   Jerry F. Costello, chairman of the St. Clair County Board,
easily defeated East St. Louis Alderman Clarence Ellis Sr. in the
the 21st Congressional District's Democratic primary.
   With 429 of the 469 precincts, or 91.5 percent, reporting,
unofficial returns showed Costello with 17,040 votes to Ellis'
1,930.
   Republican Robert H. ``Bob'' Gaffner, of Greenville, who had no
opposition in the special primary, had 3,671 votes.
   The five-county district has 270,060 registered voters, but
morning thundershowers, summer distractions and a lack of interest
in the election held down turnout, officials said.
   The primary winners will face off Aug. 9 in a special general
election. The winner of that contest will finish the term of Price,
a Democrat from East St. Louis, who died April 22 of pancreatic
cancer. Price, who was 83, had already announced he would not seek
re-election after serving 44 years in Congress.
   In March, Costello and Gaffner won their respective primaries
for the right to run in the November election.
   After Price's death, Illinois law mandated a special election to
fill the office for the remainder of the term that ends in January.
The special election offers its winner a possible advantage in
November and, if elected then, seniority over 30 to 40 incoming
freshmen House members in January.
   During the current campaign, Ellis stressed his political
experience and education. He has served 13 years on the Aldermanic
Council and has masters' degrees in public administration and
education administration.
   The Costello camp promised to work for economic development, for
protection of the Social Security system and against drugs.
</TEXT>
