<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     07-12 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Proposes Resumption Of Family-Reunion Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea called on communist North
Korea Wednesday to resume humanitarian programs to promote reunions
between some 10 million people separated from their families on
this divided peninsula.
   Kim Sang-hyup, president of South Korea's National Red Cross,
made the proposal in a telephone message to his North Korean
counterpart Son Sung Pil.
   ``In view of the ardent aspirations of separated family members,
it is our imperative task to find out the whereabouts of their
dispersed family members and relatives and help them to meet
freely,'' Kim said in the message.
   Korea was divided into the Soviet-backed north and
U.S.-supported south at the end of World War II. It is estimated
that at least 10 million people were separated from their relatives
by the division and during the Korean War in 1950-53.
   In his message, Kim proposed the two Koreas resume by the end of
the year a family-reunion program suspended since 1986.
   His appeal followed a statement Thursday by President Roh
Tae-woo who called for improved relations with North Korea,
including broad exchanges of visits between people of the two
countries.
   North Korea dismissed Roh's gestures as ``nothing new'' and
renewed its own demand for holding a ``national conference'' to
discuss, among other things, co-hosting of this summer's Olympic
Games in Seoul and the withdrawal of 42,000 U.S. military personnel
from South Korea.
   Under the North Korean plan, the conference would be attended by
about 50 government officials as well as social, political and
cultural leaders from each side.
   Kim specifically proposed that the Red Cross societies of the
two Koreas serve as an intermediary to help elderly people contact
each other.
   His office said the program could be extended to include some
one million overseas Koreans who want to locate relatives in the
two Koreas through the Geneva-based Interantional Red Cross.
   In 1985, for the first time in 40 years, the two governments
agreed to an exchange involving 151 people. The agreement also
included visits by cultural groups and 51 journalists.
   North Korea withdrew from the Red Cross contacts and economic
and parliamentary talks in 1986 to protest joint U.S.-South Korea
military exercises.
</TEXT>
