<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 6thLd-Writethru a0781 07-12 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0781,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veep Decision Nears; Jackson Says He Wants The Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 6-8 to UPDATE with Brountas comments after
meeting with Dukakis</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee-to-be Michael
Dukakis pondered possible running mates on Monday, with Jesse
Jackson pressing more strongly than ever for a spot on the ticket.
Signs pointed to an announcement within a few days.
   Dukakis and his top adviser, Paul Brountas, met at Dukakis'
house Monday morning. Brountas then traveled to Washington to meet
with Jackson, who said for the first time Monday that he would take
Dukakis up on an offer to join the ticket.
   Jackson told reporters after his meeting with Brountas that ``it
is self-evident'' that he wants the job, and said he assured
Brountas he would be a loyal vice president.
   ``If it was offered to me, I would accept it,'' Jackson said. He
has said repeatedly he deserves an offer of the No. 2 spot, but up
until Monday, he had declined to say publicly what his answer would
be if that offer were extended.
   Brountas said the two had an ``excellent meeting...very
productive'' but declined to provide any details of the discussion.
Afterward, he flew back to Boston for a late-night meeting with
Dukakis.
   After a 45-minute session at Dukakis' home, with campaign
manager Susan Estrich in attendance, Brountas was asked if a
decision had been made.
   ``No comment,'' he said.
   Asked if the selection process was over, Brountas responded:
``He (Dukakis) can always ask more questions if he wants.''
   Dukakis is expected to announce his choice this week before
heading to the Democratic National Convention, which opens next
Monday. Some aides said an announcement could come as soon at
Tuesday, but others said there was still no timetable.
   Although the Massachusetts governor faces a budget crisis at
home that threatens to hurt his national candidacy, he arrived at
the Statehouse late because of the Brountas meeting. Dukakis had
planned to leave within three hours but ended up staying for nearly
seven _ still a few hours shorter than his usual workday.
   ``Have a good evening,'' was all Dukakis would say to reporters
as he left for home after a meeting with three top campaign aides,
including campaign manager Susan Estrich.
   Several campaign aides said privately that the time at home was
to be spent working to pick a running mate. ``He hasn't made up his
mind yet,'' said one Dukakis aide. ``Or if he has, he hasn't told
anybody.''
   Jackson had been scheduled to meet with Brountas last Friday,
but the meeting was postponed with Brountas saying he needed more
time to ``receive and review'' information from the Jackson
campaign. The Dukakis campaign had requested detailed personal,
financial and medical information from Jackson and other prospects.
   The civil rights leader has said he is the most qualified to
share the ticket with Dukakis and has called the others known to be
under consideration ``unknown quantities.'' They include Sens. John
Glenn of Ohio, Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
and Bob Graham of Florida and Reps. Richard Gephardt of Missouri
and Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   Dukakis aides have been aggravated by Jackson's aggressive
effort to portray himself as the logical running mate and by an
apparent effort by Jackson campaign manager Gerald Austin to
discourage the selection of Gore. Jackson said Austin's comments
were unathorized.
   During a weekend campaign swing through several Western states,
Dukakis responded tersely when asked if Jackson would have veto
power over his decision. He said the decision was his alone to make.
   Dukakis is to travel Tuesday night to Washington, where he is
scheduled to hold a series of Capitol Hill meetings on Wednesday
and also address the annual convention of the NAACP.
   When he arrives back in Boston on Wednesday night, Dukakis will
have two work days left to make good on his promise to resolve the
state's budget problems by the end of the week.
   On his desk is an $11.75 billion spending plan for fiscal 1989,
which began July 1. Legislative leaders have urged Dukakis to use
his line-item veto power to reduce that spending plan. Dukakis also
is awaiting legislative passage of a politically sensitive plan to
eliminate the $370 million deficit remaining from fiscal 1988.
   The governor is scheduled to take Saturday off and fly to
Atlanta for the convention on Sunday.
</TEXT>
