<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newspage-All-Stars     07-12 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage-All-Stars,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AL 2, NL 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American League beat the National League
2-1 in another pitcher-dominated All-Star Game Tuesday night,
winning the matchup for only the fourth time in 26 games.
   American League pitchers held the NL stars to six hits.
   The NL still leads the series 37-21, with three of those losses
coming under Manager Whitey Herzog. He became the only NL manager
to lose three times.
   Oakland's Terry Steinbach, who has only a .217 batting average,
homered in the third inning off Dwight Gooden and hit a
bases-loaded sacrifice fly to the warning track in the fourth
against Bob Knepper. Steinbach, one of 30 first-time All-Stars, was
named the game's most valuable player.
   AL pitcher Frank Viola set down the only six hitters he faced
for the victory and Dennis Eckersley, leading the majors with 26
saves, got the final three batters.
   A crowd of 55,837 watched the game, including Vice President
George Bush, who threw out the first ball.
</TEXT>
