<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Euthanasia     07-12 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Euthanasia,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Mercy Killing Is Common In Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mercy killing is common in many Chinese
hospitals, an official report said today.
   The China Daily said that one Shanghai hospital reported 28
percent of the 563 deaths in its medical, surgical and gynecology
departments in the past three years were the result of euthanasia.
   Incurably ill patients were allowed to die at the request of
relatives who wanted to end the patients' suffering, it said.
   The report said most cases of euthanasia in Chinese hospitals
were ``passive,'' meaning the withholding of life-preserving
treatment to terminally ill patients.
   Mercy killing is not a sanctioned medical practice in China, but
recent polls have shown substantial popular acceptance.
   The People's Daily reported last April that a survey of 283
retired people in Shanghai found more than half favored euthanasia
for incurably ill patients.
</TEXT>
