<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Convention-Windfall Bjt   07-12 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convention-Windfall, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Price Hikes Commonplace As Democrats Converge On Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With hot water going for nearly $27 a gallon and
potted plants renting for $79.50, there is money to be made at next
week's Democratic National Convention.
   The days when delegates pulled into town with a $10 bill and a
clean shirt and left without changing either are history.
   The 35,000 visitors for the July 18-21 event are expected to
leave about $30 million in Atlanta. But some local plans to partake
of the windfall have gone awry.
   An employee of an Atlanta office furniture and equipment rental
firm told one caller his company and many others like it had raised
prices 30 to 40 percent in anticipation of the convention rush.
   So many news organizations and some Democratic National
Committee groups flocked to a Detroit-area firm willing to deliver,
install, maintain and remove typewriters, computers, copiers,
telefax machines and office furniture at roughly half the going
Atlanta cost.
   For example, water coolers were quoted locally at $30 a day. The
Detroit firm provides them at $30 a month.
   Some Atlanta companies are renting typing tables at $50 each,
waste baskets for up to $27 and chairs for as much as $40.
   Convention Florist Service Int'l. Inc. lists the rental price on
7-foot green plant at $79.50. Local florists checked by telephone
offered to sell similar plants outright for from $45 to $65.
   Hotels are also looking at a boom, with rooms for delegates,
reporters, VIPs, fund-raisers, lobbyists, protesters and the
curious at a premium.
   A prospectus for a major textile convention coming to Atlanta in
September lists a single room at the Atlanta Hilton at $102. A
reservations clerk quoted a rate of $135 for the Democratic
convention.
   A spot check found some hotels charging higher rates although
some quoted rates at or below the rate being charged at the
September textile convention.
   Many of the receptions, news conferences and hospitality rooms
scheduled for the convention will be held at the Georgia World
Congress Center, home base for most of the 12,000 news media
representatives plus the party faithful who cannot fit into the
convention hall.
   MGR Inc., the food service contractor for all events there, will
cater about 950 convention functions over four days, from small
hospitality suites to a windup ``victory party'' for 30,000.
   MGR president Phillip Noyes said the company is hiring about 500
extra employees to handle the rush. However, the prices have been
in effect for a year.
   ``We aren't the cheapest in the country,'' he acknowledged. ``We
provide a highly specialized service and people pay for that. Our
business isn't any different. People want a product that's iced
down, chilled and ready, and all that goes with it.''
   Last year a poll of 500 trade shows and conventions picked MGR
as the best convention catering firm in the country.
   MGR will provide soft drinks at about $43 a case. Most meals
will be served buffet-style with lunch at $14.50 and dinner at
$18.50.
   Coffee, or hot water to make tea or instant coffee, is about $27
a gallon after tax and a 17 percent service charge are added. Fruit
juice will be about $29 a gallon. Convention tenants are barred
from having their own coffee makers.
   ``They're charging $165 for 100 little pieces of chicken.
Everybody is complaining,'' said Jesse Jackson aide Yolanda
Carroway.
   ``Prices have not been raised at all,'' said Tim Sterns, who
oversees convention catering for the Democratic National Committee.
He said DNC surveys showed the prices to be lower than those at
many downtown hotels.
   ``They have been very accommodating,'' he said when asked about
the price of MGR's coffee service. ``They put in a program where
the initial service is $50 and they provide a coffee maker. Each
day they will deliver supplies at a lower rate for people who want
to make their own coffee. They have made some concessions in that
way.''
   Delegates may get a break, however, if they come down with
toothaches. An Atlanta dentist, Edward J. Mills, is offering free
emergency dental service to delegates during the convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
