<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Duarte     07-12 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Duarte,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte, Defying Cancer, Gets Back to Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defying terminal cancer,
President Jose Napoleon Duarte returned from Washington to begin
catching up on official business after six weeks' absence.
   ``I am here now to reassume the presidency, in order to continue
working for what I most love: democracy,'' the 62-year-old Duarte
said upon arriving Monday from the U.S. capital, where he underwent
diagnosis and treatment beginning May 31.
   ``I certainly am not cured. But I am strong. I have the capacity
and the strength to carry out both the medical requisites my
disease demands and my work for the people,'' said Duarte, the
Western Hemisphere' staunchest U.S. ally.
   Duarte, whose five-year term ends June 1, 1989, was leaner than
when he left and his face was somewhat drawn.
   But his step was firm and his embrace appeared strong as he
greeted Rodolfo Castillo Claramount, the vice president and acting
chief executive, and other officials on the tarmac of Ilopango
Airport outside the capital.
   After a brief airport ceremony, he was driven to the
presidential residence to rest. The chemotherapy Duarte is
undergoing for liver cancer has debilitated him somewhat, but he
vowed the illness would not keep him down.
   Doctors have given him between six and 18 months to live.
   Duarte promised to continue working with the military against
leftist guerrillas ``in order to bring peace to my people ... in
that way I will make it to the first of June and hand power over to
the one who is elected by the people.''
   Duarte's governing Christian Democratic Party is in the deepest
crisis of its 28-year history. Each of two bitterly feuding
factions has nominated a presidential candidate.
   The right-wing opposition won municipal and legislative
elections in March. That victory, along with the Christian
Democrats' internal problems, have created the impression that the
right-wing Republican Nationalist Alliance could win the March 1989
presidential election.
   Castillo told a news conference last week that Duarte's work
routine will be established ``according to the evolution of his
disease.''
   The president is to return to Walter Reed Medical Center in
Washington next month for at least one more massive chemotherapy
application. Salvadoran officials have said subsequent treatment
could be carried out in El Salvador.
</TEXT>
