<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First name `Bobs' in 4th graf of 4th item is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop star Michael Jackson was greeted by 800
screaming fans as he arrived at Heathrow Airport to begin his first
British tour.
   As Jackson, 29, was whisked through customs Monday, fans waving
banners saying ``We Love You Michael'' and ``Welcome To London''
strained for a glimpse of the man they had awaited for since early
morning.
   Jackson appeared briefly on a viewing platform, wearing dark
glasses and a ``Sgt. Pepper'' suit in the style of the Beatles.
   He waved back at his fans and said, ``This welcome is truly
wonderful, I love the English people,'' before six security guards
escorted him away.
   Jackson opens his tour Thursday with a concert at London's
Wembley Stadium. He will perform Saturday at a charity concert to
be attended by Prince Charles and his wife, Diana.
   Later this month, Jackson's ``Bad Tour'' _ named for his album
``Bad'' _ will continue in Ireland and Wales before returning to
London in August.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Sinatra, Sid Caesar and
Gregory Peck are among the 200 friends expected to help comedian
Milton Berle celebrate his 80th birthday tonight.
   Said Berle, ``I'm going to miss the All-Star (baseball) game,
but I'm going to have an all-star game of my own.''
   The guest list for the bash at the nightclub La Cage Aux Folles
includes Lucille Ball, Jack Lemmon, Red Buttons, Steve Allen, Danny
Thomas and Don Rickles.
   ``He's really excited about the party,'' Berle's wife, Ruth, who
set it up, said Monday.
   Berle was host of TV's first hit show, ``Texaco Star Theater.''
His vaudevillian antics endeared him to a generation of Americans
and earned him the title ``Mr. Television.''
   Berle opens at Caesar's Palace in Atlantic City, N.J., on Aug. 9
with Danny Thomas and Sid Caesar. He then has performances
scheduled in Las Vegas, Nev., beginning Aug. 24.
   ``He's really 80 years young and his contribution to the world
of comedy will live forever,'' Miss Ball said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television producer Norman Lear and his wife
are the proud new parents of a baby boy, a spokeswoman says.
   Benjamin Davis Lear was born late Sunday, weighing 7 pounds, 2{
ounces, Lear publicist Pam Ruben said Monday.
   The child is Lear's fourth but the first for his wife,
psychologist Lyn Davis, 40. The two were married in September.
   Lear, 65, is best known for creating the hit television series
``All in the Family.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Rooney, appearing at a ceremony
marking the 50th anniversary of the making of the film ``Boys
Town,'' said he wants to make a weekly TV series based on the
famous home for boys.
   Rooney, who played the tough teen-ager Whitey James in the 1938
film, said he would approach Columbia Pictures next year about the
possibility of creating the TV series.
   ``Yours truly is going to be Father Whitey Marsh, the head of
Boys Town,'' he said Monday.
   Rooney appeared Monday with Bobs Watson, who was 7 years old
when he played little Pee Wee in the movie starring Spencer Tracy
as Father Flanagan, founder of Boys Town. Rooney was 18 when the
movie was made.
   Watson, who became a United Methodist minister 25 years ago and
lives in Southern California, said making the movie had a big
impact on his life.
   ``Father Flanagan was one of those men who touched my life
deeply and was one of the reasons why I went into the ministry,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liza Minnelli, once dependent on alcohol and
drugs, now dances and does 200 sit-ups a day to stay in shape.
   ``I've never felt so wonderful in my whole life,'' the
42-year-old singer, dancer and actress says in the August issue of
Ladies' Home Journal. ``I feel younger than I've ever felt.
Carefree.''
   She kicked her chemical dependencies during a stay at the Betty
Ford Center in California.
   ``Chemical dependency is a sad, lonely story that millions of
women share,'' she said. ``The only solution is education. If I can
spare somebody from going through what I went through, I'll gladly
do that.''
   The entertainer said she is cultivating a quiet, reflective side
of her personality.
   ``I'm learning to be a friend to myself,'' she said. ``Once a
day, you say to yourself, `How are you, honey? How are you doing?'
   ``We can't all look like Elizabeth Taylor but we can look like
that inside,'' she said. ``If you get your mind right, you can do
anything.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Society band leader Lester Lanin
will try his hand at movies after a music career that has spanned
nearly 75 years.
   Lanin, who is closing in on 80 but refuses to reveal just how
close, is here this week to film ``Life After Life,'' a Tri-Star
picture starring Cybill Shepherd and Ryan O'Neal.
   Lanin will portray himself in the film, leading his orchestra in
three fox trots and a rock number.
   It's the first time Lanin has agreed to do a movie, although
he's received other offers. ``I feel at this stage of the game I
can go forward. I'm going in for some better things.''
   Lanin has been hired to perform by eight presidents and four
kings and queens.
</TEXT>
