<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Seabrook     07-12 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Seabrook,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Promises To Consider Lawmakers' Opposition To Seabrook
Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has promised to weigh
opposition to a proposed executive order that could help license
the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant by circumventing the
objections of Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   Lawmakers from the all-Republican New Hampshire congressional
delegation, upset over the proposed federal intervention, said they
received the pledge Monday after a White House briefing with Reagan.
   ``We found the president very positive, very sympathetic, very
understanding,'' said Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H. ``It was clear to
all of us that the president was going to very actively consider
our request that this order never be published.''
   Rudman and Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., expressed optimism that
the president may reject the proposal.
   ``I am very hopeful that this visit has an effect on the
president in convincing him that the process was working (and) the
federal government need not become involved at this time,'' Rudman
told reporters outside the White House.
   Humphrey added, ``The president didn't say yes or no, but I came
away more encouraged about our prospects of blocking this order
than frankly I had expected to.''
   But Rep. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who said before the briefing that
he thought it would be extremely difficult to derail the proposal,
said afterwards that he felt no more optimistic about the
lawmakers' chances.
   ``He gave us no reading at all as to what his decision would
be,'' said Gregg, noting that Reagan reiterated his strong support
for atomic power and expressed concern over state governments'
ability to block reactor licenses.
   ``The president has not made a decision,'' said Rep. Robert
Smith, R-N.H. ``He will weigh our evidence and our advice. That's
the best we can hope for at this time.''
   The four lawmakers, loyal and long-time allies of the Reagan
administration, have expressed support for plant licensing as long
as federal regulators determine that the plant and evacuation plan
are safe.
   Licensing for the Seabrook reactor has been stalled largely by
the refusal of Dukakis to submit evacuation plans for the six
Massachusetts communities that fall within the plant's 10-mile
emergency zone.
   The proposed executive order would give the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, which has served a strictly advisory role in
atomic safety issues, the power to design and implement evacuation
plans when local governments refuse to do so.
   The four were infuriated last month when they learned of the
proposal through plant opponents, who discovered a draft and leaked
it to reporters.
   Reagan told the delegation that he had not seen any draft of the
proposal, which sources said was initiated by the Energy
Department, pushed by four senators and approved unanimously by the
president's Domestic Policy Council.
   Dukakis and other plant opponents have said it is impossible to
evacuate the area quickly and safely because of narrow rural roads
and a large summertime population.
</TEXT>
