<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlueFlu 2ndLd-Writethru a0689 07-12 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blue Flu, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0689,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Police Move In As City Cops Call In Sick; `Flu' Cured After
24 Hours</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with late-evening shift back to
normal, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `Woodfork said...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State troopers patrolled city streets Monday
to make up for an apparent sick-out by more than 300 officers upset
over low wages and the lack of a labor contract. The job action
ended at late evening.
   Police Chief Warren Woodfork said city streets were probably
safer than usual because of the 60 troopers in the city. There were
143 officers and troopers on patrol, compared with a usual 83,
police said.
   Officers began straggling back to work for the start of their
late-evening shift, said police department spokesman John Bryson.
``They have returned to work. We're back up to normal strength,''
he said.
   Woodfork said his department could continue to maintain security
in the city of 500,000 even if police union members carry out a
threat to stop work during next month's Republican National
Convention.
   About 130 troopers already are scheduled to be in New Orleans
next month during the GOP convention.
   The sick-out began Sunday night and Woodfork said he didn't know
how long it would last, although he heard it was to end Monday
night.
   Leaders of the Police Association of New Orleans have long been
pressuring Mayor Sidney Barthelemy to enter the city's first
collective bargaining agreement with the union. The union claims a
membership of about 900 of the 1,100-member police force.
   Barthelemy, who was out of town Monday and unavailable for
comment, has refused to recognize PANO as a collective bargaining
group.
   Union President Ron Cannatella did not return telephone calls
and there was no word from the union on whether it had called for
the sick-out.
   Woodfork said he had no immediate plans to discipline officers
who called in sick Sunday or Monday.
   ``I would just ask the officers who are out sick to search their
consciences. Don't hold the city of New Orleans hostage,'' he said.
</TEXT>
