<HEAD>With PM-Convention-Networks Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Networks Plan Prime-Time Convention Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three major networks plan to carry live
coverage of the Democratic National Convention for approximately
two hours of prime time each night, Monday through Thursday.
   All three networks plan coverage from 9-11 p.m. EDT each night.
CBS will start at 8 p.m. on Thursday.
   ABC's coverage will be anchored by Peter Jennings with
commentary by David Brinkley. ``World News Tonight'' and ``Good
Morning America'' will originate from Atlanta during the
convention. ``Nightline'' will stay home in Washington, but will
include reports on the convention as news merits.
   Walter Cronkite, who is under contract negotiations with CBS,
nevertheless returns for his 19th convention serving as network
commentator. Dan Rather will anchor the convention coverage. ``CBS
Evening News'' will originate from Atlanta, as will ``CBS This
Morning.''
   NBC's Tom Brokaw will anchor his network's coverage with John
Chancellor providing commentary. ``NBC Nightly News'' and the
``Today'' show will originate from Atlanta.
   C-SPAN will carry each session of the convention live without
commentary each night.
   Cable News Network will have updates throughout the day, then
carry complete live coverage of the convention session each night,
followed by a half-hour wrapup, then ``Crossfire'' and ``Inside
Politics '88.'' Convention highlights will be shown 4-6 a.m. EDT.
   PBS' ``MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' will also report from the
convention.
   In the battle of the political columnist-commentators, ABC
landed columnists George F. Will and Tom Wicker. CBS snagged Kevin
Phillips and Roger Rosenblatt.
   CNN's lineup of experts include columnists Patrick Buchanan, Tom
Braden, Rowland Evans, Mark Green and Robert Novak. PBS has U.S.
News & World Report Editor David Gergen and Washington Post
columnist Mark Shields.
   NBC says it is depending on its own Chancellor, Brokaw and
political reporter Ken Bode, though political consultants Bob
Squier and John Sears will offer commentary on ``Today.''
