<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InsiderTrading-Sturm 1stLd-Writethru a0761 07-12 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading-Sturm, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0761,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Omaha Executive Settles Insider Trading Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The commission...', with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Sturm statement and to delete extraneous word `commission';
picking up 10th graf, `But SEC...'. A version moved on financial
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Omaha, Neb., business executive accused of
passing inside information to a friend settled civil charges Monday
by agreeing to pay the government more than $282,000.
   Donald L. Sturm, 56, signed a consent agreement without
admitting guilt, settling a civil insider trading lawsuit filed by
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The commission accused Sturm, identified as the owner of a bank
and vice chairman of Omaha-based Peter Kiewit Sons Inc., a
construction and manufacturing company, of getting information from
a relative about the corporate takeover of Aviation Group Inc., a
North Carolina air cargo service.
   Sturm allegedly passed the information to a friend who bought
30,000 shares of stock with money loaned by Sturm and made $128,412
in trading profits, the SEC contended.
   The SEC did not allege that Sturm made any money on the
transaction or had used the friend merely as a middleman to shield
stock purchases.
   ``It's as if Sturm actually made the profits and gave it to the
friend, although he (Sturm) didn't buy the stock,'' said Jerry A.
Isenberg, an SEC official in Washington.
   Isenberg said Sturm _ not his friend _ was charged because Sturm
``was involved in initiating the trade. He financed the trade.''
   Sturm's attorney, Max Gitter, was out of town and unavailable
for comment.
   However, The New York Times said in Tuesday's editions that
Sturm issued a statement saying he did not pass on or possess
material non-public information.
   ``Nor did I know that merger negotiations were under way,'' the
statement read. ``After months of efforts to convince the SEC that
it has drawn wrong conclusions, and knowing that I did nothing
wrong, I have nonetheless chosen to settle this matter rather than
to dispute it any further.''
   The SEC did not identify Sturm's bank, the relative who tipped
him off or the relative's investment bank.
   But SEC filings at the time of the acquisition identified Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. as the investment banking firm.
   Besides the $154,085 in alleged illegal profits plus interest,
Sturm agreed to pay the government $128,412 in penalties for a
total of $282,497.
</TEXT>
