<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EpiscopalConvention Bjt   07-12 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Episcopal Convention, Bjt,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Closes Without Resolving Homosexual Ordination Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopal Church leaders have closed their 69th
General Convention without adopting a proposal that could have
encouraged the ordination of homosexuals.
   A resolution Monday expanding ``access to the selection process
for ordination'' for all persons, including homosexuals _ but
refusing to recognize a right to ordination for all _ fell one vote
short of passage in the church's House of Deputies.
   The 900-member House of Deputies, divided between lay and
clerical church members, and the 200-member House of Bishops
establish policy for the 2.7 million-member church, whose 10-day
convention ended Monday. The conventions are held every three years.
   Delegates considered almost 500 resolutions at the convention,
which opened July 2. But the question of ordaining gay priests
dominated the final days of the convention.
   Current church law says candidates for ordination must be at
least 21 years of age and pass prescribed medical, psychological
and academic tests. But leaders of some of the church's 118
dioceses in the United States have ordained homosexual priests
without running afoul of Episcopal canon law.
   In 1979, the 66th General Convention approved a resolution
stating in part, ``We believe it is not appropriate for this church
to ordain a practicing homosexual.''
   That resolution, however, is not a part of canon law, which
draws a distinction between homosexual activity, which it says is
sinful, and homosexual orientation, which it says is not.
   Church leaders on both sides of the homosexual debate agreed
that Monday's vote left the issue unresolved.
   Canon law was left intact and thus maintained discretion within
the dioceses as to consideration of homosexual candidates for the
priesthood, said the Rt. Rev. Paul Moore Jr., bishop of New York
City.
   ``I'm not unhappy that it didn't pass,'' said the Rt. Rev.
George N. Hunt, bishop of Rhode Island. ``We are not of one mind on
the subject. Until we are, we should be cautious of passing
anything until we can speak with authority.''
   ``I was disappointed that, to the portion of people who tend to
see themselves as being disenfranchised from the church, (approval
of the resolution) would have given some pastoral concern,'' said
the Rt. Rev. O'Kelley Whitaker, bishop of central New York.
   But, Whitaker added: ``It doesn't cripple the church.
Homosexuals are involved in the ordination process in many dioceses
already. It is happening anyway.''
   Confusion over parliamentary procedure marred the homosexual
debate, church leaders said.
   ``I've been a bishop a long time ... and I have never heard as
many parliamentary procedure tactics as I have seen in this house
this week,'' Presiding Bishop Edward Browning told the House of
Bishops.
   Also Monday, both houses approved a resolution opposing
``abortion as a means of birth control, family planning or sex
selection.''
   The resolution in its final form acknowledged that women in the
United States have a legal right to medically safe abortion. But it
also deleted a passage expressing the church's opposition to any
government action barring a woman's right to abortion.
   Delegates on Monday also approved a resolution extending for two
years the experimental use oelief and practice, curtail masculine
references to God as much as possible. The church's Liturgical
Commission later will evaluate the experiment.
   Among the final resolutions approved was one calling frrowly
rejected the resolution Sunday, when some delegates claimed the
boycott would hurt U.S. businesses. But the deputies reversed their
vote Monday to express solidarity with Anglican Archbishop Desmond
Tutu of South Africa, who has promoted the boycott as a means of
protesting racial segregation in that nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
