<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Advance, Dollar Eases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market's main barometer broke past the
28,000-point level in active trading Tuesday, while the dollar lost
ground against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 68.91-point
winner Monday, gained another 113.85 points, or 0.40 percent, for a
28,099.84 total by the end of trading.
   The dollar opened at 132.90 yen but fell slightly in morning
trading. It retreated further in afternoon dealings before closing
the day at 132.70 yen, down 0.63 yen from Monday's 133.33 yen. It
traded between 132.60 yen and 133.08 yen during the day.
   An exchange dealer at the Bank of Tokyo said there was no major
market-affecting news behind the dollar's decline, which followed
an overnight fall in New York.
   The dollar closed at 133.07 yen Monday in New York, down from
last Friday's closing of 133.29 yen.
   The dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dollar
would trade in a narrow range against other major currencies until
the announcement of U.S. trade figures for May, slated for Friday.
   He said many market players were predicting the U.S. monthly
trade deficit for May could widen.
</TEXT>
