<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Members Of Flight Crew To Be Protected Witnesses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lede to delete extraneous word `a'; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, The two xxx.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former Royal Jordanian airlines employees
are in federal protective custody to testify against a suspected
Lebanese terrorist charged with leading the hijacking of their
plane in 1985.
   The two unidentified members of the jetliner's flight crew
entered the federal witness protection program after agreeing to
testify at the trial of Fawaz Younis, a prosecutor said Monday at a
pre-trial hearing in the case.
   Younis, a former member of Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia, is
charged with leading a group of five men who stormed the Boeing 727
with AK-47 assult rifles at Beirut International Airport on June
11, 1985.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ramsey Johnson said the former airline
employees were uprooted from their homes in the Middle East and
entered the U.S. protection program after ``their decision to
testify in the trial.''
   Johnson said FBI agents are still trying to locate an
Arab-speaking passenger who identified Younis at a court-ordered
lineup last March. ``We believe he is an excellent witness,'' the
prosecutor told U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker.
   Younis was arrested last September after he and a friend, Jamal
Hamdan, went aboard an FBI-chartered yacht in international waters
off the coast of Cyprus.
   Hamdan, who cooperated with the FBI in luring Younis to the
yacht with the prospect of making a drug deal, is also in
protective custody, Johnson said.
   No date has been set for the trial.
   A federal appeals court is considering whether statements Younis
made to FBI agents during four days of interrogation aboard a Navy
ship in the Mediterranean can be admitted into evidence.
   Prosecutors appealed Parker's ruling in February that Younis'
confession was illegally obtained because he didn't understand his
right to remain silent.
   Parker ruled that Younis was unable to make a responsible
decision because of his unfamiliarity with the U.S. legal system.
The judge also noted that during his interrogation, Younis was
seasick and suffered pain in his wrists, which were broken when two
FBI agents slammed him to the deck of the yacht.
   At Monday's hearing, Parker said he had found a classified
document that contradicted a previous assertion by Johnson that the
FBI had never considered placing an attorney aboard the ship to
advise Younis.
   Johnson had told the judge in February that the idea ``just
didn't come up.''
   Parker, indicating the secret document he had examined
contradicted that answer, told Johnson: ``You are charged with the
knowledge of the information contained'' in the secret documents
turned over to the court.
   On June 30, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ordered
Parker to conduct a hearing on whether to admit the document into
evidence.
   The appeals court said the document ``raises questions that go
directly'' to Younis' claim he was denied a right to counsel during
his interrogation.
   The judge gave Johnson 48 hours to consult government agencies
about declassifying the document and scheduled a hearing for next
Monday.
</TEXT>
