<HEAD>Democrats Unveil Computerized Voting System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computerized system developed in Atlanta will
be used to help speed balloting at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk said Monday he
expects the system ``will probably save 40 to 45 minutes a vote.''
   The Integrated Voting and Information System, or IVIS, was
developed by AT&T's data systems group and Bell Labs specifically
for the convention, said Barry Johnson of AT&T media relations. It
will be used for ballots on issues.
   The nominating procedure for presidential and vice presidential
candidates will still involve the traditional voice roll call vote,
Kirk said.
