<HEAD>Dukakis Leads Bush In Washington Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis leads Republican George
Bush by 11 percentage points, 47 percent to 36 percent, in a new
poll of Washington state voters published by The Seattle Times.
   The telephone poll of 503 voters in the state indicated a large
portion of each candidates' support is soft, however.
   Voting ``definitely Dukakis'' were 26 percent, while 21 percent
said they would ``probably'' vote for him. Those ``definitely'' for
Vice President Bush numbered 19 percent, while 17 were ``probably''
for him. Seventeen percent were undecided.
   The poll was conducted last week by Elway Research for The
Seattle Times, which reported the results Monday. The margin of
error was plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   The poll indicated little difference in the results when Dukakis
was matched with several potential running mates, except that the
likely Democratic nominee lost ground when paired with Jesse
Jackson, who finished second overall in delegates.
   Jackson's presence on a Democratic ticket pushed Bush slightly
ahead of Dukakis, 44-41 percent.
</TEXT>
