<1ST_LINE>u a BC-HelicopterEscape     07-12 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Helicopter Escape,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Third Convict In Helicopter Escape Captured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities Tuesday captured a
convicted murderer who escaped from a state prison yard with two
other inmates in a helicopter that lifted off in a hail of gunfire
the day before, a state police official said.
   Daniel Mahoney, 30, was captured shortly before 1 a.m., said
state police Sgt. John Balderston.
   A Corrections officer spotted Mahoney's tracks around 7:30 p.m.,
and called in a canine unit, Balderston said. Officers followed the
tracks along the Rio Grande to a bridge near Los Lunas about 20
miles south of here.
   The other two inmates were captured Monday in a dramatic aerial
chase along the Rio Grande Valley that lasted nearly two hours,
officials said. Also arrested was a woman authorities believe is
Mahoney's girlfriend.
   The pilot, who flew the same helicopter in the movie ``Rambo
III,'' was being held at the Santa Fe County Jail overnight while
authorities checked out his story that he had been hijacked,
officials said.
   The copter nearly rammed a pursuing U.S. Customs helicopter and
tried to force a police helicopter into a crane.
   ``We both hung with him. We knew he had to set down because he
was running low on fuel,'' said Maj. John Denko, pilot of the state
police chopper.
   About 100 prisoners were in the exercise yard at the
Penitentiary of New Mexico near Santa Fe when the Aerospatiale
Gazelle helicopter, landed around 9:50 a.m. and picked up the three
inmates.
   Guards in two towers opened fire as the chopper took off, said
Don Caviness, a spokesman for the New Mexico Corrections Department.
   The copter flew first to a small airport at Los Lunas, 80 miles
away. Waiting police wounded and captured one inmate in a
gunbattle. The woman also was taken into custody, while Mahoney
escaped on foot.
   The copter then took off again, leading the customs and police
helicopters on a 20-mile chase to Albuquerque International Airport
before finally landing as its gasoline supply dwindled. The other
inmate was captured there.
   Mahoney was serving life plus 60 years for second-degree murder
and armed robbery in Florida.
   Randy Mack Lackey, 36, of Curry County, N.M., serving a
nine-year sentence for larceny, was wounded in the shoulder and
captured at the Los Lunas airport. Francis Preston Mitchell, 26,
serving life for first-degree murder in Utah, was captured at the
Albuquerque airport. Beverly Shoemaker of Santa Fe was also taken
into custody at Los Lunas.
   Mahoney and Mitchell were being held under an interstate compact
that provides for prisoner exchanges.
   Roadblocks were thrown up from Albuquerque to Socorro as
authorities pressed the search for Mahoney. Police using dogs and
officers on horseback and in airplanes also joined in.
   ``We understand he may be armed,'' a dispatcher at the Valencia
County Sheriff's Department who asked her name not be used said
late Monday. ``He is considered very dangerous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
