<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea     07-12 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Rejects South Korean Call For Improved Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has rejected as nothing new the
proposals of President Roh Tae-woo of South Korea for improving
relations between the two nations, the north's official news agency
said today.
   Roh on Thursday unveiled a plan to ease his nation's bitter
confrontation with the communist north and pave the way for
peaceful reunification of the divided peninsula.
   ``This is nothing new and is not worth examination,'' the Korean
Central News Agency quoted a statement issued by North Korea's
Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland as
saying.
   The news agency, monitored in Tokyo, quoted the statement as
saying that if the South Korean authorities ``truly want dialogue
and reunification, they should respond, though a bit late, to our
proposal for convocation of a north-south joint conference.''
   In the July 7 special declaration, Roh called for broad trade,
humanitarian, cultural and political contacts with the north.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since their land was
divided at the end of World War II in 1945. They fought the Korean
war in 1950-53.
   Talks between the two Koreas have been held intermittantly since
the early 1970s. They opened new talks in the early 1980s, but
North Korea suspended all dialogue in 1986 to protest joint
U.S.-South Korea military exercises.
   In Seoul, the Yonhap News Agency reported today that South Korea
was considering encouraging the United States and other Western
nations to open trade links with the north to help ease tensions.
   The agency, quoting an unidentified official, said the
government will make efforts to induce American and Western
companies to establish contacts with the north on a gradual basis.
No official confirmation was available on the report.
</TEXT>
