<DOCNO> AP880712-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nicaragua-Contra-Reax     07-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Contra-Reax,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Leaders Say Sandinistas Showing `True Colors'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders say there is little hope for a
peaceful move toward democracy in Nicaragua, where the Sandinista
government has expelled U.S. diplomats, quelled dissent and shut a
newspaper and radio station.
   ``They had been acting like a chameleon for months and months.
Now they have shown their true colors,'' Adolfo Calero, a director
of the U.S.-backed rebels, said by telephone today from Washington.
   ``We just hope that the United States, Europe and the free world
once and for all accept that they are totalitarian and never had
any interest in democracy,'' he said.
   The Sandinista government on Monday gave the U.S. ambassador and
seven other embassy officials three days to leave, accusing them of
state terrorism.
   Opposition newspaper La Prensa and Roman Catholic radio station
Radio Catolica were ordered shut down. The moves came a day after
police clashed with thousands of demonstrators at an
anti-Sandinista rally 40 miles outside Managua.
   Calero said such actions fly in the face of a peace agreement
signed three months ago with the Contras in which the government
pledged a series of steps aimed at satisfying the rebels' demands
for ``democratization.''
   ``At this point, I can't see any further negotiations for a
peaceful transition to freedom in Nicaragua,'' Calero said. ``The
Sandinistas have made it clear they're just not interested.''
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, another Contra director based in Miami,
said the rebels have been negotiating in good faith with the
Sandinistas, but that continued repression inside Nicaragua would
leave them little choice but to return to a full-scale armed
struggle.
   If that happens, Calero said in a telephone interview, much of
the blame should be placed on Congress, which in February rejected
President Reagan's request for additional military aid to the
Contras.
   ``Those who were clamoring to give peace a chance in February
defeated their own purpose by denying us aid,'' Calero said. ``They
took away the strength the resistance needed to keep the
Sandinistas at the negotiating table. It doesn't look like we're
going to be doing much talking now.''
</TEXT>
