<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0505EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tibet     07-12 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Free 52 Arrested In Pro-Independence Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Tibet have freed 52 people, some of
them Buddhist monks, arrested for taking part in pro-independence
riots held in March in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, a government
newspaper said today.
   The Guangming Daily said Tibetan authorities decided to show
leniency because the protesters expressed regret and some aided
police investigations by exposing instigators of the March 5 riots.
   The report did not say how many people remained in custody. It
quoted Yuan Chenquan, deputy chief of the Lhasa Public Security
Bureau, as saying most participants in the riots were ``acting
blindly'' and only ``a handful of criminals need further
investigation.''
   The Panchen Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's second-highest official and
a supporter of Chinese policy in Tibet, said in April that 200
people were detained following the riots, which erupted at the end
of a Buddhist religious festival. He said most would be released
after questioning.
   The government has only reported the arrests of four people, in
the slaying of a policeman. The Panchen Lama said five people died
in the violence, while Western travelers put the death toll at
about 24.
   The newspaper said the 52 people released included young monks
from three major monasteries in the Lhasa area and students from
the Tibet Buddhism College. It said that while in custody they
studied the Chinese constitution, criminal law and relevant
regulations.
   The riot began when monks at a prayer festival shouted
pro-independence slogans and threw stones at police. Thousands of
Tibetans joined in and clashed with police throughout the city.
   In September and October, similar rioting left at least 14 dead.
   The rioters, followers of exiled spiritual leader the Dalai
Lama, claim China is illegally occupying the mountain region and
demand an independent Tibet.
   China says Tibet has been an inalienable part of the country for
700 years. Communist troops entered Tibet in 1950 and in 1959 put
down an uprising during which the Dalai Lama and thousands of his
followers fled to exile in India.
   Animosity between Tibetans and non-Tibetan Chinese reached a
peak during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, when radical leftists
suppressed Tibetan religion, persecuted worshippers and destroyed
Buddhist temples.
   Since 1976, the Beijing government has guaranteed freedom of
religion and rebuilt some damaged temples, but tensions have
remained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
