<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CBS-TimesPoll 1stLd-Writethru a0449 07-12 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS-Times Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hangs Onto His Lead But Unfavorable Rating Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lede to clarify; picks up 2nd graf pvs, The CBS xxx.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis held a lead over
Republican George Bush in a national poll, but the likely
Democratic nominee's unfavorable rating was also rising.
   The CBS News-New York Times poll found Dukakis ahead 47 percent
to 39 percent among the random sample of 947 registered voters
surveyed by telephone last week. The margin of error was plus or
minus three percentage points.
   The lead for the Massachusetts governor was 8 points. In May the
same poll found a 10-point Dukakis lead, 49-39.
   Twenty-eight percent of respondents in the new poll expressed a
favorable view of Dukakis, down from 38 percent in May. Twenty-one
percent expressed an unfavorable view, up from 14 percent. Many
still had no opinion.
   Bush, however, did not benefit from the movement in Dukakis'
rating. The all-but-certain Republican nominee's own favorable
rating was 26 percent, down from 33 percent, and his unfavorable
rating was 31, about the same as his 35 percent in May.
   While voters were uneasy about Dukakis' ability to handle an
international crisis, they expressed similar reservations about
Bush. Thirty-six percent said they would be confident in Bush in a
crisis and 50 percent said they would be uneasy. For Dukakis it was
30 percent confident, 49 percent uneasy.
   Similarly, both men received poor ratings on crime. Twenty
percent said Dukakis was tough enough on crime and 36 percent said
he was not; 23 percent said Bush was tough enough and 49 percent
said he was not.
   On the campaign itself, more respondents thought Bush was
attacking Dukakis than thought Dukakis was going after Bush.
Thirty-five percent said Bush was spending more of his time
explaining his program while 32 percent said he was spending more
time attacking Dukakis; for Dukakis, 50 percent thought he was
mostly explaining and 23 percent said he was attacking Bush.
   Finally, 60 percent said they thought the candidates meant it
when they promised not to raise taxes, but believed the winner
probably will have to raise taxes anyway. Another 32 percent said
the candidates did not mean it when they promised not to increase
taxes.
   The Dukakis lead in the new CBS-Times poll falls between the
results of polls done last month. A Gallup poll late in June found
a 5-point lead for Dukakis, down from a 14-point lead in a Gallup
poll in early June, and an ABC News-Money Magazine poll in late
June had it at 45-42, essentially a dead heat. However, in mid-June
Dukakis led by 12 points in a Washington Post poll and by 15 points
in an NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
