<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybe the naked truth is that
politicians in Alabama don't care about the nudist vote. Or maybe
they just don't dare to court it.
   Bob Truett, owner of Gymno-Vita Park, a nudist club in St. Clair
County, invited state Democratic and Republican party officials to
speak to his group Sunday.
   State Republicans declined the invitation outright. Instead they
sent campaign literature that arrived late.
   State Democratic Party Executive Director Al LaPierre agreed to
speak _ wearing clothes if he wanted to _ Truett said.
   But LaPierre apparently couldn't bear to show up.
   ``People were standing around the pool waiting for him and he
never showed up,'' Truett said.
   Truett said LaPierre expressed no reservations Thursday when
Truett called to confirm his appearance.
   LaPierre could not be reached for comment.
   Truett said politicians shouldn't ignore his non-partisan club.
After all, 40 to 50 people turned out to hear LaPierre, he said.
   ``There are thousands of nudists across the country,'' Truett
said. ``And many of them vote.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanted: good homes for $10,000 worth of
shampoo, hair conditioner and bath gel in 97,900 little packets.
   The Fairmont Hotel is getting rid of those packets that grace
many hotel bathrooms as part of its preparations for the Republican
National Convention.
   ``We replaced them ... with superior plastic bottles,'' said
hotel spokesman John De Mers. ``What makes them superior, of
course, is you don't have to rip them open with your teeth and get
shampoo in your mouth. And you can get two or three shampoos out of
one bottle. Plus people love to take them home as souvenirs.''
   De Mers had two questions when the hotel chain's San Francisco
headquarters ordered him to get rid of the packets: how many were
there, and who should they go to?
   It took time to answer the first question.
   ``I got someone to lead me to the shampoo and started counting.
And I counted and I counted and I counted,'' De Mers said Monday.
   It turned out there were 38,500 packets of shampoo, 54,900 of
hair conditioner and 4,500 of bath gel.
   There still was the question of who should get them.
   ``You can give food to the foodless and homes to the homeless,
but who do you give shampoo to?'' he asked.
   So the hotel is holding a Send Us The Suds contest, with Aug. 15
_ the day the Republican National Convention gavels down in the
Superdome _ as the deadline for two-page written entries explaining
how much shampoo, conditioner or bath gel is wanted, and what it's
wanted for.
   ``I would have to say that the more unexpected the reason, the
better,'' said De Mers. ``We're looking purposely for needs that we
can't possibly anticipate. People shouldn't stop entering if they
have a fairly strange reason they need the shampoo. It may just
make them a winner.''
</TEXT>
