<DOCNO> AP880712-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Airliner     07-12 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Airliner,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Meeting On Downing Of Iranian Jetliner Delayed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Security Council debate on the U.S.
missile attack on a Iranian passenger jet has been postponed until
Thursday, officials said.
   Diplomatic sources familiar with council procedures said council
President Paulo Nogueira-Batista of Brazil delayed the meeting
originally scheduled for today after consultations with U.S.
Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, Iran's U.N. ambassador, Mohammad
Ja'afar Mahallati, and members of the council.
   The 15-member Security Council was preparing to consider an
Iranian declaration condemning the United States for shooting down
the plane in the Persian Gulf on July 3. Iran said all 290 people
aboard died.
   The United States, Britain and France are expected to use their
veto power as permanent council members to stop any censure
resolution or any demand that the U.S. fleet leave the gulf.
   The sources said Iran had been unable to gain a council majority
to condemn the downing of the jetliner and it would present a
statement, to be followed by a debate, without submitting a
resolution.
   Washington says the USS Vincennes shot down the plane by
accident, believing the jetliner was an attacking warplane.
   The decision to delay the council meeting was made late Monday.
   Earlier Monday, the U.S. government announced an offer of
voluntary compensation to families of victims, but not to the
Iranian government.
   Mahallati, when asked about the U.S. government announcement,
said ``reparation is not sufficient, definitely, because the root
cause of this tragedy and similar tragedies should be removed from
the Persian Gulf.
   ``And it cannot be anything less than withdrawal of U.S. forces
from the Persian Gulf.''
   Requesting the council debate is a turnabout for Iran, which has
boycotted council sessions for years because it claims the council
bows to pressure from Washington and is biased against Iran in the
8-year-old war with Iraq. Iran wants America condemned for murder
in the airliner incident.
   Western diplomats said the United States is expected to argue
that the war and Iran's refusal to accept a truce are at the root
of the problem.
   The United States has been urging the council to impose an arms
embargo on Iran to compel it to accept a cease-fire called for in a
resolution the council passed unanimously on Jul 20, 1987.
   Iraq has agreed to accept a cease-fire, but Iran demands that
Iraq be branded the aggressor before a truce takes effect.
   Nations now on the council are the permanent members _ the
United States, Britain, China, France and Soviet Union _ and
Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Japan, Nepal, Senegal, West
Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
