<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     07-12 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Does Not Expect Flight Delay From Damaged Test Rockey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA officials said they don't expect
damage to a test booster will delay the tentatively scheduled
September launch of the first space shuttle since the 1986
Challenger disaster.
   The accident will, however, postpone the final test-firing of
Morton Thiokol's redesigned booster from July 25 until the end of
August, officials said.
   The booster was damaged Saturday when a worker testing one of
the motor's three field joints inadvertently switched
pressurization lines and damaged insulation that helps contain
superheated gasses during flight, Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky
Raab said Monday.
   However, Edward S. Campion of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, said, ``We do not expect it to affect the STS-26
launch schedule.''
   STS-26 is the designation for the first flight of a space
shuttle since the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion destroyed Challenger and
killed seven crew members.
   An 11-member panel from the National Academy of Sciences will
meet next week to evaluate the mishap.
   NASA spokesman David Garrett said the test motor will have to be
partially disassembled for evaluation and possible repairs.
   ``After the rocket is opened up at the joint, we'll have
something more to say,'' said NASA spokesman Ken Atchison in
Washington. ``At this point, our best estimate is that we don't
anticipate a delay.''
   The damaged test rocket already contained severe intentional
flaws designed to determine whether the redesigned joints can
withstand the heat and pressure of launch even in the event of some
failures.
   The test rocket incorporates a new design created after
Challenger exploded after its launch from the Kennedy Space Center.
   The explosion was blamed on a faulty booster joint that allowed
a plume of superhot gas to burn through an O-ring, triggering the
blast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
