<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Soviets-WrappedCheese     07-12 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviets-Wrapped Cheese,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Ranking Soviet Military Official Visits West Point</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Formulating the strategies of a vast
army may come as second nature to Soviet generals, but one thing
seems to baffle them: single-sliced, plastic-wrapped American
cheese.
   Col. Gen. Dmitri A. Grinkevich, the chief of staff of Soviet
ground forces, paid a visit Monday to the U.S. Military Academy as
part of a Soviet delegation that has been visiting American
military installations.
   Grinkevich, one of the highest-ranking officers in the Soviet
army, is the highest-ranking Soviet officer ever to visit West
Point, according to Maj. Bruce Bell, spokesman for the academy.
   During his four-hour visit, Grinkevich had lunch with about
1,600 cadets in Washington Hall, West Point's mess hall. He sat at
a table with five cadets, several of whom spoke Russian, Bell said.
   When faced with a single slice of cheese wrapped in plastic, the
Soviet military man apparently had trouble, Bell said. Cadet
Jeannie Koch, who was sitting at the same table, had to show him
how to unwrap it.
   ``It appeared as if he had never had to unwrap singularly
wrapped cheese before,'' Bell said.
   Grinkevich is part of the delegation headed by Soviet Chief of
Staff Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev that ended a weeklong U.S. tour
Monday.
   Bell said the ``Soviet general seemed very warm and engaging but
he didn't make make any comments whatsoever'' about West Point or
the cadets.
</TEXT>
