<2ND_LINE>PM-NU-Blue Flu,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Sick-Out Ends After 24 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour ``blue flu'' epidemic that idled
nearly a fourth of the city's 1,350 police officers was over today
with the city still refusing to recognize a police union for
collective bargaining.
   Police Chief Warren Woodfork said streets were probably safer
than usual because of 60 state troopers who were brought into the
city for patrol duty.
   Although the Police Association of New Orleans disavowed any
connection with the absences, the union's president said job stress
was a logical extension of the city's refusal to bargain with the
group and raise salaries.
   Officers began straggling back to work for the start of their
late-evening shift Monday, said police department spokesman John
Bryson. ``They have returned to work. We're back up to normal
strength,'' he said.
   He said the 334 officers who called in sick beginning late
Sunday represented 24.7 percent of the department's 1,350 or so
employees.
   Woodfork said his department could continue to maintain security
in the city of 500,000 even if police union members carry out a
threat to stop work during next month's Republican National
Convention.
   Woodfork said there were no immediate plans to discipline
officers who called in sick. Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, who has
refused to recognize the union, was out of town Monday and could
not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
