<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0839EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ArmsTalks 1stLd-Writethru   07-12 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0503,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks On Cutting Long-Range Nuclear Stocks Resume</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for grafs 6-7 pvs, ``Kampelman and ...'' to
UPDATE with opening session over; pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Kampelman,
chief ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superpower talks on reducing long-range nuclear
arsenals resumed today after a seven-week break with both sides
identifying at least two major hurdles toward completing a draft
treaty.
   Before the opening session, U.S. chief delegate Max Kampelman
reaffirmed Washington's stand that a pact that would halve each
side's stockpile ``should not be held hostage'' to limits sought by
Moscow on U.S. plans for a large-scale space defense against
ballistic missiles.
   The other chief source of disagreement centers on Soviet
insistence on limiting sea-launched cruise missiles.
   Asked whether negotiators see a possible fifth superpower summit
or the end of Ronald Reagan's presidency in January as a deadline,
Kampelman told reporters talks will ``continue no matter who is
president and no matter who the leader of the Soviet Union is.
   ``I don't think important issues should be governed by the
calendar,'' he said. ``If it takes longer, fine. If it takes
shorter, fine.''
   Kampelman, chief Soviet negotiator Alexei Obukhov and their full
delegations met for about two hours at the U.S. mission to launch
the 10th round of Geneva talks since March 1985. The session then
recessed for the day, and no date was immediately announced for the
next session.
   The ninth round of talks recessed before the May 29-June 2
summit between Reagan and Mikhail S. Gorbachev, which produced only
slight progress toward a long-range nuclear forces treaty.
   The superpower leaders then ordered negotiators to continue
``energetically and purposefully.'' No end date has been announced
for this new round.
   The chief negotiators hinted that a breakthrough is not in sight.
   ``Don't look for drama,'' Kampelman told reporters Monday.
``We're at a stage now where hard work is required rather than
drama.''
   Obukhov warned after his arrival Sunday: ``We do not want to
lose momentum.''
   While both negotiators said the talks have come ``a long way,''
Kampelman also noted, ``Much that is important still remains to be
solved.''
   He said a draft could still be completed under the Reagan
administration and voiced hope the new round will, ``at the very
least, significantly narrow the differences between us.''
   Both sides agree that the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction
Treaty should cut each side's stocks over seven years to an overall
limit of 6,000 nuclear warheads and 1,600 launchers, such as heavy
bombers and land-based intercontinental missiles.
   Some details of monitoring compliance with a future pact are
also settled, but both negotiators stressed more work was needed.
   Obukhov told reporters progress ``now depends primarily'' on
resolving disputes over U.S. plans to develop a space-based missile
defense system, called the Strategic Defense Initiative, and on
limiting the deployment of long-range sea-launched cruise missiles.
   ``We reject the Soviet attempts to use these negotiations to
have us end our Strategic Defense Initiative,'' Kampelman said.
   For sea-launched cruise missiles, the Soviets have proposed
limits and called for anti-cheating measures including inspections
of warships.
   Washington has balked, saying the weapons cannot be reliably
detected.
   On Monday, U.S. negotiator Steven Hanmer called the Soviet
verification proposals ``totally impractical'' and said current
prospects for resolving the issue are dim.
   Last December, Reagan and Gorbachev signed a treaty scrapping
all intermediate-range nuclear forces. Both countries ratified that
pact shortly before the Moscow summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
