<HEAD>Friend of Pilot Says He Would Never Make Escape Attempt
Voluntarily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``Bella told xxx, to CORRECT spelling of
wife's name, Carrol sted Carol</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Helicopter Escape, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of the helicopter that plucked
three convicts out of a New Mexico prison flew the same aircraft in
the movie ``Rambo III,'' a friend says.
   Charles Bella, 43, of El Paso, who told authorities his
Aerospatiale Gazelle was hijacked before Monday's failed escape
attempt, would not have voluntarily helped the inmates, said Tony
Mobley.
   ``Anybody who knows him knows how hard he works,'' said Mobley,
who has known Bella 16 years. ``No one would believe he would risk
everything he's worked for for someone who got theirs the easy way.
I would stake my life on it.''
   Two inmates were captured during a nearly two-hour chase that
followed the escape, and the third was apprehended early today,
authorities said. Police also arrested a woman who was in the
aircraft when it landed in a yard at the Penitentiary of New Mexico
near Santa Fe.
   Bella told his wife, Carrol, that the woman forced him to fly to
the prison by putting a gun to his head and handcuffing him to the
control stick.
   Bella was being held at the Santa Fe County Jail while
authorities checked his story, officials said. Mrs. Bella said New
Mexico authorities told her he probably would be released.
   She said her husband told him in a phone conversation Monday
that he was ``fine but mad.''
   Bella owns two helicopters and uses them in his charter
business, Bear Helicopters, Mrs. Bella said. The El Paso business
mainly serves TV news crews and real estate businesses, she said.
   Bella thought he was being hired to fly some people over a
prospective land purchase in New Mexico, his wife said.
   ``He met this supposed secretary at the Santa Fe airport and she
evidently held a gun to his head,'' she said.
   Bella flew stunts in ``Rambo III'' and the movie ``Extreme
Prejudice,'' Mobley said.
   In ``Rambo III,'' the Gazelle, modified to look like a Soviet
Hind helicopter, is shot down by Rambo, played by Sylvester
Stallone.
   A picture of Bella standing next to Stallone in front of the
Gazelle hangs on the living room wall of Bella's home.
