<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HousingIntegration     07-12 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Integration,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Families Move Into South Boston Project Without Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black families have become the first black
tenants in 10 years at a public housing project in South Boston,
the scene of racial violence when public schools were integrated in
the 1970s.
   The families moved Monday into the Mary Ellen McCormack housing
project and were greeted by Cathy Flynn, wife of Mayor Raymond
Flynn. Police kept bystanders and reporters at a distance during
the move, which took place without incident.
   Elizabeth Clinkscales and Bessie Payne and their families stayed
in their apartments Monday and would not comment.
   Ms. Clinkscales and Ms. Payne, both 36, met with reporters on
Saturday and expressed a desire to begin a stable life in their
apartments.
   ``It will take some courage to do it but I'm just doing it
because I'm a decent human being that needs to live somewhere,''
said Ms. Clinkscales, who lives with her 19-year-old daughter and
4-year-old grandson.
   ``I'm no pioneer,'' said Ms. Payne. ``I'm just almost a homeless
person _ and I don't like that feeling at all. I'm looking forward
to making a new home and getting my life straightened out again.''
   Ms. Payne has a 13-year-old son and 8-year-old daughter.
   The families were given three-bedroom apartments by the Boston
Housing Authority after they were evicted from other apartments.
   Their move is not part of an ongoing integration plan affecting
31 of 69 public housing projects, including the 1,000-tenant
McCormack.
   The plan by Flynn and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development seeks to provide subsidized housing for an estimated
500 black families passed over for placement in South Boston and
Charlestown projects since 1983.
   City officials hope successful implementation of the plan will
stall a lawsuit by minority groups.
   Many residents watching the families move in to McCormack felt
the black families would not encounter problems.
   ``I really think the press has blown it out of proportion,''
said 18-year-old Kelly Manion. ``We'll get along together. In fact,
it just might be good for the people living here.''
</TEXT>
