<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashHoax     07-12 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Hoax,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted In Fake Plane Crash Sentenced</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits to add summary line</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of masterminding a fake
plane crash during a heavy snowstorm has been sentenced to one year
in a federal prison and ordered to undergo psychiatric evaluation.
   The sentence given Monday to Mark Blair ``sends a strong message
that it's a serious crime to cry wolf,'' said U.S. Attorney Richard
Wiebusch.
   The radio report sparked a search last Jan. 8 that cost $50,000
and involved as many as 100 people, 20 aircraft and six police
agencies. They looked for a downed jet with three dead passengers
and a badly injured pilot.
   U.S. Circuit Judge Hugh Bownes said ``more than minimal planning
was involved'' in faking the crash during the storm, in which
visibility was one-half mile, temperatures were in the teens and
nine inches of snow fell.
   Blair ``must have known that (the fake report) would set off a
massive ground and air search,'' Bownes said.
   Blair, 29, was convicted in May of making a false report to the
government, a crime punishable by a fine and up to five years'
prison.
   Although Blair said he was not surprised by the sentence, he
insisted he is innocent and will appeal. Bownes declined to set
bail for Blair pending appeal.
   At the trial, Blair testified that he couldn't have committed
the hoax because he was asleep and wasn't aware a plane had been
reported down.
   But one of his neighbors testified that he heard the sound of a
two-way radio through Blair's window and a voice crying out for
help.
   David Webster, a Navy reservist and Delta Airlines pilot,
testified that he and his crew tracked the voice of a man who
talked sporadically and said that he was loosing blood, was chilled
and weak, and that at least one person in his plane was dead.
   Webster, 39, testified that his crew was overcome with emotion
when the man said he heard the Navy plane overhead.
   ``People in my plane were screaming and yelling .... I got tears
in my eyes thinking, `We're going to get this guy out,''' Webster
said.
   Bownes recommended that Blair be jailed at the Federal
Correctional Institution in Butner, N.C., a prison with extensive
psychiatric facilities.
   Blair also was sentenced to two years' probation, during which
he will be required to receive mental health counseling.
</TEXT>
