<HEAD>Iraq Says Its Troops Pushed Iran's Army From Iraqi Territory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Iraq saying it has retaken
region, Iran saying it pulling back from positions in northern
mountains, details. No pickup. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi forces today pushed Iran's army out
of the last major pockets of Iraqi territory it held along the
southern border, the official Iraqi radio said.
   Iran said its warplanes bombed Iraqi positions in the southern
Zubaidat region of Iraq, but did not say the Iraqi forces had
regained control of the area. Iran also announced its forces were
pulling back from positions in Iraq's northern mountains.
   Iraq's presidential guards spearheaded the offensive to retake a
chunk of land in the Zubaidat region along the border with Iran,
according to war communiques broadcast by Iraqi radio.
   The offensive began just after dawn and the Zubaidat area ...
 ... five missions over the Zubaidat region.
   IRNA also said Iranian troops had retreated from the town of
Halabja in northeastern Iraq to new ``defensive positions.'' The
retreat was designed to ``ma more secure approaches,'' the  ...
   In Baghdad, there was no official confirmation of an assault on
Halabja, but military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said an attack has been expected for weeks.
   Iran seized Halabja, in the Kurdish area of Iraq, last March. It
later accused Iraq of unleashing a chemical weapons offensive
against the town, killing 5,000 people.
   Iraqi communiques concentrated on the retaking of the Zubaidat
region, which fell to Iran several years ago. Neither country
confirmed how much territory Iran held in the area.
   The communiques said an unspecified number of Iranians were
either killed or wounded in today's battle east of Amara, which is
180 miles southeast of the Iraqi capital of Baghdad.
   It is the latest in a series of battlefield defeats for Iran
since the Iraqis took back the Faw peninsula on April 18.
   The communique announcing that the Zubaidat area had been
recaptured was widely believed written by President Saddam Hussein.
He has written them in the past and the phrasing in today's latest
report mirrored his style.
   It reiterated Iraq's readiness to end the war under terms of a
U.N. Security Council's Resolution 598. The resolution calls for an
immediate cease-fire and an independent inquiry into which side
started the 8-year-old war.
