<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TransplantDeath     07-12 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transplant Death,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Domino' Transplant Donor Dies 14 Months After Procedure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cystic fibrosis victim who became the
nation's first living heart donor has died of respiratory failure,
14 months after receiving a heart and lungs transplant at Johns
Hopkins Hospital.
   Clinton House, 29, who donated his heart to another man after he
received a heart-lung transplant, died while awaiting a second
transplant, his cardiologist, Dr. Thomas Traill, said Monday.
   House's respiratory failure
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   his rejection of the
transplanted lungs, the cardiologist said.
   Meanwhile, John Couch, 39, of Yardley, Pa., who received House's
original heart, continues to do well, Traill said. Couch had
suffered from congestive heart failure.
   House received the heart and lungs of a brain-dead accident
victim in a 17-hour operation on May 10-11, 1987. He needed a lung
transplant, but doctors did a heart-lung transplant because the
procedure is safer.
   House donated his healthy heart to Couch in the nation's first
so-called domino donor transplant, hospital spokesman Phil Kibak
said.
   House ``had a good summer last year, a good fall,'' said Traill.
``But from about that onwards, he began to do progessively less
well because of the system rejection.''
   House had been waiting since February for a second double
transplant, Traill said.
   Couch ``was sad and distressed,'' by House's death, said Traill.
``It didn't come as a complete surprise to (Couch), because he knew
Mr. House had been doing poorly. They had been keeping in touch.''
   Cystic fibrosis causes production of a thick, sticky mucus that
clogs the lungs and digestive system. It is the nation's most
common inherited disease, afflicting about 30,000 Americans, and
usually kills victims by the time they reach their mid-20s.
</TEXT>
