<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Coming To America' Holds First Place For Second Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second consecutive weekend, Eddie
Murphy's ``Coming To America'' was the box office leader while
Disney's ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' was second.
   The weekend box office saw four debut movies enter the Top 10
list, three of them sequels: ``Arthur 2: On The Rocks,'' the
follow-on to ``Arthur''; ``Short Circuit 2,'' reprising the tale of
a friendly robot and ``Phantasm II,'' a horror revival.
   The teen-oriented comedy ``License to Drive'' was the new effort.
   ``Coming To America,'' starring Murphy in a romantic comedy lead
that reverses his rough-talking characters of previous movies,
collected $13.2 million.
   Disney's ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' a fascinating mix of
animation and live action, took in $11.5 million to bring its take
to $54 million in just three weeks.
   In third place was ``Arthur 2: On The Rocks,'' with Dudley Moore
reviving his dipsomaniac millionaire just when comic portrayals of
drunkeness in the media are coming under fire. The movie earned
more than $5.1 million.
   ``Big,'' starring Tom Hanks, also earned about $5.1 million for
fourth place, while ``Bull Durham'' was fifth with $3.9 million.
   ``License To Drive,'' a movie about a boy's decision to
disregard his driver's license test failure and take a beautiful
girl on a date in a vintage Cadillac, earned $3.8 million for a
sixth place finish in its debut week.
   Moviegoers chipped in $3.8 million to see ``Short Circuit 2,'' a
movie about the further adventures of the curious robot Number Five
and his inventor.
   ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' earned $3.2 million for eighth place.
   ``Phantasm II,'' featuring the shiny orb that attacks its
victims with a variety of weapons, brought in $3 million for ninth
place, followed by ``The Great Outdoors,'' with $2.6 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $13.3 million, 2,064
screens, $6,464 per screen, $49.4 million, two weeks, $30 million.
   2. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' Disney, $11.5 million, 1,286
screens, $8,957 per screen, $54.5 million, three weeks, $40 million.
   3. ``Arthur 2: On The Rocks,'' Warner Bros., $5.15 million,
1,462 screens, $3,612 per screen, $5.15 million, one week, n-a.
   4. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $5.13 million, 1,384 screens,
$3,712 per screen, $60.6 million, six weeks, $15 million.
   5. ``Bull Durham,'' Orion, $3.96 million, 1,221 screens, $3,251
per screen, $27.3 million, four weeks, n-a.
   6. ``License To Drive,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.85 million, 1,223
screens, $3,148 per screen, $5.4 million (five days), one week, n-a.
   7. ``Short Circuit 2,'' Tri-Star, $3.84 million, 1,346 screens,
$2,855 per screen, $3.8 million, one week, n-a.
   8. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' Paramount, $3.2 million, 1,658
screens, $1,940 per screen, $92.2 million, seven weeks, $14 million.
   9. ``Phantasm II,'' Warner Bros. $3 million, 1,227 screens,
$2,455 per screen, $3 million, one week, n-a.
   10. ``The Great Outdoors,'' Universal, $2.6 million, 1,274
screens, $2,090 per screen, $27.7 million, four weeks, n-a.

