<DOCNO> AP880712-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-JacksonInAction 1stLd-Writethru a0440 07-12 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson In Action, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Dukakis Won't Be Alone In The Convention
Spotlight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with Bentsen selection as Dukakis running mate,
insert new 6th graf, bgng: Dukakis today; sub 20th graf bgng: And
it is; sub next to last graf, bgng: He declared; adds editor's note
at end
   </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson isn't making life easy for Michael
Dukakis.
   Dukakis and his aides undoubtedly hoped next week's Democratic
National Convention would allow the Massachusetts governor to bask
_ solo _ in the warmth of a prime-time party unity festival, the
next step toward a showdown with George Bush in the fall.
   That was until Jackson decided to campar the
vice presidential nomination, to arrange a grand arrival in this
convention city and encourage a few thousand of his closest friends
to join him and deign arduously foride the proposed bare-bones platform
crafted by
the Dukakis forces.
   Jackson was asked a few days ago whether he was worried about
stealing some of Dukakis' thunder.
   ``It has nothing to do with thunder,'' was his taunting reply.
``Mr. Dukakis had no intention of bringing any thunder to Atlanta.''
   Dukakis today stole some of Jackson's thunder. According a
well-placed Democratic Party source, Dukakis will announce later
today that he has selected Sen. Lloyd BWe intend to have an effective,
informative convention that
would inspire our nation, unify our party and take us to victory,''
he said Monday.
   But he also said that his actions in the future will be
influenced by the treatment his candidacy and platform proposals
receive.
   ``The conclusion of those steps will in some measure determine
what our fall activities will be,'' he said.
   Jackson has an uncanny ability to remain on the stage long after
other politicians would have departed. He remained a campaigner in
the primary season long after a conventional politician would have
run out of money and called it quits.
   
   He campaigned assiduously for the vice presidential nomination,
while others who want it as much or more practically blush anytime
the subject is mentioned within their earshot. Who else in American
politics would announce one day that he had decided whether he
would accept an offer to join Dukakis on the ticket, but wouldn't
tell anyone what his decision was?
   And who else would describe as ``unknown quantities'' all the
other contenders for the vice presidential nomination?
   His platform issues will be debated on national television next
week if it goes that far. He will speak during prime time on the
second night of the convention. His name will be entered into
nomination for president the following night.
   And it is conceivable that his name could be put into nomination
for vice president on the final night in a final, symbolic clash
with Dukakis.
   That, of course, would give him the chance to go to the podium
once more, perhaps to bestow his blessing at last on Dukakis and
his running mate.
   But even now, Jackson is making sure the spotlight doesn't turn
away from him when the convention ends.
   He declared on Monday _ before the choice of Bentsen became
known _ that if Dukakis offered him second place on the ticket ``I
would accept it.'' He said he assured Dukakis' emissary Paul
Brountas that he would be a loyal vice president.
   But Jackson said that if he were not chosen, he would expect
further discussions with Dukakis before defining what role he will
play in the fall campaign.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: David Espo covers politics for The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
