<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PlayboyClubloses     07-12 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Playboy Clubloses,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Playboy Club In U.S. Is Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Playboy Club in the United States
_ the 5-year-old Lansing Playboy Club in the Hilton Inn here _ will
close at the end of the month, the hotel's sales director said.
   Playboy Clubs in Des Moines and Iowa closed at the end of April.
   The first Playboy Club was opened in Chicago in 1960 by Playboy
magazine publisher Hugh Hefner, according to Karen Ziffra,
licensing manager of Chicago-based Playboy Enterprises Inc. In the
early 1970s, she said, there were as many as 22 Playboy Clubs
around the country.
   The decision to close the Lansing club coincided with the Hilton
Hotel's effort to create a new image, said Shelly Ahlers, the
hotel's sales director.
   For most of its life, the Playboy Club was a $25-a-year club
geared to males, said Bill Brook, the hotel's food and beverage
manager. In May of 1987, because of a decline in business, it was
opened to the general public.
   ``It's the end of an era,'' Brooks said. ``It was a glorious
club.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
