<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BylineStrike     07-12 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byline Strike,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bylines Withheld at Post to Protest Lack of Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters, artists, photographers and
columnists for The Washington Post withheld their bylines from
today's editions of the newspaper to protest the two years they
have gone without a labor contract with the company.
   The last contract between Post management and the
Washington-Baltimore Newspaper Guild expired July 9, 1986.
   In a flier distributed in the newsroom, Lew Diuguid, head of the
bargaining committee of the Post unit of the union, accused the
Post of ``failure to bargain in good faith.'' The guild said it
planned a two-day byline strike.
   Union leaders say there is a two-tier pay system which
established a lower minimum scale for those hired after 1976,
causing what they say is pay discrimination by race and sex.
   The union also opposes what it says is a ``pattern of force-outs
of `expensive' senior employees.''
   In a statement, Executive Editor Benjamin C. Bradlee and
Managing Editor Leonard Downie Jr. said, ``We all want a new
contract between the Post and the guild'' and that the Post ``has
now signed contracts with every one of the other 10 unions''
represented at the newspaper.
   The statement denied existence of a two-tier wage system and
said the Post is not trying to force out higher paid employees.
   The last negotiated contract between the Guild and the Post
established a top minimum pay rate of $664.35 a week. Sandra
Polaski, administrator for the guild, said that under
company-imposed rules pay has been raised, leaving an average
$240-a-week gap between white males, who are at the high end of the
scale, and black females, at the low end.
   She said that even when black women and white men with the same
experience and time at the newspaper are compared, an average
$170-a-week pay discrepancy exists.
   The guild is filing a class action complaint this week with the
D.C. Office of Human Rights asking for an investigation of
differences in pay, hiring, promotion and discharge based on sex,
race, national origin and age, Polaski said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
