<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Northwest-Truck     07-12 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Northwest-Truck,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Plane Sideswipes Service Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The left wing of a Northwest 727 passenger
jet was damaged when the plane sideswiped a service truck and
caused it to tip over, Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport
police said.
   The 84 passengers were reassigned to later flights because the
plane was forced to return to its hangar, Northwest spokesman Red
Tyler said Monday.
   The truck, which carries fuel filters for airplanes, was
unoccupied at the time of the accident, about 5:40 p.m. Monday. No
one was hurt, airport police said
   The plane, Northwest Flight 398, was bound for Indianapolis.
About 3 feet of its left wing was damaged.
   The truck, property of Butler Aviation, was parked in an airport
service area about 1,000 feet from the runway, when the plane
struck as it prepared for takeoff, said Lt. Gordon Longton of the
airport police.
</TEXT>
