<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Vendors 1stLd-Writethru a0485 07-12 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vendors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peddler Patrol Begins; Vendors Stay Off New York Streets In
Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `But the vendors xxx, to CORRECT Fulton Market
to Fulton Street Mall</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many hungry New Yorkers scanned the streets in
vain for hot dogs, shish kebabs and ice cream as Mayor Edward I.
Koch began enforcing a 5-year-old ban on food vendors on crowded
city sidewalks.
   A special police unit took to the streets Monday to see that
licensed vendors follow the ordinance, which limits the time and
location that food pushcarts may operate. But many peddlers had
already pulled their stands off the sidewalks in protest, and said
they planned to demonstrate at City Hall.
   ``Demonstrations will have no impact on us. None at all!'' said
the mayor. ``I wouldn't care if they came with 20,000 stands (to
City Hall). It will have no impact.''
   Police said they confiscated four of the polished metal
pushcarts with colorful umbrellas during the first day of the
peddler patrol. But some 600 carts disappeared from the streets as
a small group of vendors gathered across from Radio City Music Hall
to protest.
   ``It means I've got two kids and I'm out of work now. And the
mayor doesn't give a damn,'' said Thomas Michaelides, who's been
hawking hot dogs for 25 years, like his father before him.
   Those looking for a cheap lunch found themselves going hungry or
paying more than they'd like.
   ``I can't afford a $4 sandwich,'' said Jane Faraci, 36, an
office worker. ``But I can afford a $1 hot dog.'' She sat without a
meal near Rockefeller Center, sipping the soda she had purchased to
drink with her lunch.
   The mayor admitted the crackdown was a bit of political
arm-twisting to get the City Council to pass a new law that would
allow six vendors, chosen by lottery, to work each prime street
block.
   But the vendors and City Council members have balked at the
plan, resulting in Koch's edict to begin enforcing the 1983 law,
which bans vendors from corners in midtown, including Rockefeller
Center and Times Square, in the Wall Street area, near the United
Nations and in Brooklyn's Fulton Street Mall.
   A spokeswoman for the City Council, Peg Breen, said the sweep
was ``overreacting.'' She said current law, prudently enforced,
could reduce sidewalk overcrowding.
   The M. Parpis Food Distribution Co., which owns 50 vending
carts, found little help in court to fight the ban.
   Parpis' lawyers argued in Manhattan's state Supreme Court that
the ban is an unreasonable use of the city's regulatory power.
   But Justice Irving Kirschenbaum said Monday the city was within
its legal rights. Five hours later, Justice Ernst H. Rosenberger of
the Appellate Division of State Supreme Court denied a similar
request by Parpis.
   Interspersed among the picketing vendors were a dozen
red-bereted Guardian Angels, whose leader, Curtis Sliwa, vowed the
group would try to physically block the city from confiscating any
carts.
   ``As you are carting away their carts and taking the vendors
away in handcuffs, crack dealers are operating with impunity on the
same block,'' said Sliwa.
   Vendors whose carts are confiscated face up to a $1,000 fine.
Recovering the carts will cost $65 plus a $5-a-day storage fee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MissileLaunches     07-12 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Missile Launches,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Unarmed Minuteman Missiles Reach Target in South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unarmed Minuteman 3
intercontinental ballistic missiles were successfully launched
today, the 133rd and 134th in a series of tests of the weapons
system, officials said.
   The first missile was fired at 4:40 a.m. from an EC-135 jet, the
military equivalent of the Boeing 707, said Capt. Teresa V. Waddell
of the base information office.
   The missile reached its target in the Kwajalien Atoll test
range, 4,200 miles southwest of the base in the Western Pacific
Ocean, Ms. Waddell said.
   The second missile was launched at 6:21 a.m. from the ground at
the base, 150 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   The second missile followed the same path as the first and
reached the target range about 30 minutes after launch, said Airman
1st Class Ann-Marie Townsend.
   Both missiles were launched by a task force from F.E. Warren Air
Force Base in Wyoming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
