<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Clash     07-12 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Clash,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish U.N. Troops Caught In Crossfire In South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish troops of the United Nations
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon were caught in the crossfire
today in a battle between Israeli-backed militiamen and Shiite
Moslem guerrillas, security sources said.
   The sources said they had no immediate word of militia or
civilian casualties because the fighting was too intense around the
village of Braachit to allow U.N. or Red Cross teams to enter.
   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
said units of the Irish battalion manning several positions in
Braachit, 15 miles southeast of Tyre, were pinned down in the
fighting. But no casualties were reported among U.N. troops.
   Goksel said the fighting broke out at 1 p.m. when ``unknown
elements'' fired two rocket-propelled grenades at a hilltop
position manned by the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army near
Braachit.
   The Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army, which man's Israel's
self-designated security zone along the border, has come under
repeated attack by Moslem guerrillas.
   Goksel said South Lebanon Army tanks fired 90 rounds into the
village, which lies on the northern edge of the Israeli security
zone.
   The sources said five artillery or tank shells a minute were
hitting the village, which has a population of 3,000.
   The sources said two Israeli Cobra helicopter gunships later
attacked the village with machine gun fire.
   An Irish officer in Braachit, reached by telephone, said ``most
of the village has been destroyed.''
   The security sources said Lebanese Red Cross teams made two
attempts to enter the village to bring out casualties, but were
driven back by gunfire.
   Israel established the security zone in south Lebanon after it
withdrew the bulk of its forces from Lebanon in 1985. The Israelis
had invaded Lebanon three years earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
