<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FBI-Interpol     07-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Interpol,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Reportedly Keeps Chinese Interpol Leader Out Of U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI prevented a top officer of an
international police organization from entering the United States
because he was believed to be a spy who helped China gain access to
U.S. intelligence information, the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   Zhu Entao, a vice president of Interpol, was to have attended
the group's executive committee meeting in Washington last week,
but was refused a visa to enter the country, the newspaper said..
   Authorities believe Zhu played a key role in gathering
information from Larry Wu-Tai Chin, a former CIA translator. Chin
committed suicide two years ago after being convicted of selling
classified information to the Beijing government.
   Over a long period, Chin allegedly turned over volumes of
top-secret documents revealing the West's assessment of China's
strategic, military, economic and scientific capabilites.
   The Chin case was considered one of the most severe breaches in
American intelligence security in recent years.
   Chiwei Zhang, press officer for the People's Republic of China,
denounced the barring of Zhu as ``a violation of international
norms.''
   However, he declined to say what intelligence role Zhu plays for
China.
   China retaliated by notifying the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration that it was canceling plans for two Chinese
narcotics agents to attend a DEA international training session at
Quantico, Va., in the fall.
   Government sources told the newspaper that U.S. officials tried
to downplay their refusal to give Zhu a visa by arranging for the
Interpol meeting to take place at the group's Paris headquarters
instead of in Washington. Zhu reportedly attended the Paris
gathering.
   Richard C. Stiener, chief of Interpol's U.S. national central
bureau, was ``too tied up and won't be able to talk'' about the Zhu
incident, spokeswoman Beverly R. Sweatman said.
   However, she said Zhu was elected a delegate at Interpol's 1985
general assembly meeting in the United States, which means that he
attended that session.
   A U.S. intelligence source told The Times the FBI raised
objections to Zhu's most recent attempt to enter the country
because they knew more about him after the Chin case than they did
in 1985.
</TEXT>
