<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonDummies     07-12 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Dummies,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Escape, Leave Dummies In Beds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCKER, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four inmates, including two convicted
murderers, fooled prison guards by putting ``dummies'' in their
cots and escaped overnight from a state prison in central
Arakansas, officials said today.
   The escape was discovered at 7 a.m., but prison spokesman David
White said authorities were not sure when the men broke out of the
prison's maximum security unit in Tucker, about 30 miles southeast
of Little Rock.
   White said bed checks are usually conducted about every four
hours, and the dummies were counted at least twice during the night.
   ``At the 7 a.m. count, when there wasn't any movement, they were
discovered missing,'' White said.
   At about the same time, authorities also found a hole in a fence
around the prison. According to White, it was the first escape from
the unit.
   White identified the escapees as convicted murderers James Ray
Renton, 50, and Raymond Coble, 29; Tommy Winberry, 38, convicted of
two counts of attempted murder, and David Fane, 31, convicted of
aggravated robbery and other crimes.
   Coble and Winberry escaped from another state prison in November
1986, White said, but were recaptured a short time later.
   Jefferson County Sheriff's Lt. Boe Fontaine said deputies were
using an airplane, tracking dogs and a roadblock in their search
for the escapees.
</TEXT>
