<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthernAfrica-Talks     07-12 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Southern Africa-Talks,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Meet For Last Day of Talks on Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African, Angolan, Cuban and U.S.
officials met today for the last day of their talks on ending South
African rule in neighboring Namibia and withdrawing Cuban troops
from Angola.
   The military and political officials held the talks at the U.S.
Coast Guard base on Governors Island in New York harbor.
   The participants in the talks have released no comments on the
outcome of the talks.
   South Africa has said it would accept a U.N. Security Council
resolution calling for Namibia's independence under black majority
rule only after the withdrawal of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops
backing Angola's Marxist government.
   Anti-communist rebels, backed by the United States and South
Africa, have been fighting government troops since 1985.
   U.S. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, have said
the timetable for the Cuban pullout has not been set and is the
most difficult issue in the talks.
   The U.S. goal is a complete Cuban withdrawal within one year,
when a United Nations resolution has proposed granting independence
to Namibia, also called South-West Africa.
   Angola and Cuba have said that the Cuban withdrawal should take
place over four years.
   Angola has been convulsed by civil war since it gained
independence from Portugal in 1975. The government, supported by
Cuba, has been fighting anti-communist rebels belonging to the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   South Africa has repeatedly sent troops across the border from
Namibia into Angola to support the rebel forces. The Angolan
government is seeking the permanent withdrawal of all South African
forces from its territory.
   Cuba has increased its troop strength in Angola from 35,000 to
37,000 soldiers last fall to about 50,000 now, U.S. officials have
said.
   South Africa has had administrative control over Namibia since
1920.
   The four parties involved in the current talks first met for
talks in London in May and again last month in Cairo, Egypt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
