<DOCNO> AP880712-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen-Finances     07-12 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Finances,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demo Ticket Has Two Millionaires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Michael Dukakis' selection of Lloyd Bentsen
as his running mate, the 1988 Democratic presidential ticket will
consist of two millionaires.
   Bentsen has a personal worth estimated at $1.4 million to $2
million, according to financial disclosure forms on file in public
records.
   The Texas senator is also a prolific campaign fund raiser who
ran into controversy last year with a practice of collecting
$10,000 apiece from lobbyists who ate breakfast with him once a
month.
   After press reports surfaced about the ``breakfast club,''
Bentsen acknowledged in February 1987 that he had made a ``doozy''
of a mistake in forming such a club.
   Bentsen had solicited members to his ``Chairman's Council'' by
sending letters to 200 political action committees and lobbyists
telling them he was seeking advice and assistance for his campaign.
   On his personal financial statement this year, which is separate
from the campaign fund, Bentsen listed income of between $296,733
and $418,225 and up. The forms are designed in a manner that does
not require disclosure of a specific amount.
   His assets included a Warwick condominium and furnishings in
Houston, a qualified blind trust from which he received at least
$100,001 in interest last year, a note to Brazoria Lake inc. of
Brazoria County, Texas, and Bellfield Farm on the Shenandoah River
in Clarke County, Va.
   Bentsen was born into wealth. His father, ``Big Lloyd'' Bentsen,
migrated to the Rio Grande Valley after World War I and made
himself wealthy as a rancher and by buying land and reselling it.
   Dukakis has a net worth of more than $500,000 in property,
investments and salary, and also is the potential beneficiary of $1
million in trusts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0445 07-12 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Camp Mum On Whether Veep Choice Made</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis not commenting today in top 5 grafs,
picking up in 4th graf pvs, As Brountas; subs 11th graf pvs, The
top</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, apparently having chosen Lloyd
Bentsen as his vice presidential running mate, smiled and joked
with news photographers today but declined to talk about the choice
that sources said he'd made.
   The sources, who commented only on condition they not be named,
said the Texas senator was chosen late Monday night in a meeting
among Dukakis, his long-time confidant Paul Brountas and campaign
manager Susan Estrich. The word was passed to Bentsen late in the
night or early this morning and he accepted.
   Bentsen, 67, was flying to Boston today to meet with Dukakis.
   Dukakis refused to speak to reporters when he arrived at the
Statehouse today, although he allowed photographers into his office
as he sifted through paperwork. ``It's kind of fun, this business
running for the presidency,'' he said.
   Dukakis and Brountas met Monday night a few hours after Brountas
talked with Jesse Jackson in Washington.
   As Brountas left the house, he was asked if the selection
process was over and he replied, ``He (Dukakis) can always ask more
questions if he wants.''
   Asked if a decision had been made, the Boston lawyer said, ``No
comment.''
   While he waited for Brountas, Dukakis appeared in his yard
shortly after dark, dressed in shorts and a short-sleeve shirt and
mowed his lawn with a push mower.
   Dukakis was meeting today with party chairman from around the
country, a session designed to assure them that they would be
included in planning for the fall campaign.
   ``We asked for the meeting,'' said Ohio Democratic chairman
James Ruvolo. ``We wanted to get things squared away.''
   Ruvolo said he had no idea what the status was of his state's
vice-presidential favorite, Sen. John Glenn of Ohio.
   Speculation about the potential vice presidential choice was a
top subject of conversation in Atlanta among the early arrivals for
the convention.
   The top contenders were believed to include Glenn and Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee. Also on the short list were Sens.
Bentsen and Bob Graham of Florida and Reps. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri and Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   The contenders themselves were maintaining a discreet silence _
except for Jackson who said for the first time that ``if it was
offered to me I would accept it.''
   Jackson made his statement after meeting with Brountas in
Washington, his first public declaration that he would accept the
spot if Dukakis offered it.
   Jackson said he gave Brountas the detailed personal financial
information that has been solicited from prospective running mates,
and said he offered his ``candid view as to the office of vice
president ... and what I thought my qualifications would be.''
   Brountas refused to discuss the substance of the discussion,
saying only that it was ``an excellent meeting ... very
productive.''
   Jackson said ``it is self-evident'' that he wants to be vice
president and said he assured Brountas that he would be a loyal
second to Dukakis.
   If he is not on the ticket, said Jackson, he would expect
further discussions with Dukakis about his role in the fall
campaign.
 
</TEXT>
