<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0533,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Capture Three Inmates Plucked From Prison By
Helicopter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6, ``A yellow-and-bronze xxx, with three grafs,
and graf 14 pvs, ``He was flying xxx, with more detail on escape</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AQ1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police with dogs today captured a
murderer whose girlfriend allegedly hijacked the helicopter used in
an aerial prison breakout that was foiled by other copters after a
wild two-hour chase, authorities said.
   Daniel Mahoney, 30, was caught early this morning near Los Lunas
after a corrections officer spotted his trail and called a canine
unit, which tracked him along the Rio Grande, said state police
Sgt. John Balderston.
   The two other Penitentiary of New Mexico inmates who escaped
Monday morning with Mahoney, his girlfriend and the pilot also were
in custody today. The pilot said he had been hijacked and a friend
said he had flown the same helicopter in the movie ``Rambo III.''
   Authorities gave this account of the escape attempt, during
which a U.S. Customs Service helicopter was nearly rammed and the
escapees allegedly tried to force a state police chopper into a
crane:
   A yellow-and-bronze Aerospatiale Gazelle helicopter landed in a
prison yard about 9:50 a.m. Monday, and the three convicts jumped
aboard amid fire from tower guards. One other unidentified convict
was forced off or jumped off the chopper, which haad a hard time
getting off the ground.
   A Customs copter and Immigration and Naturalization Service
airplane chased them 80 miles south to Mid-Valley Airport in Los
Lunas, where Mahoney, Randy Mack Lackey and Beverly Shoemaker
jumped out. Waiting state troopers wounded and arrested Lackey
after he tried to run them down with a pickup truck.
   They also arrested Ms. Shoemaker, 41, but Mahoney escaped.
   The Gazelle flew to Coronado Airport, a commuter airport on the
north side of Albuquerque, where it hovered as police drove up. It
headed south as a state police helicopter joined the chase, and
headed for Albuquerque International Airport. There, the Gazelle
tried to ram the Customs craft and to force the police copter into
a crane.
   ``We were hanging right with him,'' said state police pilot Maj.
John Denko. ``We were not giving him a chance to set down and get
away.''
   The Gazelle landed on the airport tarmac with its pursuers right
behind, Denko said. The pilot ``was running low on fuel. He was
getting desperate.''
   A man later identified as Francis Preston Mitchell leaped out,
``looked around for a second, put his hands up and flattened on the
ground,'' he said.
   The pilot, Charles ``Cheater'' Bella, 43, of El Paso, Texas, was
found in the helicopter, handcuffed to the controls, authorities
said. ``No one was armed when we got to them,'' Denko said, adding
that officers saw two guns thrown out of the helicopter during the
chase.
   Bella was being held at the Santa Fe County Jail today while
police checked his story that he was hijacked after flying to Santa
Fe to pick up a fare.
   Bella, owner of Bear Helicopters, was hired by a man who
identified himself as a businessman, said his wife, Carrol, in El
Paso. He told his wife that Ms. Shoemaker put a gun to his head and
handcuffed him to the control stick.
   Bella's Gazelle played the ``Russian'' copter movie star
Sylvester Stallone shot down with a explosive-tipped arrow in
``Rambo III,'' said a friend, Tony Mobley. Bella also did stunts in
the movie ``Extreme Prejudice.''
   Ms. Shoemaker's name appears on Mahoney's visitor list and the
Santa Fe resident is believed to be his girlfriend, said Dan
Taylor, spokesman for the state Department of Public Safety.
   Mahoney was serving life plus 60 years for second-degree murder
in Florida. Lackey, 36, was treated in Albuquerque for a shoulder
wound and returned to the prison, where he was serving nine years
for larceny in Curry County, N.M. Mitchell, 26, was doing life for
murder in Summit County, Utah.
   The three escapees had been housed in adjacent cells, and were
classified as medium-security prisoners, said state Corrections
Secretary O.L. McCotter.
   Mahoney and Mitchell were being held in New Mexico under an
interstate agreement providing for exchange of prisoners among
states.
</TEXT>
