<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru a0520 07-12 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Falls to Lowest Close Since Late '86, Outlook Lower Still</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with prices falling further today, picks up
5th graf pvs, Refined products...; Version moved on financial
circuits</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices dropped sharply for the second
straight day today, tumbling toward the $14-a-barrel level in
reaction to fears of a relentless supply glut and OPEC's failure to
restrain output.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a sensitive barometer of
price trends, the August-delivery price for West Texas Intermediate
was $14.49 a barrel by midday, down 29 cents from the 20-month
closing low of $14.78 set Monday.
   ``The market is awash in crude and the focus has returned to
that,'' said Chris McCormack, an energy futures trader with the New
York investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``The market just
looks extremely bearish.''
   The decline Monday erased gains made last week, which were based
on fears of supply disruptions caused by a major oil platform
explosion in the North Sea.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also fell sharply,
although not as steeply as crude. Wholesale heating oil for August
delivery fell 2.06 cents a gallon to 41.33 cents, while wholesale
unleaded gasoline fell 1.04 cents a gallon to 52.13 cents.
   At one point during the day, crude prices rose briefly on a news
report that the price-monitoring committee of the 13-member
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries might confer soon.
   OPEC's official news agency said the meeting might be held after
the cartel's general secretary, Indonesia's Subroto, met with
officials of the United Arab Emirates for talks ``concerning the
current oil market situation.'' Output cheating by members of the
cartel has weakened the market seriously recently, making OPEC's
$18-per-barrel target price more remote than ever. The United Arab
Emirates has been mentioned as a significant violator.
   Said Edward Ryan, a trader at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.'s energy
futures unit, ``Crude has gotten down to a supply-demand scenario.
There's simply too much. I think the market needs to see something
of substance. The rhetoric of OPEC is ridiculous. Every trader
considers it ridiculous.''
   By some analyst reckonings, the cartel now is pumping as much as
18.8 million barrels a day, more than 3 million barrels a day over
its official ceiling of 15.06 million barrels.
</TEXT>
