<HEAD>Thunderstorms Drench Texas, Cause Flooding</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts 2nd graf to CLARIFY that drowning victims total five.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `During a...'; ADDS new material from
Baltimore area in grafs 7 and 8. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `In
Pennsylvania...'
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms drenched central Texas today after dropping nearly
10 inches of rain, causing severe flooding along rivers and creeks,
while storms pelted New England with hail and wind gusting to 89
mph.
   Five people were killed in the Texas floods, including four
members of a California family whose station wagon was swept down a
flooded creekbed in western Texas. One man was missing after he
tried to reach safety from a stalled truck in the rain-swollen
Guadalupe River near Hunt.
   During a six-hour period overnight in Texas, 1.97 inches of rain
fell at Crossville, 1.12 inches at Bergstrom Air Force Base in
Austin and .81 inches at San Antonio.
   Rain continued early today over south-central Texas, and
forecasters warned that more heavy rain was possible.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from Alabama to
New England.
   On Monday, thunderstorms produced large hail and damaging wind
along the mid-Atlantic coast and in New England. Windsor Locks,
Conn., had wind gusts to 89 mph and Groton, Mass., had gusts to 60
mph.
   Violent thunderstorms in the Chesapeake Bay area left 194,000
homes and business without power in the Baltimore and Washington
areas. Baltimore Gas and Electric planned to distribute dry ice
today to customers without power.
   The storms also knocked out the signal system on the Amtrak line
between Odenton and Perryville in Maryland's Cecil County, delaying
more than a dozen trains for about 90 minutes.
   In Pennsylvania, strong wind tore the tops off trees and left
power lines sagging near Oaksville and Wellsville. A thunderstorm
in southeastern New York produced high wind that toppled several
trees at Millerton. A storm also ripped down power lines in
Aberdeen, Md.
   In the South, storms overnight dropped .75 inches of rain near
Montgomery, Ala., .74 inches at Tuscaloosa, Ala., and .71 inches at
Columbus, Ga.
   Parts of the East continued to swelter under a heat wave Monday,
with New York reaching a record 98 degrees for the date and
Baltimore a record 102.
   The high for the nation Monday was 109 at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The weather was fair early today across the West and in the
north-central United States.
   Today's forecast called for thunderstorms, some possibly severe,
over the Dakotas; showers and thunderstorms from southern New
England to southern Florida, over the lower Appalachians, and
across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, southern Missouri and
Arkansas; and showers and thunderstorms from Montana to Washington
state.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s and 70s over
the Pacific Northwest and the upper Missouri Valley; 70s to near 80
degrees over the Great Lakes, northern New England and the
California coast; 90s from southern New Jersey through Florida, the
Gulf of Mexico states, southern Plains, western portions of the
central Plains and parts of Nevada and Utah; 100 to 110 degrees
over the desert Southwest; and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46 at
Marquette, Mich., to 92 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 cloudy; Boston 77 hazy; Buffalo 67 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 76 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 69 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 69 fair; Detroit 65 fair; Miami 83 fair; New York 78
showers; Philadelphia 76 hazy; Pittsburgh 74 cloudy; Portland,
Maine, 75 hazy; Washington 76 showers.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 71 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 thunderstorms; Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 68 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 70 partly cloudy; Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 64 fair; Nashville 74 cloudy; New Orleans 79 fair; St. Louis
76 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 73 fair; Anchorage 58 cloudy; Las Vegas 88
fair; Los Angeles 65 cloudy; Phoenix 92 fair; Salt Lake City 78
partly cloudy; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 56
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 68 partly cloudy; Toronto 64 fair.
</TEXT>
