<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Drought 1stLd-Writethru a0450 07-12 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drought, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 10 grafs new to UPDATE with Senate bill introduced;
pickup 9th graf pvs, But they would.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm senators unveiled a legislative blueprint
today for payments of up to $100,000 to prevent heat and lack of
rain from driving crop and livestock producers off their
drought-stricken land.
   ``We're not going to see their lives as farmers and ranchers end
this year because of a freak of nature,'' declared Agriculture
Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., as he unveiled the
measure in a Senate floor speech.
   But Leahy sounded a cautionary note concerning the bill's
timetable.
   ``This legislation will move as quickly through the committee
and the Senate as the members want it to move,'' he said, echoing
statements Monday that reckless speed with the legislation would be
a mistake.
   Farmers and ranchers ``also realize that if we were to try some
politically expedient, zip-through piece of legislation, a lot of
them are going to be left out,'' he told reporters Monday at the
White House.
   Farm lawmakers emerged from a meeting with President Reagan
saying no snags have appeared to slow action on the relief bill
calling for federal disaster payments of up to $100,000 for
drought-stricken crop producers.
   They said Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng told the
president that the measure, which would cancel a 50-cent cut in
dairy prices, is shaping up as ``a pretty good piece'' of
legislation.
   Lyng said Thursday that the need for a bill is now ``urgent''
and House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said Monday that he wanted
floor action this week.
   ``I don't think anybody should put artificial deadlines on it,''
Leahy said. ``The important thing is that you tell people about to
go bankrupt that there is hope, that there will be planting and
raising herds next year.''
   As sketched by congressional sources, both House and Senate
bills would provide disaster payments for drought-stricken
producers of those crops covered by federal farm programs and those
that are not. Payments would amount to 65 percent of pre-drought
expected earnings, whether from target prices, price-support loans
or market prices.
   But they would apply only to losses in excess of 35 percent of
the crop. Any deficiency payments _ income supports provided by the
Agriculture Department _ would be deducted from the disaster
payments, and there would be an array of other limitations. No
individual would be able to receive more than $100,000 under the
legislation.
   For example, a corn producer would receive a disaster payment of
65 percent of the target price of $2.93 a bushel, or $1.90 a bushel
multiplied by the amount of his loss in excess of 35 percent of the
historical yield he has established with the Agriculture Department.
   A farmer with 100 acres planted in corn under the program and a
100-bushel expected yield would receive a disaster payment of
$12,350 under the legislation if his entire crop were wiped out.
   For livestock producers, a number of programs already in effect
would be restructured to take in all types of food animals. The
bill also would allow the secretary of agriculture to depart from
current practice and provide such assistance to farmers who do not
grow their own feed.
   Blazing sun and lack of rainfall have scorched hay across much
of the Farm Belt, and livestock feed is now at a premium. Cattlemen
are complaining that they are obliged to rush to market with their
herds for lack of feed.
   Under the bill, farmers would be allowed to plant soybeans and
sunflowers on 10 percent to 35 percent of a farm's program acreage
without losing the historical wheat, feed grain, cotton and rice
bases they have established with the Agriculture Department for
purposes of taking part in farm programs.
   There have been forecasts of a squeeze in soybeans supplies
because of the drought, and prices already are high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
