<DOCNO> AP880712-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writhethru a0444 07-12 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writhethru, a0444,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Hopes to Lure Black Voters Away from Democratic Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 13 grafs new with Bush comments before NAACP; picks up
5th graf pvs, bgng, `While the.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, wooing votes at
the NAACP convention, promised today to have a ``positive civil
rights agenda'' and paid tribute to Jesse Jackson ``for running the
race, for being heard.''
   In an appearance before several thousand people at the 79th
convention of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, Bush did not mention reports of Michael Dukakis'
plans to name Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate on the
Democratic ticket.
   Bush, delivering his speech beneath a banner proclaiming,
``Vote, Be Heard,'' got a warm reception from the audience. He said
he wanted to be heard ``because I do not intend to concede the vote
of any American.''
   The vice president, certain to be the Republican presidential
nominee, said a Bush administration would mark ``a new day'' from
the Reagan administration.
   ``I will have a positive civil rights agenda,'' he pledged.
   ``I guarantee you I will be personally involved in protecting
the civil rights of all Americans,'' Bush said. ``This effort will
be at the top of the agenda of my attorney general, and he or she
will be directly accountable to me for results.''
   The audience applauded loudly.
   Bush also said he had known Jackson, the runner-up in the
Democratic primaries, for a long time in a friendly, personal way.
   ``And I don't have to cover up the differences _ I have profound
differences with Jesse on many of these issues, but I salute him
for running the race, for being heard, and he deserves a salute
from us,'' Bush said, again drawing loud applause from the audience.
   The vice president readily acknowledged that Republicans since
the days of President Franklin D. Roosevelt have not been able to
win much of the black vote.
   However, he pledged that if elected president his decisions
``will not depend on getting a certain percentage of the black
vote. I want to do what is fair. I want to do what is right. And I
want to do what is principled.''
   Bush promised that regardless of the black vote he gets ``you
will be heard, I promise you that. You are going to be called on.
You are going to be partners in my presidency.''
   Jackson is to address the convention tonight and Dukakis is to
speak before it on Wednesday.
   While the Reagan administration has been criticized as being
insensitive to blacks, Bush has a good relationship with some black
leaders and has promised that a Bush administration would have a
positive civil rights agenda.
   By a significant margin, blacks voted for Democrats Walter
Mondale in 1984 and Jimmy Carter in 1980 rather than the
Reagan-Bush ticket. However, in opening the NAACP convention,
Benjamin Hooks, the group's executive director, said it would be a
``fatal mistake'' for Democrats to assume they have the black vote
wrapped up.
   The NAACP is the third special interest group that Bush has
courted this week, following an appearance Sunday before
Lithuanians and before a group of farm writers, editors and
broadcasters on Monday.
   Responding to a question from the audience at the Agricultural
Communicators Congress, meeting in Washington, Bush said he might
consider Senate Republican leader Bob Dole or any of the other
contenders in the Republican primary race as a running mate.
   The vice president said Dole of Kansas was ``deservedly popular
in agricultural America. He knows a great deal about it.''
   ``But I just don't want to start going through long lists or
short lists (of candidates) because believe me, at this juncture,
we don't have them,'' Bush said.
   ``I will say this about Bob Dole. He and I went head on head,''
Bush added. ``So did Pat Robertson and Al Haig and Pete du Pont and
Jack Kemp. ...
   ``My party has never been more unified going into a Republican
convention than we are right now thanks to the way Bob Dole and the
others have been conducting themselves and their sense of
advocacy,'' Bush said. ``So the fact you ran against somebody
certainly in my view would not preclude consideration of that
person.''
   Outlining factors that will influence his decision, Bush said
the fundamental criteria will be who _ man or woman _ is best
qualified to take over if something happens to the president.
   ``I would want a certain philosophical compatability to be
there,'' he said. ``Then I will do what all politicians do _ throw
a little bit of seasoning in there for geography.'' However, Bush
said that factor was not important as it has been.
   ``I'll look who the Democrats pick and then we will have
procedures for selecting, and they will be, getting, soliciting
opinion from the senators, the Republicans and members of the
Republican National Committeee and congressmen and governors and
all of that.
   ``And that will probably be done by the Republican National
Committee,'' Bush said. ``Sometimes that's been done in the past.
   ``And then I will make a very personal decision,'' he added.
   In a speech that he billed as non-partisan, Bush nevertheless
took several jabs at Dukakis, saying, ``I am not the one who feels
that the problems of agricultural America can be solved by planting
more belgian endive.''
   He also said a Bush administration would help farmers export
more crops, ``not force farmers to produce less. That is the major
difference.''
</TEXT>
