<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Vatican-Soviet     07-12 0114</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Vatican-Soviet,0116</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Ambassador Pays Rare Call On Pope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet ambassador to Italy met with Pope
John Paul II on Tuesday and briefed him on the recent Soviet
Communist Party Congress, the Vatican reported.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro said it was the first time a
Soviet ambassador had requested a private audience with the pope,
although Soviet ambassadors have accompanied Soviet officials to
meetings with the pontiff.
   Navarro called it a ``courtesy call and a further occasion for
dialogue between the U.S.S.R. and the Holy See.''
   He said the ambassador, Nikolai M. Lunkov, had taken part in the
party congress and wanted to inform John Paul about it.
</TEXT>
