<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Pen Pals,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Deputies Go Directly To Jail Cell For 45 Minutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security was especially tight in one cell
in the Oakland County Jail, where three sheriff's officers spent 45
minutes locked inside after scuffling with an inmate.
   The inmate was alone when he tore a telephone from a wall of the
holding cell on Friday.
   The first officer entered the cell and the inmate punched him in
the face. A second officer came to help, and all three scuffled. A
third officer arrived and put her foot in the cell door. She
grabbed the inmate's leg and was pulled inside, too.
   The door automatically locked shut, leaving the foursome inside
with no telephone.
   Southfield police arrived 45 minutes later to book a prisoner,
and the officers were freed, Southfield Officer Gary Conat said.
   The inmate, who was not identified, proved a less than gracious
host, sheriff's Lt. Jerry Girard said.
   ``When the Southfield police finally get upstairs and the
officers are released, the inmate's on the floor, snoring,'' Girard
said. ``He was sound asleep.''
</TEXT>
