<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--FreeFray     07-12 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Free Fray,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Swamp Warehouse For Free Soaked Clothing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't tell Harold Wolfe about the drought.
   Wolfe, who owns a hardware store, was deluged twice Monday,
first when a water main broke and flooded his warehouse and then
when he decided to give away 10,000 pieces of soaked secondhand
work clothing.
   ``Once they were wet, I decided not to clean them,'' said Wolfe,
who in drier times sells the used pants, shirts and coveralls for
$1 to $4 apiece. ``I put them in the field and let the word out
that they were free.''
   Word got out, all right, as 250 people descended.
   ``It was fun. People were fighting over them,'' Wolfe said.
``Some of them really had nerve; they asked for sizes.''
   ``It's a nice haul,'' said Mary Pullens, 61, who lives across
the street. ``Anyone who uses work clothes and wasn't working was
here.''
</TEXT>
