<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-12 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Activists To Participate In Municipal Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white anti-apartheid
coalition said Tuesday it would not adopt the election boycott
strategy of black activists and instead would try to elect
pro-integration candidates in municipal elections.
   The Five Freedoms Forum, which represents 25 human rights and
religious groups, said the focus of its campaign would be to elect
an anti-apartheid municipal council in Johannesburg, the country's
largest city.
   Segregated elections for councils in white, black, mixed-race
and Asian communities are scheduled nationwide for Oct. 26, the
first time voters of all races will go to the polls on the same day.
   The government has outlawed public calls for an election
boycott, but black activists have said they oppose participation in
any elections until South Africa's 26 million blacks are given
voting rights on the national level.
   Prominent anti-apartheid clergymen two weeks ago defied the
government ban and urged South Africans not to vote in October.
   The Five Freedoms Forum, in a statement, said it was not
criticizing those who favored a boycott of the elections.
   ``The Johannesburg City Council, as a whites-only body, is a
structure infected with the racism implicit in the government's
apartheid policy,'' the statement said. ``However, despite the
inadequacy of these structures, we do not believe that any purpose
would be served by calling on whites to boycott.''
   The statement said the elections could be used as a vehicle for
campaigning against apartheid laws such as the Group Areas Act,
which establishes racially segregated residential districts.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a segregated society in
which the blacks have no vote in national affairs, controlled by
the 5 million whites.
   The government is spending more than $2 million on an
advertising campaign to promote participation in the elections.
   Officials of Transvaal Province, which includes Johannesburg and
Pretoria, on Tuesday called on employers to help their black
workers register to vote by obtaining forms that could be filled
out at workplaces.
</TEXT>
