<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser Funeral, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 800 People, Including Teamster Leaders, Attend Presser
Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, material from eulogies; picks up 6th
graf, `Presser, 61 xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.R. Kropko</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President Jackie
Presser was praised at his funeral today as a major civic force in
Cleveland and as a ``tough guy'' with heart.
   The executive committee of the Teamsters union and about 800
other people listened as Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, commended
Presser for his appearances before a Senate committee.
   ``He wanted people to know that there were people in the
Teamsters willing to stand up and face the public,'' said Hatch,
who chaired the hearings before the Labor and Human Relations
Committee. ``He believed in the labor movement, and he wasn't
afraid to stand up and say so.''
   Presser, he said, ``was a tough guy but one with a heart. He
laughed infectiously at bitter taunts that would hurt lesser men.''
   Among those greeting guests as they entered was Harold Friedman,
international vice president and president of Presser's own Local
507. Friedman was charged with Presser in a $700,000
payroll-padding scheme at Local 507 and still is awaiting trial.
   Presser was also a defendant in a U.S. District Court lawsuit
filed two weeks ago in an attempt by the U.S. government to take
over the Teamsters and rid the union of alleged Mafia domination.
   Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich described Presser as a major
civic force for Cleveland and praised him for his assistance in
helping the city out of default. Presser was vice president of a
state-appointed commission that oversaw Cleveland finances until it
rose out of default a year ago.
   Acting President Weldon Mathis and the other union leaders made
no comment as they entered the packed Berkowitz-Kumin Chapel.
Presser's casket was at the front of the chapel, which was draped
with flowers.
   Presser, 61, who died Saturday, had been battling brain cancer
and a lung clot. Although his union has been criticized by federal
officials, Presser was remembered by local leaders in his hometown
of Cleveland as a man dedicated to the city.
   ``He never had Cleveland out of his consciousness, even when he
was outside Cleveland and traveling around the world,'' Mike Benz,
executive vice president of the Greater Cleveland Growth
Association, said Monday.
   A native of Cleveland who has been involved in organized labor
most of his adult life, Presser made a big mark on the community 18
years ago when he helped found the United Labor Agency, an
organization to help needy local residents, said Michael J. Murphy,
the agency's executive director.
   The union leadership indicated earlier that it might announce a
date to select Presser's successor as president of the
1.6-million-member union after today's services.
   The payroll-padding trial had been scheduled to start today but
was postponed because of Presser's battle with brain cancer.
   Presser denied ever being controlled by the mob. He said he was
an FBI informant and that the FBI authorized the hiring of ``ghost
employees'' at Local 507.
</TEXT>
