<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachWaste     07-12 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Waste,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One New York Beach Blood Vial Infected With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three vials that washed ashore last
week on New York beaches contained human blood infected with the
AIDS virus, state Health Commissioner Dr. David Axelrod said today.
   Axelrod said the sample, discovered on Lido Beach about 20 miles
east of New York City, also tested positive for hepatitis at the
state Health Department laboratory in Albany.
   Another vial, found on a beach about 40 miles east of the city,
contained blood that tested both positive and negative for the
virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, Axelrod said.
   A third vial tested negative, the health commissioner said.
   Axelrod said the chances of beachgoers getting infected with the
AIDS virus or hepatitis, by either stepping on the vials and being
cut by broken glass or from blood spilled on the beach or in the
water, are ``remote.''
   Neither virus can survive for long outside the human body, and
the sample that tested positive for the AIDS virus is believed to
be inactive.
   ``The conditions to which the infected samples were exposed
almost certainly destroyed most if not all the active virus,''
Axelrod said.
   While the results ``confirm some of our fears'' about the danger
of the material that washed up on Long Island beaches, Axelrod said
``we do not feel the presence of these materials represent a
significant public health hazard.''
   Axelrod said investigators do not yet know where the vials
originated or how long they were in the water. But the commissioner
said they are of a design that is ``clearly associated with the
medical establishment.''
   The vials could have come from a doctor's office, medical
research facility or a hospital, he said.
   The discovery of blood samples and other medical debris
temporarily closed some of Long Island's most popular beaches late
last week in the midst of a prolonged heat wave. When the beaches
reopened over the weekend, attendance was cut in half in many
places.
   As of today, all beaches on Long Island and in New York City
were open except for a 1.4-mile stretch of Staten Island's Midland
Beach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
