<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Reported to Attack Plant Activists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with government spox saying one detained,
says no riot police involved, Solidarity saying a dozen activists
still in church; pickup 10th graf pvs, ``About 4,000 ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police attacked and arrested steel workers
who threatened to strike during Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit, and
today surrounded a church where some workers took refuge,
opposition activists said.
   A government spokesman confirmed a ``conflict-prone situation''
at the church, and said at least one person was temporarily
detained after the incident Monday night in the southeastern city
of Stalowa Wola. But he denied any organized police attack.
   Ewa Tomaszewska, a spokesman for the banned Solidarity trade
union movement, said an undetermined number of people were detained.
   ``We suspect that the action is an act of revenge for a rally
that took place July 7,'' said Zbigniew Romaszewski, who monitors
human rights for Solidarity.
   About 50 people retreated into the grounds of the church, said
Romaszewski and Tomaszewska. About a dozen remained there today,
said Ewa Kaberna, a Solidarity activist in the city, speaking in a
phone call from the church.
   Police in Poland rarely enter church grounds to make detentions.
   ``Conflict-prone situations did arise there yesterday ... But I
can say that there were no major disturbances,'' said a government
press spokesman, Ryszard Strauss.
   But he added, ``I cannot say that not a single policeman used
his truncheon because I was not there.''
   There was no effect on work at the Stalowa Wola steel mill,
where the workers are employed, he said.
   Strauss said police moved in when members of the Solidarity
committee of the mill attempted to launch a rally outside the
church. He denied a report that riot police were involved and said
only normal patrols were continuing at the church Tuesday.
   A strike occurred at the mill April 29-30 during Poland's worst
wave of labor unrest since the December 1981 military crackdown
that stifled Solidarity.
   About 4,000 Stalowa Wola workers were reported by Solidarity
spokesmen to have rallied Thursday to demand reinstatement of seven
dismissed members of the April strike committee.
   Rally organizers said that if the seven were not rehired, they
would call a strike during the Gorbachev visit. The Soviet leader
and his wife Raisa arrived Monday and are scheduled to stay until
Saturday.
   Today, they were visiting the southern city of Krakow.
   Tomaszewska said a strike at the Stalowa Wola mill was expected
``in the upcoming days,'' but no date had been set.
</TEXT>
