<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-FaneuilHall     07-12 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Faneuil Hall,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Chooses `Cradle Of Liberty' To Announce Bentsen As Running
Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faneuil Hall, the historic building picked by
Michael Dukakis to introduce Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his
running mate, has been a centerpiece of both the American
Revolution and of a modern economic revival.
   A box-shaped brick structure with a steeple crowned by a
grasshopper weathervane, the Great Hall in Faneuil Hall, as it is
formally known, was built in 1742 as a gift to the city by merchant
Peter Faneuil.
   It earned the nickname ``The Cradle of Liberty'' as a forum for
revolutionaries grousing about the taxation policies of the British
Empire and plotting their revolt.
   Later it was the staging ground for anti-slavery, temperance and
women's suffrage rallies. Among speakers who stood there were
Frederick Douglass, Daniel Webster and Susan B. Anthony.
   Still much in use for public celebrations and political
speeches, it was here that Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., announced
his candidacy for the presidential nomination in November 1979.
   Dukakis has also stood on this stage before. The 900-seat hall
just 100 feet from Boston Harbor was the background for some
tapings of ``The Advocates,'' a public affairs TV program he
moderated in 1970-73, before he became governor of Massachusetts.
   The building, owned by the city and maintained by the National
Park Service, became the anchor of a 1970s refurbishment of the
Faneuil Hall Marketplace, a cobblestoned mall of boutiques, food
stalls and souvenir vendors. It is one of the nation's most visited
tourist attractions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-MIAs     07-12 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam To Turn Over More U.S. Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team goes to Vietnam on
Wednesday to pick up what may be the remains of 25 missing American
servicemen.
   It will be one of the largest shipments of remains given to U.S.
officials since U.S. forces withdrew from Vietnam in 1973.
   The remains are to be loaded onto a U.S. C-141 transport plane
during a simple military ceremony, then flown to U.S. Army
laboratories in Honolulu for analysis, Lt. Col. Paul Mather said on
Tuesday.
   Mather is leading the team of about 20 personnel from the Joint
Casualty Resolution Center and the Army Central Identification
Laboratory.
   Mather, head of the resolution center's office in Bangkok, said
the Vietnamese have not given him any details about the remains.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the initiative taken by
Vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just
one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing
humanitarian issue,'' a U.S. Embassy statement said.
   The shipment of remains will be the fifth since retired Gen.
John W. Vessey, acting as a special presidential envoy, reached an
agreement in Hanoi in August under which Vietnam agreed to speed up
the search for remains.
   In return, Washington sent several medical teams to explore how
private U.S. agencies could help Vietnamese, including veterans
disabled in the war against the United States. Washington doesn't
give official aid because of Vietnam's military occupation of
Cambodia.
   About 58,000 Americans lost their lives before U.S. forces
withdrew from South Vietnam in 1973. The North Vietnamese
communists won the war in a lightning offensive in April 1975.
   The last shipment of remains, on April 6, was the largest ever.
Vietnam returned 27 sets of remains it tentatively identified as
those of Americans, and three other sets which it said were those
of ethnic Asians who might possibly be among the missing Americans.
   Vietnam has returned more than 150 sets of remains that have
been confirmed as those of Americans. The lack of diplomatic
relations with the United States has hindered progress, and 1,761
Americans remain unaccounted for.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty     07-12 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Wants Review Of ABM Pact, But Soviets Have Not Replied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has proposed to the Soviet
Union a review be held soon of the 1972 treaty that restricts the
two superpowers' defenses against ballistic missiles, but Moscow
has not replied, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   The review would set the stage for a decision by President
Reagan on whether to scrap the accord, considered a main pillar of
arms control efforts and a restraint on his quest for a space-based
defense against Soviet rockets.
   The treaty states that a review conference be held every five
years. The U.S. proposal is that it be held in Geneva, beginning on
Friday or next Monday, said the U.S. official, who spoke only on
condition of anonymity.
   Since the Soviets have not replied yet, it is unlikely to be
held that quickly even if the response is favorable, the official
said.
   In the meantime, Reagan has to decide whether the Soviets'
phased-array radar station at Krasnoyarsk is a ``material breach''
of the treaty. His senior advisers discussed the issue at an
unpublicized meeting last week of the National Security Planning
Group and did not reach a consensus.
   In two reports to Congress, the president has charged the radar
stations violated restrictions imposed by the treaty. But that does
not mean he will conclude the pact should be scrapped.
   Some of his advisers are known to be suggesting Reagan try to
persuade the Soviets to level the Krasnoyarsk facility in the
interest of preserving the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   More hard-line advisers reportedly are recommending he accuse
the Soviets of a ``material breach'' of the pact and abrogate it.
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, declined on Monday
to discuss the options presented to Reagan. ``No decision has been
made,'' the spokesman said. ``The issue is under review.''
   Fitzwater said `'there are sound and valid arguments on both
sides of the question'' and that Reagan would make a decision
``before the review.''
   The treaty constrains defenses against ballistic missiles on the
theory a potential aggressor might hold back if his country faced
retaliatory devastation.
   The Soviets have denied Reagan's accusation that Krasnoyarsk is
a treaty infraction, but many American analysts who question the
president's views on other arms control issues concur in his
judgment about Krasnoyarask.
   In the meantime, the treaty limits how fast and far the United
States can go in its search for a space-based defense against
ballistic missiles that uses such sophisticated technology as laser
beams and kinetic energy.
   The program, known formally as the Strategic Defense Initiative,
is being carried out under what the Reagan administration describes
as a ``strict interpretation'' of the 1972 treaty. A broader
interpretation would provide more leeway and scrapping the treaty
would remove all legal restraints.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
