<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Drownings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Rivers Flood After Storm, Five Drown, One Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add body recovered; INSERTS two grafs two
grafs after 7th pvs, ``Killed were xxxxx, with drownings of three
boys at Colorado dam</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rescue attempt failed to save a Boy Scout
and his scout master brother from a rain-swollen river in central
Texas, and raging flood waters swept four family members to their
deaths in a creekbed in the western part of the state.
   The body of Frank Tellez, 13, was found in the Guadalupe River
on Monday afternoon, and the body of his brother, 33-year-old
Richard Tellez was found today, officials said.
   The two were in a stalled pickup truck at a low-water crossing
with Dan Knight, director of the nearby Bear Creek Boy Scout camp,
authorities said. Knight said he managed to swim to safety after a
failed rescue effort.
   The river had risen 21 feet Monday near Hunt, about 50 miles
northwest of San Antonio, destroying piers and docks at summer
camps along its banks. The river began receding Monday afternoon.
   Four members of a San Jose, Calif., family drowned Sunday when
flood waters sent their station wagon down a creekbed in Pecos
County in western Texas, authorities said.
   A fifth family member, Cipriano Enriquez Rodriquez, 47, clung to
a tree overnight, then walked to a town about four miles away to
report the accident, said Sheriff Bruce Wilson.
   Killed were Rodriquez's wife, Maria Anna Ibarra Rodriquez, 55,
their son-in-law, Pedro Navarette Ruiz, 30; and two grandchildren,
Govanna Rodriquez, 12, and Pedro Rodriquez Jr., 7.
   In western Colorado, authorities today recovered the body of a
third boy who drowned Monday after they were swept into the
Gunnison River from a ledge at the base of a dam. A fourth boy, the
twin brother of one of the drowning victims, managed to reach
safety, officials said.
   The Mesa County Sheriff's Department said the boys were crossing
the base of Roller Dam about noon Monday when one of them slipped
and fell in. The others either jumped or slipped into the river
pool in an effort to help, officials said.
   In the central Texas drowning, Knight said he got out of the
truck when it stalled and went to a nearby home to get some rope
and inner tubes. But the rope was too short, he said.
   ``They were inside and they started to panic. I went up to the
truck to pull them out,'' Knight said. ``We were holding hands and
walking past the truck when a tree came up and hit us. We floated
about a half mile down to the bend and I was still holding to them.
A log hit my head and arm pretty hard and I had to let them go.''
   Evelyn Hickey, a witness, said the effort was heroic. She said
Knight risked his life trying to save them.
   ``He had made several attempts at the boy, but the other man
pulled them down. When he couldn't help them anymore, he got out a
long way downstream,'' Mrs. Hickey said.
</TEXT>
