<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 3rdLd-Writethru a0609 07-12 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0609,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Expels U.S. Ambassador, Seven Other U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with Melton planning to depart
today, Nicaragua's vice president saying no additional measures
planned; pickup 6th pvs, ``Earlier today ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton met
today with embassy personnel after the Sandinista government
accused him and seven other American officials of inciting unrest
and ordered the diplomats to leave the country.
   President Reagan said today that in response to the expulsion
orders, he had ordered Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnerman and
seven other Sandinista representatives to leave the United States.
   ``I have told the State Department to send their ambassador and
seven comrades back to Managua,'' Reagan told reporters in
Washington.
   U.S. officials said Melton was preparing to leave the country on
a special flight later in the day after meeting with embassy
personnel. It was not clear if the seven other American diplomats
would travel with him.
   An embassy source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
ambassador was meeting with embassy personnel.
   In Brussels, Belgium, Nicaragua's vice president today said no
additional diplomatic action was planned against the United States
to protest what he called U.S. efforts to destablize the country.
   ``We don't plan now to go beyond these measures,'' Sergio
Ramirez told reporters after meeting with officials of the European
Economic Community.
   Earlier today, the State Department called the expulsion of the
Americans ``an outrage and completely without justification.'' In
Manila, Secretary of State George P. Shultz also described
Nicaragua's expulsion order an ``absolute outrage'' and said
Washington would retaliate.
   Also on Monday, the Sandinistas shut down the country's Roman
Catholic radio station, arrested an opposition politician and
closed the lone opposition newspaper, La Prensa, for 15 days.
   The moves came a day after police used tear gas and beat
protesters in breaking up one of the largest anti-government
demonstrations since the Sandinistas came to power. An estimated
10,000 people took part.
   Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto said the U.S. diplomats, who
were ordered to leave within 72 hours, had engaged in ``activities
complementary to the state terrorism the administration of U.S.
President Ronald Reagan is carrying out against Nicaragua.''
   He said he summoned Melton to his office Monday to inform him of
the order.
   D'Escoto called Melton ``a robot of the maniacal (Assistant
Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs Elliott) Abrams'' at
a news conference.
   He said U.S. Embassy officials were at Sunday's rally in
Nandaime, about 40 miles south of Managua, at the Interior
Ministery said police arrested 42 people. The Sandinistas have
repeatedly accused U.S. diplomats of trying to destablize their
government by encouraging unrest.
   In a letter to Shultz, D'Escoto's identified the U.S. diplomats
ordered expelled with Melton as John E. Hope, first secretary in
charge of economic and commercial affairs; Hugh V. Simon Jr., first
secretary; Delvin Junker and David Nolan, both second secretaries;
John S. Creamer and Aubrey A. Carlson, third secretaries and vice
consuls; and Robert Bruce Murray, an assistant attache.
   Melton, 52, arrived as ambassador in May, filling the post left
vacant since July 1987.
   ``This man has violated all acceptable standards of behavior,''
D'Escoto said. ``I told him that here you cannot come give orders
like a proconsul in Honduras and that this country is sovereign and
independent.''
   On June 6, 1983, the government expelled three U.S. diplomats
accused of taking part in an alleged plot to poison D'Escoto. The
United States responded by closing several Nicaraguan consulates in
the United States.
   In closing Radio Catolica, the Interior Ministry accused the
station of ``inciting to violence, disorder and lack of respect for
constitutional government'' in reporting about Sunday's
demonstration.
   In compliance with a regional peace plan, both the station and
La Prensa were allowed to reopen in October after being shut down
for more than a year.
   An official in the Interior Ministry press office, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said police on Monday arrested Miriam
Arguello, secretary-general of the opposition Conservative Party
for ``being the principal instigator'' of Sunday's rally.
   Witnesses said police started Sunday's fracas by pushing at the
back of the crowd. They said the crowd threw stones in response to
police tear gas. Ten police officers were injured, the official
Voice of Nicaragua said. It did not say how many protesters were
hurt.
   The Sandinistas came to power in 1979 after a civil war toppled
the rightist government of Anastasio Somoza.
   The U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras have been fighting the
government for nearly seven years. They signed a preliminary peace
accord March 23 and a tenuous cease-fire remains in effect.
   In February, Congress turned down Reagan's request for renewed
military aid to the Contras.
</TEXT>
