<2ND_LINE>AM-Tiny Horse,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ragtime The Miniature Horse Gets To Stay At Home, Court Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate panel has ruled that
Ragtime, a 29-inch high miniature horse, can live in a woman's
house and back yard, but neighbors and the city threaten a civil
suit.
   The panel of two Ventura County Superior Court judges upheld
Municipal Court Judge Herber Curtis' September 1987 decision that
Patty Fairchild could keep Ragtime on her property. Thousand Oaks
appealed that ruling.
   Curtis ruled that a city law prohibiting the keeping of two
horses on less than 20,000 square feet of property did not clearly
apply to one horse.
   ``It brought tears to my eyes,'' Mrs. Fairchild said Monday
after she learned of the decision by Melinda Johnson and Bruce
Thompson. The ruling was endorsed by Superior Court Judge Kenneth
Yegan.
   The city has since revised its ordinance, but Mrs. Fairchild
will not be re-cited, said Assistant City Attorney Shawn Mason. He
said officials will rely on a suit by the city or one brought by
the Oakbrook Homeowners Association to obtain a favorable court
ruling. The homeowners group claims the horse creates an offensive
stench and violates city rules.
   Ragtime, a 2-year-old American miniature horse, spends most of
his time outdoors at the 6,000-square-foot Fairchild home, but
occasionally goes inside to eat or sit on the family couch.
</TEXT>
