<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AlohaHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0514 07-12 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aloha Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inquiry Will Focus On Quality Assurance, Design And Maintenance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with five grafs, hearing opens, picking up 4th graf
pvs, ``In announcing xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inquiry into the reasons that a jetliner lost
part of its roof will focus on quality assurance, the design and
certification of airplane bodies, and human and other factors in
maintenance, the chairman of a fact-finding board said today.
   The National Transportation Safety Board wants to supplement
facts gathered after 18 feet of an Aloha Airlines jet's roof peeled
back on April 28, said John K. Lauber of the National
Transportation Safety Board as a four-day hearing began.
   Lauber cautioned that five-person NTSB hearing board is not
designed to determine who was at fault or who was liable for the
Boeing 737's accident.
   Officials have said the hearing will also look into the
maintenance and usable life of aging jetliners in general.
   The first witnesses scheduled to testify were from Aloha
Airlines and included the company's vice president of operations,
Thomas Derieg.
   In announcing the hearings, Lauber said an NTSB report on the
accident wouldn't be released for months but added that ``safety
recommendations to prevent a recurrence of such an accident could
be made at any time.''
   A flight attendant was swept to her death and 61 of the 94 other
people aboard Aloha Flight 243 were hurt when the cabin top peeled
away on a flight from Hilo to Honolulu, exposing the first-class
section to the open air at 24,000 feet.
   The pilot and co-pilot managed to land the crippled jet 13
minutes later in Maui although one of the two engines quit.
Aviation experts said they were amazed the aircraft could land at
all.
   The damaged plane and two other Aloha 737-200s, both later
grounded, had the highest number of landings of any Boeing
commercial jets, officials of the aircraft manufacturer said after
the accident. The damaged plane was built in 1969 and had 89,680
landings.
   The accident prompted the Federal Aviation Administration to
order inspections and repairs of older, high-cycle 737s.
   Those expected to testify included representatives of the
Federal Aviation Administration, Boeing Co., Aloha, Air
Transportation Association and British Civil Aviation Authority,
plus experts from Massachusetts Institute of Technology and State
University of New York, said Benson.
</TEXT>
