<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Kuwait     07-12 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Kuwait,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says He'll Fight for Missile Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today pledged to fight for a
proposed sale of Maverick missiles to Kuwait and said he believes
there is a chance of success.
   Posing for photographers as he prepared to meet with Crown
Prince and Prime Minister Sheik Saad Al-Abudllah Al-Sabah, Reagan
told reporters:
   ``You bet we're going to fight for it. We want very much to
complete that.''
   Asked if there was any chance of success, he replied, ``I think
so.''
   In his formal speech at a departure ceremony after their private
meeting, the president said, ``We strongly support the request for
F-18 aircraft and accompanying weapons now pending before
Congress.''
   The Senate voted last week to bar any sale of Mavericks, one of
the missile systems involved in the sale, to the Kuwaitis. This
vote is subject to action by the House and a conference committee
of the two houses.
   The Kuwaiti leader, in his response, thanked Reagan for U.S.
support and said, ``We have followed with great interest your
efforts toward peace in the Middle East and hope such efforts will
continue.''
</TEXT>
