<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreacherCharged     07-12 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preacher Charged,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Charged With Killing Woman Same Day He Preached Sermon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who led officers to the
shallow grave of a woman he allegedly shot on a Sunday before
preaching a sermon has been charged with murder, authorities said.
   The body of Lula Sims, 24, was found Monday night in woods 40
miles from Vicksburg, Warren County Sheriff Paul Barrett said. Her
family had reported her missing on July 3.
   The Rev. Jonathan Hamlin, 24, was charged with murder after he
showed up at the sheriff's office with his attorneys Monday
afternoon, Barrett said.
   ``We started talking then and by 6 p.m. he said he would take me
to the body,'' Barrett said. ``He said he knew where it was, but he
never did say that he killed her. At that point I charged him with
murder.''
   Barrett said an investigation showed Hamlin shot the woman at
her Vicksburg home early on July 3.
   Barrett said he believed the shooting occurred during an
argument and that Hamlin ``disposed of her body and then returned
to Vicksburg to preach at Sunday morning worship services.''
   Chief Deputy Otho Jones said Hamlin, married and a father of
three, became a suspect early last week when authorities learned he
was in a relationship with Sims, a divorced mother of three.
   Hamlin is pastor of Cool Spring Missionary Baptist Church and
Zion Traveler Church in Vicksburg.
   Barrett said Hamlin's case would likely go to a grand jury in
the fall. He is being held without bond in the Warren County Jail,
and no hearing has been scheduled for him to enter a plea.
   The sheriff said authorities had recovered a .22 caliber,
pearl-handled revolver believed used in the shooting.
   An autopsy has been ordered.
</TEXT>
