<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Delvalle-Miami     07-12 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delvalle-Miami,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama President in Miami For Medical Checkup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle has slipped
out of his Panamanian hiding place and was in Miami on Tuesday for
a routine heart checkup, that nation's ambassador to the United
States said.
   ``But he is definitely going pack to Panama,'' said Ambassador
Juan Sosa in Washington. ``He has a commitment to return Panama to
democracy.''
   The U.S. government still recognizes Delvalle as his nation's
chief of state despite his February overthrow by Panama's military
ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Delvalle has been in hiding in Panama with the help of the
United States since Noriega preplaced him with Manuel Solis Palma.
   Delvalle had heart bypass surgery about 10 years ago and is
supposed to have a checkup every six months, said Sosa. He said the
president is not hospitalized, and is being tested by his private
physician.
   ``He's fine,'' Sosa said.
   The ambassador said Delvalle had no plans to go to Washington to
meet with U.S. officials, but did not rule it out.
   ``He will decide that after he finishes his checkups,'' said
Sosa.
   Delvalle arrived here secretly Sunday, according to Panama's
Miami Consul Roberto Dominguez.
   He was expected to return home in a few days. For security
reasons, the officials would not say how or when Delvalle was
traveling.
   After Noriega was indicted in Florida on charges of drug
trafficking, Delvalle tried to fire him as head of the country's
military.
   But Noriega refused to go, and instead had Delvalle replaced.
Delvalle has continued to issue anti-Noriega statements from his
hiding place in Panama.
   After Delvalle's mother died in Miami last week and her body was
flown to Panama, Solis Palma offered to allow him to attend the
funeral, but the president did not show up at services.
</TEXT>
