<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Melton-Profile     07-12 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Melton-Profile,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambassador on Duty in Managua Only 2 Months Before Ouster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Career diplomat Richard Melton served only two
months as ambassador to Nicaragua before the Sandinista government
ordered him out of the country on grounds of interfering in
Nicaragua's internal affairs.
   Melton, 52, is one of the State Department's most experienced
Central America experts and is considered close to Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams. He is known around the State
Department for his low-key style.
   Before his appointment to Managua, Melton served as director of
the State Department's office of Central American affairs.
   In early 1987, he took an interim assignment as head of the U.S.
Embassy in Costa Rica after Ambassador Lewis Tambs resigned and
returned to private life.
   Melton arrived in Managua on April 12, a period of high hopes
because of a temporary cease-fire signed three weeks earlier by the
Sandinistas and the Contra rebels. He presented his credentials to
President Daniel Ortega in May.
   Melton is a 27-year veteran of the foreign service. His first
foreign assignment was as political officer in Managua in 1963
during the rule of the Somoza family dynasty. He speaks Spanish and
Portuguese.
</TEXT>
