<DOCNO> AP880712-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 8thLd-Writethru a0690 07-12 1266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0690,100</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New lead; Combines previous.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today chose Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his Democratic
running mate, duplicating a Massachusetts-Texas ticket that won the
White House for John Kennedy in 1960. ``We're going to fight for
every state in the Union and we're going all out to win,'' Bentsen
told a boisterous Boston campaign rally.
   In their joint appearance at historic Fanueil Hall, the
Massachusetts governor cited the parallels to 1960 as well as
Bentsen's strengths.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen brings to this ticket and to this nation, years
of experience, a deep committment to civil rights and equality of
opportunity that goes way back to the 1940s,'' Dukakis said.
   ``The Republicans in 1988 are about to do what they in 1960,
when they nominated an incumbent vice president,'' the Democratic
presidential nominee-in-waiting said. ``Jack Kennedy and Lyndon
Johnson beat that incumbent vice president president in 1960 and
Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen are going to beat them in 1988.
   Early this morning, Dukakis began to call the other Democrats
who had made it onto his short list of possible running mates to
tell them of the decision. But Jesse Jackson, who flew from
Cincinnati to Washington early today, apparently did not get a call
before the choice became known.
   A curt ``no'' was Jackson's reponse to a reporter's question in
Washington on whether he had talked with Dukakis. Jackson would
only say ``no comment'' on the choice of Bentsen as he headed for
private meetings with supporters.
   He and Bentsen passed through the same Washington airport
terminal within minutes of each other today without meeting, as
Bentsen headed to Boston with top Dukakis aide Paul Brountas.
   In Boston, Dukakis praised Bentsen for his work in Congress,
saying, ``He has hit a grand slam homerun because as chairman of
the Senate Finance Committee. He has personally and successfully
led the fight for welfare reform, for catastrophic health
insurance,'' as well as work on a trade bill and a plant-closing
legislation.
   Bentsen, 67, said his choice is a clear signal for the fall
campaign.
   ``The fact that he's taken a senator from Texas, a senator from
the South shows that we're going to fight for every state in the
union and we're going all out to win,'' Bentsen said.
   Even as Democrats braced for reaction from party liberal
activists and Jesse Jackson supporters, some Republicans were hard
put to criticize the choice. Senate GOP leader Bob Dole, frequently
mentioned as a possible vice president on George Bush's ticket,
said Dukakis ``couldn't have picked a better man.''
   Former Democratic National Committee Chairman John White, a
Jackson supporter from Texas, said Bentsen has ``one of the best
civil rights records in the Senate. He voted against the poll tax
when he was in the Congress back in the 50s .... He's not a
newcomer.''
   Dukakis' choice sets up a home-state showdown with the
Republicans for the big prize of 29 electoral votes, since Vice
President Bush, the GOP's presidential nominee-to-be, claims Texas
as his voting residence.
   ``It makes Texas a battleground,'' said Republican strategist
Vince Breglio.
   ``The Massachusetts-Texas combination got this country moving
again in 1960 _ and it will do the same for the nation in 1988,''
said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, whose brother tapped Lyndon Johnson in
1960 _ a reluctant decision that was instrumental in Kennedy
winning a close election.
   Bush said in an interview published today that the selection of
Bentsen won't change his claim to Texas.
   Bentsen ``doesn't worry me,'' Bush told the Boston Globe before
Bentsen's selection. ``We can carry the state.''
   Bush has lost to Bentsen once already. They squared off in a
1970 race which propelled Bentsen to the Senate for the first of
his three terms.
   Dukakis chose Bentsen at a late Monday night meeting with top
aides Brountas and Susan Estrich, just hours after Jesse Jackson
for the first time declared his hopes for the vice presidential
nomination.
   The next 24 hours will provide a highly visible stage for
Jackson to give his response to the Bentsen choice and for Dukakis
to appeal to Jackson's supporters for the unity he needs for a
peaceful convention in Atlanta next week.
   Jackson speaks to the annual convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People tonight,
following a Bush speech there earlier. On Wednesday, Dukakis and
Bentsen will appear at the NAACP meeting.
   Bush promised the NAACP that he would fight for civil rights as
president, whether or not he receives strong black support in the
fall and he praised Jackson.
   ``And I don't have to cover up the differences _ I have profound
differences with Jesse on many of these issues, but I salute him
for running the race, for being heard, and he deserves a salute
from us,'' Bush said, again drawing loud applause from the audience.
   And the reaction of other liberal Democrats to the selection of
the conservative Texan was certain to spark interest in Atlanta.
   ``Wild, absolutely wild,'' said one liberal party official of
the choice. ``I have no idea what his civil rights record is.''
   Some Jackson supporters have talked of entering his name in
nomination for vice president as a challenge to Dukakis, although
Jackson has not spoken publicly on the subject.
   Bentsen is little known outside of his home state, polls
suggest. A Gallup Poll in mid-May said 77 percent of respondents
had not heard enough about Bentsen to offer an opinion on the Texas
senator.
   Dukakis chose Bentsen off a short list of seven possible running
mates, including Jackson, Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Albert Gore Jr.
of Tennessee and Bob Graham of Florida and Reps. Richard Gephardt
of Missouri and Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   Dukakis sent Brountas, his campaign chairman, to Washington on
Monday to meet with Jackson. It was when Brountas returned to
Boston to meet with the Massachusetts governor that the decision
was made.
   ``If it was offered to me, I would accept it,'' Jackson said
after meeting with Brountas. He said it was ``self-evident'' that
he wants the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   He continued to stir his careful mixture of promise and problems
for Dukakis, saying, ``We intend to have an effective, informative
convention that would inspire our nation, unify our party and take
us to victory.''
   Democrats looking for a peaceful convention saw new signs of
hope Monday, as party chief Paul Kirk proclaimed the battles over
the party platform might be resolved without a messy fight on the
floor.
   ``I don't expect that there will be any so-called floor fights
on the platform,'' Kirk told reporters in Atlanta. ``There may be
differences of opinion. There may be agreements to disagree. All
the indications that I have are whatever differences had existed,
they are gradually being worked out.''
   Bush was already sharpening his rhetoric in preparation for a
fall campaign that continues to look like a tight battle.
   ``I am not the one who feels that the problems of agricultural
America can be solved by planting more Belgian endive,'' Bush told
a farm meeting in Washington.
   The vice president was referring to the Massachusetts governor's
suggestion in early 1987 in Iowa that crop diversification was a
solution to agricultural problems, pointing to farmers' experience
in his home state.
   A tight race was the analysis from the latest CBS News-New York
Times poll.
   It put Dukakis ahead of Bush by a 47-39 margin among 947
registered voters surveyed by telephone last week. The margin of
error was plus or minus three percentage points.
</TEXT>
