<1ST_LINE>u w AM-JusticeAgenda     07-12 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice Agenda,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Drug Initiative at Top of Justice Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Thornburgh Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Thornburgh is preparing to become the
next attorney general at a time when Justice Department and White
House officials are trying to launch a major anti-drug initiative
in Congress.
   Acting Associate Attorney General Frank Keating said this week
the Reagan administration is anxious to get legislation revamping
portions of immigration law to make it easier to deport aliens
convicted of drug trafficking and to bar the entry of drug
traffickers into the United States.
   Keating said that this is one of about 30 measures the
administration wants Congress to enact, including one authorizing
the death penalty for persons convicted of murder while engaged in
a continuing drug enterprise.
   However, congressional Democrats have yet to appoint anyone to
President Reagan's joint executive-legislative branch drug task
force, which was supposed to shape the legislation, and
congressional sources have said the Democrats don't plan to
participate.
   ``The legislative agenda is stalled,'' Keating told a news
conference. ``We think this is an issue which transcends party
lines.'' Anti-drug legislation of some kind appears inevitable in
this election year.
   Drug trafficking, as well as two other top Justice Department
priorities, organized crime and pornography, have been at the top
of Thornburgh's own agenda. His attacks on the three while U.S.
attorney for western Pennsylvania in the early 1970s led to his
appointment in 1975 by President Ford as assistant attorney general
in charge of the department's criminal division.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III may still be in office to
handle two other major items on the department's agenda. Meese said
Tuesday that his own plans ``haven't ... totally jelled yet,'' but
that he still plans to leave toward the end of July or early
August, as he said last week when he announced he was resigning.
   Meese reiterated through department spokesman Patrick Korten
that he hopes to decide whether the Detroit Free Press and the
Detroit News should be allowed to merge their advertising,
circulation and production operations under the Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   Meese also may still be in office when the department decides
whether to seek an indictment of former Philippine President
Ferdinand Marcos, who has been investigated by a number of federal
grand juries since he was ousted in February 1986. Marcos lives in
exile in Honolulu.
   However, Meese probably will be gone by the time federal
prosecutors are ready to seek indictments in the Pentagon
investigation, which is being coordinated by the U.S. attorney's
office in Alexandria, Va. The indictment are not expected until
late in the year.
   Also on the Justice Department agenda: Senate confirmation
hearings late this month for Keating, Deputy Attorney General
Harold Christensen and criminal division chief Edward Dennis. All
are currently serving in acting capacities.
   Christensen and Dennis are replacing former Deputy Attorney
General Arnold Burns and Assistant Attorney General William Weld,
the criminal division head, whose protest resignations March 29
over Meese's continued tenure brought accusations of a serious
leadership gap in the department.
   The department under Thornburgh also will be coping with the
issue of drug testing. The program would subject 1,800 Justice
employees in sensitive jobs to mandatory, random urinalysis. The
employees, many of them lawyers, are suing the department, saying
the program that could begin shortly violates their constitutional
right to due process and to protection against unreasonable
searches and seizures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
