<DOCNO> AP880712-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Roemer-Legislature     07-12 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roemer-Legislature,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Finishes First Lawmaking Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer, who vanquished
three-term Gov. Edwin Edwards with a reform campaign, finished his
first regular legislative session with many more victories than
failures, lawmakers say.
   During an 85-day session that ended late Monday, the Legislature
approved a balanced budget, a teacher pay raise, a campaign finance
reform measure and a framework to revive the state's stagnant
economy.
   ``When we started 120 days ago, this state was wounded, this
state was hurt, this state was down,'' Roemer told a joint
House-Senate meeting before adjournment. ``This is a good state and
we pulled together to try to bring it back right again.''
   ``I think overall the governor has been successful with the
programs he has been pushing. He's won far more than he has lost,''
said Sen. William Jefferson.
   When he took office March 15 after defeating Edwards last fall,
Roemer inherited an accumulated deficit of $1 billion that
threatened to bankrupt a state saddled with a corrupt image he
often described as that of a ``banana republic.''
   Edwards spent much of his third term successfully defending
himself against federal racketeering charges.
   By the close of the lawmaking session, Roemer could point to
passage of his plan for overhauling public schools and an $8
billion state budget based on conservative oil price projections in
this energy-producing state.
   On the final day of the session, lawmakers also granted the
governor continuance of the authority to make emergency budget cuts
it granted him during a special legislative session shortly after
he took office.
   However, Roemer must first obtain the blessing of a legislative
panel.
   ``I wish reductions to the budget would have been greater,''
said Rep. Allen Bradley. ``I'm not trying to be critical because we
did make substantial reductions, but not as much as I think we
could have.''
   The Legislature also approved restrictions on personal
contributions to political candidates and contributions from
political action committees. Candidates also will be required to
report all donations and expenditures.
   During his campaign, Roemer said he took no PAC money and no
contribution larger than $5,000.
   Despite the progress, Louisiana's fiscal problems are not
solved, said Sen. Don Kelly, an administration floor leader.
   ``These problems have not been cured. They won't be cured until
we have true fiscal reform,'' said Kelly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfAirlinerProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0663 07-12 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Airliner Probe, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Analysis Arrives for Probe of Airbus Incident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sub for graf 2 to state that tapes first sent to Washington
for analysis and now being returned to gulf, picks up graf 3 pvs,
``As the secrecy-shrouded, etc, 3rd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An analysis of computer tapes from the
cruiser Vincennes has been delivered to experts trying to
reconstruct the shooting down of an Iranian jetliner, U.S.
officials said Tuesday.
   The tapes were flown to the United States last week for analysis
at a Navy laboratory in Virgnia. The analysis has now been flown to
the Persian Gulf accompanied by two specialists who will present
the analysis to the six-member team of investigators.
   As the secrecy-shrouded inquiry entered its second week, the
focus was on resolving conflicts over the altitude and other
details of Iran Air's Flight 655 just before the A300 Airbus was
blown apart over the Strait of Hormuz on July 3, killing all 290
people aboard.
   U.S. military officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the computer analysis could prove crucial in determining
whether a misreading of target data by the Vincennes' sophisticated
Aegis air defense system led the ship's commander, Capt. Will C.
Rogers III, to fire at what he believed was an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   The Pentagon said the Airbus was emitting a confusing mixture of
identification signals, one typical of a commercial airliner and
another similar to that which U.S. ships had received previously
from Iranian F-14s.
   While the Vincennes initially reported the jetliner at about
9,200 feet and descending to about 7,900 feet before it was hit,
data from two other U.S. warships indicates it was nearer to 12,000
feet and either flying level or climbing, U.S. officials in
Washington were quoted as saying.
   One of the ships, the frigate Elmer Montgomery, was close by at
the time the plane was shot down and the other, the missile frigate
John H. Sides, was about 17 miles away.
   Both ships monitored the military radio messages in which, U.S.
officials said, Rogers tried repeatedly to make contact with the
jetliner, and tracked it on radar. But they did not record the
sequence of events on computer tape, said a Navy official, who
asked not to be named.
   ``Neither of those ships has anything even close to Aegis, so
what they could provide is pretty limited by comparison,'' said the
official.
   The Montgomery, a 3,800-ton frigate designed for anti-submarine
warfare, was with the Vincennes during a clash with Iranian
gunboats that occurred less than an hour before the Iran Air plane
was shot down.
   Investigators earlier interviewed officers of all three ships
under oath. The Vincennes remains anchored off Bahrain, but the
Montgomery and the John H. Sides returned to duty several days ago.
   The investigators, according to a Navy official, are trying to
collect anything that has some bearing on the disaster.
   He said this includes information that only Iran could provide,
such as whether a military plane might have played a role in the
confusion or warned the Airbus. A senior U.S. officer said last
week that any direct access to Iranian officals or data appeared
``highly doubtful.''
   U.S. officials said earlier that an Iranian scout plane, a
U.S.-built P-3 Orion, apparently was airborne and could have
monitored and relayed the Vincennes' warning messages to the
jetliner.
   Iranian pilots and others have been quoted as saying the pilot
of Flight 655 would have been so busy talking with controllers in
Bandar Abbas, Tehran and Dubai, his destination across the gulf,
that he would not necessarily have heard the cruiser's radioed
warnings on the civilian radio frequency.
   Iranian officials have not acknowledged that the plane was
transmitting a military identification signal on ``Mode 2,'' the
frequency reserved for military use, as the Americans claim.
   A U.S. source said the IFF, or identification friend or foe,
codes used by Iranian F-14s had been given to the Vincennes by the
missile cruiser Wainwright, which the Vincennes replaced on gulf
duty in late May.
   The Airbus' flight recorder also could provide important clues
to the plane's altitude and other details, but Iran's navy
commander, Rear Adm. Mohammed Hossein Malekzadegan, said on Monday
there was no truth to reports that it had been recovered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
