<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Kuwait     07-12 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Kuwait,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Promises To Work Hard For Weapons Sale To Kuwait</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan assured Kuwait's prime
minister Tuesday that he will continue to push for a proposed sale
of Maverick missiles to the Persian Gulf state.
   Posing for photographers as he met with Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheik Saad Al-Abudllah Al-Sabah, Reagan said, ``You bet
we're going to fight for it. We want very much to complete that.''
   Asked if there was any chance of success, he replied, ``I think
so.''
   Last week, the Senate voted to strip the Mavericks from a $1.8
billion arms package that included 40 F-18 fighter-bombers for the
tiny oil-rich gulf country. Critics contended the missiles could be
turned against Israel in the event of a Middle East war.
   But a senior U.S. official, briefing reporters in advance of
Sheik Saad's visit, said Israel still would retain a strategic edge
over any combination of hostile Arab countries, even if the
purchase were approved.
   The Senate voted against the Mavericks in an appropriations
amendment that is likely to be approved by Congress. That does not
kill the sale, however, since arms purchases are considered final
unless both the Senate and House reject them down within 30 days
after they are formally announced.
   In his formal remarks at a departure ceremony for the first
Kuwaiti leader to visit here in 20 years, Reagan said, ``We
strongly support the request for F-18 aircraft and accompanying
weapons now pending before Congress.''
   Skeik Saad, in his response, thanked Reagan for U.S. support.
   He said Kuwait was grateful for America's willingness to escort
its oil tankers in the war-torn Persian Gulf, and said ``we
appreciate the effective role of the United States as a superpower
in resolving issues of world peace. ....''
   A U.S. official, describing the talks Tuesday on condition of
anonymity, quoted Reagan as telling Sheik Saad, ``We will keep
pitching for F-18s.'' The official said both the United States and
Kuwait consider the Maverick missiles part of ``an integrated
package'' and want it to stay that way.
   Kuwait concluded a weapons deal with the Soviet Union over the
weekend, and U.S. officials have expressed concern about American
allies turning to other countries to obtain armaments. Saudi Arabia
agreed to buy sophisticated weaponry from Britain after a U.S.
sales package ran into congressional opposition.
   The administration officials said the Kuwaitis clearly ``have
the means'' to purchase weapons through other channels if they wish.
</TEXT>
