<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtRdp     07-12 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Seeks Water Haulers; Massachusetts Official Urges
Conservation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture and weather service officials said Tuesday this
week's rain eased the drought in Illinois but not in Ohio, while
Kentucky officials pleaded for more water-hauling trucks to help
people whose wells have run dry.
   In Massachusetts, a state environmental official said the Bay
State was not in the same condition as the drought-stricken Midwest
but noted a drop in July's rainfall and urged conservation.
   In Johnson City, Tenn., the public library canceled its annual
worm race because the critters have burrowed deeper into the soil
in search of moisture.
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened parts of the Midwest and
Southwest from Arkansas into southern and eastern Missouri and
across southern Illinois and southern Indiana. A flash flood watch
was posted for parts of north central Texas after heavy overnight
rain.
   Farmers in southern Illinois reported 24-hour rainfall ranging
from 0.2 to nearly 4 inches, but agriculture officials said more
was needed to offset dry conditions.
   ``Everything looks so good with a bit of rain over the past 24
hours,'' said Du Quoin farmer Herman Krone, whose 2,800-acre farm
President Reagan plans to visit Thursday during a tour of the
drought-ravaged area.
   However, Krone noted, almost one-third of his 1,200 acres of
corn already have been lost.
   In Ohio, the National Weather Service said scattered showers in
the last week have had virtually no impact. Conditions in
southwestern Ohio were rated extreme, the worst category listed
under the index used to measure drought severity. In the
northeastern part of the state, conditions are rated severe, the
next-highest category, the service said.
   At least 50 truckloads of hay gathered from the Carolinas and
Virginia are being shipped to Ohio on Thursday in a drive organized
by the Charlotte Motor Speedway and the National Association for
Stock Car Auto Racing.
   The Kentucky Division of Disaster and Emergency Services issued
a plea Tuesday for more water-hauling trucks to help people whose
wells have dried up. The heaviest concentration of homes in need of
water are in extreme northern Kentucky, just south of Cincinnati,
according to agency spokesman Don Armstrong.
   Rain Monday and Tuesday was the first significant rainfall
Kentucky has had since early June but was ``far from a salvation,''
according to Krit Stubblefield, a spokesman for the state
Department of Agriculture.
   The showers came too late to save corn but could buy more time
for soybeans and tobacco, he said.
   In Massachusetts, state Environmental Affairs Secretary James S.
Hoyte noted that the state's largest reservoir system was 13 feet
below its usual level and called for increased water conservation.
   ``We are taking out of the reservoir far more than nature can
replenish,'' said Hoyte, noting that rainfall for July is only
one-quarter of the average rainfall for the month.
   In northeastern Georgia, the state Department of Natural
Resources ordered the city of Toccoa to impose an immediate ban on
outdoor watering. City officials had asked for an exemption from
state-mandated water restrictions because they believed a new $3
million project to draw water from Lake Yonah had made the city
virtually ``drought-proof.''
   The Gwinnett County Commission agreed to pay a $75,000 state
fine for exceeding its June allocation of water from Lake Lanier,
but refused to enact tougher outdoor watering restrictions for
county residents. Gwinnett, northeast of Atlanta, is one of the
country's fastest-growing areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
