<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonEscape     07-12 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Escape,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Trick Guards With Dummies In Beds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCKER, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four inmates, two of them convicted
murderers, escaped a maximum-security prison after tricking guards
by putting dummies made from stuffed long johns in their cots,
authorities said Tuesday.
   Guards twice counted the dummies during overnight bed checks,
said prison spokesman David White. The inmates went to a laundry
area, slid down a homemade rope, and moved along a shallow ditch
along a fence not visible from the guard tower, he said.
   ``At the 7 a.m. count, when there wasn't any movement, they were
discovered missing,'' White said.
   It was the first escape from the Maximum Security Unit at
Tucker, in central Arkansas, about 30 miles southeast of Little
Rock.
   White said the dummies were made of white thermal underwear
stuffed with blankets. The heads were made of white stocking caps
with pieces of human hair taped to them. Two of the four worked in
the laundry room, he said.
   Sgt. Fred Brown of the Correction Department said all the
inmates were in individual cells.
   The escapees were identified as convicted murderers James Ray
Renton, 50, and Raymond Coble, 29; Tommy Winberry, 38, convicted of
two counts of attempted murder, and David Fane, 31, convicted of
aggravated robbery and other crimes.
   Coble and Winberry escaped from another state prison in November
1986, White said, but were recaptured a short time later.
   Authorities were using an airplane, dogs and a roadblock in
their search for the escaped inmates.
</TEXT>
