<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0605 07-12 0970</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0605,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Not Told of Choice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Jackson comments; pick up 7th graf pvs
bgng ``Jackson declined...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson today called the selection of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as Michael Dukakis' running mate ``a
strategic move'' and said ``I'm too controlled ... to be angry'' at
being passed over.
   Jackson said he will support the ticket nominated at the
Democratic National Convention next week but brushed off questions
about whether he will campaign enthusiastically for the party.
   ``The approach he used today was of course a matter of his own
campaign making a strategic move to solidify his organization. That
is his right to do,'' Jackson said at a news conference.
   Jackson said he first learned of the selection from reporters
who met him at an airport here this morning. He said Dukakis later
phoned him, but they did not have a lengthy discussion.
   Asked if he was angry, Jackson replied: ``No, I'm too
controlled, I'm too clear, I'm too mature to be angry. I'm focused
on what we must do to keep hope alive...''
   Jackson nearly crossed paths at the airport with Bentsen, who
was preparing to leave for Boston. The two did not meet.
   Jackson declined comment on most of the questions he was asked
by reporters as he walked to his car at Washington's National
Airport. When asked if Dukakis had informed him of a decision, he
said, ``No.''
   The night before, Jackson stated publicly for the first time
that he would accept the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket and
said he assured Dukakis' talent scout that he would be a loyal vice
president.
   But Jackson stopped short Monday night of pledging loyalty if he
is not chosen for the ticket.
   Jackson told reporters that would depend on discussions yet to
be held between him and the Massachusetts governor, the certain
nominee when Democrats convene in Atlanta next week.
   Jackson and Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas met with
reporters after a two-hour private session here Monday as Brountas
neared the end of the running mate search for Dukakis.
   Jackson, who has said repeatedly he had earned serious
consideration for the No. 2 spot, previously had demurred at saying
whether he would accept a bid. He joked to a farm group before the
job interview, ``So far Dukakis has not accepted my offer and I
have not refused his.''
   But there were no jokes after the session with Brountas,
Jackson's second interview for the job.
   ``If it was offered to me, I would accept it,'' he said. ``If
it's not offered to me, then how I respond will be based upon many
things that we've not yet discussed.''
   Jackson, who technically remains in contention for the
Democratic nomination even though Dukakis has a numerical lock on a
first-ballot victory at the convention, said, ``We intend to have
an effective, informative convention that would inspire our nation,
unify our party and take us to victory.'' He said they did not
discuss outstanding differences on the party platform.
   He said he gave Brountas ``my candid views as to the office of
the vice presidency and shared with him, when asked, what I thought
my qualifications to be and my vision of that role.''
   Brountas called it ``an excellent meeting ... very productive.
It served the purpose for which it was intended, and that is to
continue and to conclude the background check phase of the
selection process.''
   Brountas, who flew back to Boston Monday night, said, ``I plan
to review my meeting with Reverend Jackson with the governor, and
then it's up to the governor.''
   Jackson adviser John White, who took part in the meeting, told
reporters that although Brountas did not say when Dukakis would
announce his decision, ``I got the impression it was going to be
very soon ... in the next couple of days.''
   Jackson, asked to rate his chances, said, ``There is no way of
judging that.''
   Asked if the interview could have been a charade, Jackson said:
``I have no basis to challenge the intergrity of Mr. Brountas or
Gov. Dukakis. If this is just a charade, it is a great waste of
their time, at a time when time is precious.''
   Asked if he would consider having his name placed in nomination
for vice president if Dukakis chooses someone else, Jackson said,
``That's not under consideration.''
   Jackson, asked if Brountas had asked him to promise loyalty to
Dukakis, said: ``He did ask it. The answer is yes because that's
the right thing to do.'' But Jackson made clear he was only talking
about loyalty as a running mate.
   He said they talked about not only the requirements of the vice
presidency, but ``the latitude. No one, of course, would be asked
to do anything illegal or unconstitutional.''
   ``So long as there is room for serious discussion, debate and
deliberation, maturity requires that you agree to agree (and) that
you agree to disagree. ... '' said Jackson. On ``your best day,
your point of view may prevail. At your worst, your point of view
simply may be a matter of influence.
   ``I'm one to support the party. I've done that down through the
years.''
   Earlier, Jackson said, ``If I am not on the team, then the
governor must determine who the team members are and what role they
will play.'' He said he was seeking ``a partnership of equity and
shared responsibility.''
   Asked how his followers would respond if he is left off the
ticket, Jackson said: ``Let's take it one day at a time. My
constituency is tough and matured, enduring, loyal but also
responsible as it seeks its rightful place in our party's
leadership. It has earned partnership in our party.''
</TEXT>
