<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nielsens     07-12 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>July Fourth Ratings Strike Out Baseball</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fourth of July was a day for flags,
fireworks and apple pie, but not for America's favorite pastime, at
least not on TV.
   According to figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co., ABC's ``Monday
Night Baseball'' scored its lowest rating ever, a 5.9 and a 14
share on July 4. The St. Louis Cardinals played the Los Angeles
Dodgers.
   Television audience levels are traditionally low on the Fourth
of July, because many viewers are outside celebrating the holiday.
   With the movie ``Bull Durham'' a hit at the box office,
fictional baseball was big on the small screen, though. NBC reran
the theatrical film ``The Natural'' on Sunday night, and it ranked
seventh with a 15.5 rating and 29 share.
   NBC's real-life game Friday night between the New York Mets and
the Houston Astros didn't do much better than ABC's, ranking 55th
with a rating of 6.4 and 14 share. The pre-game show was the
lowest-rated show of the week.
   But NBC won the week ending July 10 with an average, prime-time
rating of 11.5 and a 23 share. CBS was second with an 8.9. ABC had
an 8.6.
   Indicative of low holiday viewing of the networks, their
combined share was down to 58, compared with the 69 that is the
average for the season-to-date.
   Bad news for the networks was good news for the Fox Broadcasting
Co., whose No. 1 show, ``America's Most Wanted,'' had a record 14
share. The rating was 6.7. The show ranked 51st, the highest
Nielsen ranking for a Fox series.
   For the week ending July 10, The ``CBS Evening News'' was first
among the network newscasts with a rating of 9.6 and a 22 share.
ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had an 8.9 and 20. After three weeks
in second place, NBC dropped back to third with an 8.3 and 19.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's estimated 88.6
million households with televisions. The share is a percentage of
sets in use.
   The highest-rated prime-time show of the week was NBC's ``Night
Court,'' with a 17.1 rating and 31 share. The rest of the top 10
were: ``A Different World,'' ``Cheers,'' ``The Cosby Show,''
``Golden Girls,'' ``L.A. Law,'' ``The Natural,'' all on NBC,
followed by ``60 Minutes'' and ``Murder, She Wrote'' on CBS, then
NBC's ``Hunter.''
   In a week with only 11 shows out of 76 that weren't reruns,
NBC's news documentary ``Guns, Guns Guns'' was ranked 21st with a
rating of 11.1 and a 20 share.
   ABC repeated its documentary ``Drugs: A Plague Upon the Land''
on Saturday and landed in 41st place with a rating of 8.3 and a 17
share. The documentary was repeated to set the stage for a
follow-up program on Monday.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Rags to Riches,''
``Kane & Abel, Part 2,'' ``New York vs. Houston,'' ``The
Pretenders,'' ``High Mountain Rangers,'' ``St. Louis vs. Los
Angeles,'' ``Hothouse,'' ``Spot Marks the X, Part 2,''
``Supercarrier'' and NBC's baseball pre-game show.
</TEXT>
