<DOCNO> AP880712-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Cardenas     07-12 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Cardenas,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas: Famous Name, Charismatic Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Mexico-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although he may lose the election, opposition
candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas appears to have secured a position as
the rallying point for the discontent with the party that has ruled
Mexico for 59 years.
   Whether he won the presidential election or not is still a
matter of heated debate. He says he did, the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, says he didn't.
   Privately, top PRI officials admit Cardenas won the Federal
District, the core of the sprawling Mexico City metropolitan area,
and three of Mexico's 31 states.
   Even those victories would be a stunning blow to the PRI, which
has won every presidential race since its founding in 1929 with at
least 70 percent of the vote, and never has lost a senate or
gubernatorial race.
   Cardenas claimed Monday he won 39 percent of the vote nationwide
to PRI candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari's 35 percent.
   After a week's delay and opposition charges of fraud, the
government has only provided partial returns on the race for the
lower house of Congress.
   Figures released Tuesday by the PRI say Salinas had 53.59
percent of the votes counted. Cardenas was second with 26.08
percent, and Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National
Action Party followed with 16.04 percent.
   Even these figures, which the opposition disputes, would be an
astonishing feat for Cardenas, a candidate who in December started
to build his predominantly leftist coalition from a tiny base.
   His campaign was considered unlikely to shake the foundations of
power, and ruling politicians dismissed him as a candidate of
``nostalgia'' who was trading on his famous name.
   Through it all, the charismatic candidate never lost his
composure.
   Before hundreds of thousands of adoring supporters on the
campaign trail, in the steamy battle over vote fraud, at
middle-of-the-night news conferences in the days-long wait for the
returns, he was always calm, always reasonable.
   While Clouthier barreled down the campaign trail, blustering
about civil disobedience, Cardenas quietly counseled restraint and
spoke of using the force of law.
   Cardenas, 54, spent the day before the election in the central
state of Michoacan, where he once was the governing PRI's governor.
   He wasn't basking in the warmth accorded a favorite son. He was
mourning his old friend and political strategist, Francisco Xavier
Ovando, gunned down while on the way home from a political strategy
session.
   ``Xavier has fallen because he was fighting for Mexico to have a
true and authentic democracy,'' Cardenas said. ``He died because he
dreamed of a better, an independent and a free Mexico.''
   That moment was like a snapshot capturing the campaign and the
candidate.
   Cardenas was criticized for wanting to turn the clock back to
1910, when the Mexican Revolution started with the promise of a
better life, or to 1938, when his father, Mexico's revered 20th
century president, nationalized Mexico's oil and handed the young
republic its pride.
   But the Cardenas message wasn't about the nuts and bolts of
governing. It was visceral: He became a focal point of discontent
with a system that seemed calcified by nearly 60 years of
single-party rule.
   It was an ironic role for politician who once seemed to be the
ultimate product of a system his father, the late President Lazaro
Cardenas, helped create.
   Cardenas flourished in the PRI. He was its governor in Michoacan
and also a senator. The break started last year when Cardenas
seemed to sense the growing force of a cold wind of disfavor that
was about to blast the PRI.
   Calling his movement the Democratic Current, he told the party
to hold a presidential primary. The traditionalists in the party
refused and Cardenas defected, forming a left-of-center coalition,
the National Democratic Front.
   When he decided to run for president he campaigned virtually
without a critical forum _ television. TV in Mexico is
government-controlled or pro-government.
   But as he traveled the nation, he gathered larger and larger
crowds, winning the support of peasants, students, the struggling
middle class, intellectuals and oil workers.
   About a month before the election, he did what was considered
impossible _ he unified the left. The candidate of the Mexican
Socialist Party, the largest organized leftist force, dropped out
and endorsed Cardenas.
   No one knows if that political unity will survive once the
campaign passions cool. But Cardenas now appears to command a
popular force the governing party cannot ignore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
