<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Chappell     07-12 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Chappell,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Cause Seeks Ethics Probe of Lawmaker</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause called Tuesday on the House
ethics committee to investigate reported ties by Rep. Bill
Chappell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, to military contractors.
   The request came in a letter to the panel from Fred Wertheimer,
president of Common Cause, the self-described citizens' lobby.
   Wertheimer said ``serious questions'' were raised by news
reports that a company headed by two Washington representatives of
defense contractors, had intervened in a Florida foreclosure case
four years ago to relieve Chappell and his companies of debts
connected with an Ocala, Fla., health club.
   Wertheimer said the reports raise questions about whether
Chappell's actions appeared to violate House rules prohibiting a
conflict of interest.
   John Davidson, a spokesman for the ethics committee, declined to
say if the request had been received and when, or if, the panel
would act.
   Chappell has strongly denied any wrongdoing.
   He is one of five House members whose names have been linked to
the ongoing Pentagon bribery investigation. Federal investigators
have said no members of Congress are a target of the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
