<DOCNO> AP880712-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Echoesof1960     07-12 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Echoes of 1960,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis-Bentsen Ticket Recalls Kennedy-Johnson Match in 1960</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time a Massachusetts Democrat invited
a Texan to be his running mate, he didn't think the offer would be
accepted. And after Lyndon Johnson took him up on it, a shocked
John F. Kennedy asked his brother, ``Now what do we do?''
   That set Kennedy and his brother Robert, his campaign manager
and closest confidant in that 1960 election, to agonizing over how
to uninvite the proud, powerful and feared Senate majority leader.
   In the end, Kennedy of Massachusetts ran with Johnson of Texas
and narrowly won the 1960 election. Like every Democrat who won the
presidency since Texas became a state, he had the votes from the
Lone Star State.
   Twenty-eight years later, in a lengthy and more deliberative
process, Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the putative
presidential nominee of the Democratic Party once again has turned
to a Texan, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, to be his vice president.
   ``Jack Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson beat that incumbent vice
president in 1960, and Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen are going to
beat them in 1988,'' Dukakis said as he made known his choice of a
running mate.
   Echoed Bentsen: ``The Massachusetts and the Texas axis was good
for the country and good for the Democratic Party in 1960 and it's
going to be a real winner in November of 1988.''
   Just as it did in 1960, Texas' rich harvest of electoral votes
and the advantage of having a southerner on the ticket played a
part in Dukakis' decision.
   John F. Kennedy, according to many accounts, gave no thought at
all during his campaign for the nomination as to who would run with
him. But after the delegates in the Los Angeles convention chose
him, Kennedy had only a few hours to make his pick. He told his
brother ``how terrible it was that he only had 24 hours to select a
vice president.''
   On returning to the rented apartment where he was staying,
Kennedy found ``the warmest and most cordial telegram of
congratulations'' from Johnson, according to Theodore White, in his
classic ``The Making of the President 1960.''
   ``Until that moment Kennedy had accepted at face value Johnson's
statement that he would never, never, never, trade his senatorial
vote for the vice presidential gavel,'' White wrote.
   Robert Kennedy said his brother told him he would offer the
nomination to Johnson first thing the next morning. John Kennedy
went to see the senator.
   ``I was in his room when he came back,'' Robert said in a 1965
interview with historian Arthur Schlesinger. ``And he said, `You
just won't believe it.'
   ``I said, `What?'
   ``And he said, `He wants it.'
   ``And I said, `Oh, my God!'
   ``He said, `Now what do we do?'''
   ``We spent the rest of the day _ and we both promised each other
that we'd never tell what happened ... alternating between thinking
it was good and thinking that it wasn't good that he'd offered him
the vice presidency and how he could get out of it,'' Robert
Kennedy said.
   ``One of the major factors ultimately that persuaded him that he
should take him was the fact that he would be so mean as majority
leader that it was much better having him as vice president, where
you could control him, than to have him as majority leader.
Particularly after you had offered him the job, then it would have
been disastrous to have that affront and withdraw it.''
   The two Kennedys decided to try and have Johnson take himself
out. Robert said he made two trips to Johnson's hotel room. On the
first, he said, Johnson's close friend, House Speaker Sam Rayburn,
was there and Kennedy only tried to feel Johnson out. But, like
everything else about that time, there are different versions of
that meeting.
   Phil Graham, the late publisher of the Washington Post who was
close to Johnson, recalled these events in a famous memorandum that
Dukakis recently studied during his search for a vice president.
   ``LBJ seemed about to jump out of his skin,'' Graham wrote of
the first Lyndon-Bobby meeting. ``He shouted at me that Bobby
Kennedy had just come in and told Rayburn and him that there was
such opposition and that Lyndon should withdraw for the sake of the
party.''
   On the second visit, Robert Kennedy said, he and Johnson were
alone. It was 2:30 p.m. on the last day of the convention.
   Robert said he conveyed two thoughts he'd worked out with his
brother. That there would be an unpleasant fight by labor leaders
if Johnson were on the ticket and that John Kennedy wanted him to
play an important role, running the party, and thereby build the
machinery he could use to run for president in 1968.
   ``I don't know whether it was just an act or anything,'' Kennedy
told Schlesinger. ``But he just shook, and tears came into his
eyes, and he said, `I want to be vice president, and if the
president will have me, I'll join with him in making a fight for
it.'
   ``I said, `well, that's fine. He wants you to be vice president
if you want to be vice president, we want you to know.'''
   At this point, too, there are conflicting accounts. Bobby
remembered returning to his brother who said he had been advised
that vaccilation on the vice president was disastrous and that he
would announce Johnson as the choice.
   James Rowe, a New Deal lawyer in Johnson's camp recalled that at
the end of the first meeting Graham called John Kennedy who told
him: ``Bobby's not up to date, I've already announced that Johnson
is the candidate.'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
