<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Leaks 1stLd-Writethru a0735 07-12 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Leaks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735, 630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS ``affidavit'' grafs 14-15 ``Some of'' etc.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen lawyers for people and companies in
the defense procurement probe are demanding that the Justice
Department launch an investigation into the sources of leaks to the
press.
   A department official said Tuesday it is ``too early'' to decide
whether to do so.
   ``We are writing to you to request that you commence an
investigation and take appropriate remedial action to deal with the
virtual flood of leaks by Department of Justice employees involved
in or privy to the details of the investigation,'' the attorneys
said in their unusual letter. One lawyer called the joint effort
``extraordinary.''
   The letter, dated July 8 and publicly released Tuesday, was
addressed to Michael E. Shaheen Jr., head of the Justice
Department's Office of Professional Responsibility. It complained
that ``frequency and substance of these `leaks' is ...
unprecedented.''
   Shaheen, who has responsibility for investigating ethics cases
involving Justice employees, refused to comment. John Russell, a
department spokesman, said it was ``too early to determine that we
will undertake an investigation.''
   Several of the defense counsels are former assistant U.S.
attorneys, obviously taking advantage of their knowledge of
internal Justice Department procedures to stop what they feel is a
case of government officials trying their case in the newspapers
and on television.
   Justice investigators have ``knowingly ensured dissemination of
confidential information and sensationalization of the entire
investigation'' by leaking information, the letter said.
   Such leaks create ``an environment in which our clients cannot
be dispassionately investigated...,'' they said.
   They suggested that Shaheen focus on possible violation of seven
statutes, regulations or rules barring Justice employees from
revealing unauthorized material. One law carries a fine of up to
$1,000 and imprisonment of a year for divulging certain material.
Other penalties can include a letter of censure or dismissal.
   Investigations into leaks are not unusual, Russell said. ``At
one time, we have anywhere from 10 to 15 leak investigations going
on,'' he said. Some of those include improper revelations of
classified material.
   Henry E. Hudson, the U.S. attorney in Alexandria, Va., who is
coordinating the massive probe, also has expressed concern about
leaks in the case, which was brought to public attention on June
14. FBI agents conducted surprise searches on more than three dozen
homes and offices in 12 states on that day.
   No one has been charged in the investigation of the Pentagon's
$150 billion-a-year procurement business. Indictments are not
expected until the end of the year, though grand jury subpoenas
have been issued for mid-July.
   The allegations are that defense consultants, often former
military officers, bribed Pentagon officials to obtain secret
information that gave their employers an edge in obtaining
contracts .
   Some of the information in the case has come from search
warrants used by the FBI in Alexandria, Va., and St. Louis, Mo., as
well as from one affidavit released in Dallas, Texas. The
affidavit, which contained information gathered by telephone
wiretaps, gave a detailed account of the investigators' case.
   Hudson has argued that the affidavits should remain under seal
because defense attorneys could take advantage of gaps in the
government's knowledge if the papers are open to public inspection.
Several news organizations around the country have filed lawsuits
challenging the sealing orders.
   The defense attorneys also complained that members of Congress
have ``quite predictably'' gone public with information provided by
Justice Department officials.
   Among the lawyers signing the letter are E. Lawrence Barcella
Jr., and Robert Plotkin, who represent defense consultant Melvyn
Paisley, and Michael Schatzow, whose client is Pentagon official
James Gaines. Paisley, a former top Navy official, has been
identified as a key player in the investigation; Gaines, a
long-time friend of Paisley's since their days at the Boeing Co.,
worked as a Navy procurement official.
</TEXT>
