<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam     07-12 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hanoi Talks Set on Emigration of pro-American Vietnamese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials will meet
Thursday and Friday in Hanoi to plan the move to the United States
of thousands of Vietnamese detained after the Indochina War because
of their American connections, it was announced Tuesday.
   The two governments have agreed to the talks ``to discuss the
resettlement in the United States of Vietnamese re-education camp
detainees who wish to come,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley told reporters.
   ``The great majority of current and former re-education camp
detainees were incarcerated because of their close association with
the United States and as allies during the war,'' Mrs. Oakley told
reporters. ``For this compelling humanitarian reason, we have
repeatedly affirmed our strong humanitarian desire to resettle
those who wish in the United States as soon as possible.''
   Robert L. Sunseth, senior deputy assistant secretary of state
for refugee programs, will head the U.S. delegation to Hanoi, she
said.
   The State Department has estimated that 900,000 former employees
of the U.S. government in South Vietnam and officials of the
defeated Saigon government were sent to political re-education
camps after the fall of Saigon and unification of the country in
1975.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach told reporters a
month ago at U.N. headquarters in New York the re-education camp
migrants will be allowed to depart on a guarantee that they do not
engage in activities hostile to the Hanoi government. He predicted
a flow of tens of thousands.
   U.S. officials also have said the United States plans to admit
29,500 people this year from the continuing flow of refugees
managing to flee Vietnam by small boat to nearby Southeast Asian
countries.
</TEXT>
