<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatalFire     07-12 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Fire,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Killed In Chicago Apartment Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire gutted half a small apartment building early
Tuesday, killing seven people, including three children, officials
said.
   The Fire Department was treating the blaze, the city's deadliest
this year, as arson although authorities had not determined the
cause, spokesman Scott LaGreca said.
   Firefighters confronted a wall of flames at the building, which
was home to about 30 people, officials said.
   ``It was just pure orange _ a full flame,'' firefighter Al Zaja
said. ``The people had no chance of getting out.''
   ``You could see the blaze for five or six blocks,'' said David
Collins, 23, a motorists who stopped to help evacuate residents.
   Collins said he kicked in two doors and carried a man from the
rear, second-floor apartment, but was unable to rescue the others.
   ``I heard children hollering on the third floor,'' he said. ``I
went to go up, but the blaze started getting really heavy, and I
started choking so I ran out.''
   Most of the residents were sleeping when the fire broke out at
about 12:30 a.m., fire officials said. The blaze was out by 2 a.m.,
they said.
   The victims were found on the floor and couches of the
second-and third-floor rear units of the three-story building,
firefighter Pat Blake said.
   Three children, ages 10, 12 and 13, were among the victims, said
fire department spokesman Tom Sheppard.
   ``Everybody was just trying to get everybody else out, but the
fire spread too quick,'' said Kent Daniels, 23, who lived in the
rear apartment on the first floor. Daniels' aunt and cousin died in
the fire, he said.
   Stephen Mallory, 16, said his grandparents and three of their
grandchildren died in the third-floor apartment. Mallory wasn't in
the building at the time.
   Firefighters found an empty gasoline can behind the house, but
police investigators don't know if it was used to set the blaze,
police Sgt. Darryl Collins said.
   The sergeant said the building had smoke detectors but it wasn't
clear if they were functioning.
</TEXT>
