<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmishInmate     07-12 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amish Inmate,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Amish Man Exempted From Wearing Orange Jump Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amish man jailed for refusing to
display an orange slow-moving-vehicle sign on his horse-drawn buggy
was exempted from wearing the orange jump suit normally worn by
inmates.
   Gideon Hershberger, 62, served seven days in the Fillmore County
Jail for contempt of court and was released Tuesday.
   Hershberger and other Amish contend that displaying the orange
signs is against their religion.
   ``I'd say it's the most I can do,'' he said. ``I don't want to
be stubborn, but I will continue without the sign. What else can I
do?''
   County Sheriff Don Gudmundson allowed Hershberger to wear his
blue denim pants, deep blue cotton shirt and navy blue suspenders.
   District Court Judge Margaret Shaw Johnson ruled earlier this
month that public safety overrides the Amish resistance to the
orange triangle.
   ``Religion is not a defense in this case,'' she said.
   Hershberger said the Amish prefer to trust God over worldly
symbols, and they want to live the way their forefathers lived.
   Some Amish use orange triangles. But others use a black triangle
with a white outline and some of the older, more conservative
members like Hershberger use no sign at all. They prefer to outline
their buggies with white reflective tape.
   Hershberger spent his jail time working in a woodworking shop
and reading.
   Gudmundson is sympathetic to Hershberger and other Amish
violators.
   ``They say they don't want to create problems for me or the
state, which they are,'' he said. ``But this is something I admire
them for, even though I can't agree with it.''
</TEXT>
