<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0732 07-12 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Campaign Manager Says Democrats Threw Away Veep Choice</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, `After all,' with Bush
comment.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Atwater, Republican George Bush's campaign
manager, said Tuesday that Democrats have ``thrown away the vice
presidential selection'' with Michael Dukakis' choice of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen as his running mate.
   ``After all is said and done, they're not going to win Texas,''
Atwater said in an interview. ``People in Texas want a president,
not a vice president. And George Bush is the man they want.''
   Bush, en route to baseball's All-Star game in Cincinnati, told
reporters, ``That's interesting. That's what I think about it,''
when asked about the Bentsen selection.
   Atwater said he was delighted with the choice of Bentsen, saying
``If I were selecting the nominee, I couldn't have done better
myself.''
   He claimed that nearly any of the other prominent Democrats
mentioned as a possible vice president, including Sens. John Glenn
of Ohio and Albert Gore of Tennessee as well as Jesse Jackson,
would have posed a greater challenge to the GOP ticket this fall.
   ``The Democrats have thrown away the vice presidential selection
as far as I'm concerned ... He will help some in Texas, but only
enough to get them (Democrats) to spend a whole bunch of time and
money down there that they're going to end up squandering away.''
   Bush's campaign manager said that the selection of Bentsen may
give Democrats a surge in the polls in Texas, ``but that will
settle down and after all is said and done, George Bush is going to
win Texas.''
   He dismissed comparisons to the 1960 Democratic ticket that also
had a Massachusetts-Texas breakdown with President John F. Kennedy
and Lyndon B. Johnson.
   ``If it was like 1960, then we'll win handily, because the South
in 1960 was solidly for Nixon. Now the South is going to be solidly
for Bush,'' Atwater said.
   ``Democrats will be saying that ad nauseam,'' Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill., national co-chairwoman of the Bush campaign, said in
reference to the comparison of the two tickets.
   ``But it's a little different running for president and vice
president than running for the Senate. We're talking about
different sets of experiences. His (Bentsen's) experience has been
in finance. You don't think of him as being strong either in terms
of social issues or in terms of foreign policy, frankly,'' Mrs.
Martin sid.
   Bentsen defeated Bush in a 1970 Senate race, but Bush aides
insisted that fact would not trouble the certain 1988 GOP
presidential nominee.
   Bush himself did not mention the selection of Bentsen in a
morning speech to a convention of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
   Bush had said he wanted to wait to see whom the Democrats would
pick for the No. 2 spot on their ticket before giving thought to a
running mate. Atwater said Bush still intends to delay his own
choice of a running mate until the Republican National Convention
in August.
   But, Mrs. Martin said, the selection of Bentsen does not make
much difference in terms of the dynamics for the GOP ticket.
   ``The one thing it does is it allows George Bush the same
freedom he had yesterday. I don't think the selection of Bentsen,
without diminishing the senator at all, is one that says now Bush
has to do x, y or z,'' she said.
   Mrs. Martin said that Bentsen was not that well known outside
Washington or Texas, other than being identified as ``kind of big
oil ... and breakfasts, breakfasts at Tiffany's sort-of-thing,'' a
reference to Bentsen's short-lived effort to organize breakfasts
with lobbyists who were to pay $10,000 each.
   ``I still think George Bush will carry Texas,'' Mrs. Martin
said. ``You never underestimate an opponent. On the other hand, I
suspect no one's in raging fear either.''
</TEXT>
