<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ObeseJourney     07-12 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obese Journey,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dick Gregory to Help Illinois Man Lose Weight</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ST1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Gregory appeared Tuesday with his latest
recruit, a 701-pound man from Illinois who is determined to become
``a normal person again.''
   ``America is the most obese nation in the world,'' Gregory said
at a news conference. ``It is well established as the No. 1
nutrition-related problem in our nation.''
   Gregory, during a brief stopover at Lambert Airport, described
the regimen he will prescribe for Steve Nellis, of Hurst, Ill., for
the next two years. It will include a diet of raw fruits and
vegetables.
   From St. Louis, the two men flew to New Jersey, where Nellis
will undergo a medical evaluation. Then he will fly to another
location, possibly in Florida, for the major portion of his
weight-loss program, which could last up to two years.
   Nellis, a former school bus driver, said his weight, although
well above normal since early childhood, was only 300 pounds when
he married his wife 10 years ago.
   ``I want to be able to go to work,'' Nellis said of his goal to
lose 500 pounds. ``I want to be able to be a better husband to my
wife and just to be a normal person.''
   More than a dozen people whose weight reductions have been
supervised by Gregory in recent years include Walter Hudson, a
Hempstead, N.Y., man whose case received wide attention last fall.
   Gregory came to Hudson's aid when Hudson, who weighed 1,200
pounds, became wedged in the door of his home. Hudson showed steady
improvement under the routine that Gregory supervised but was
forced to drop out because of his fear of leaving his home to go to
a center.
   ``Ten to 13 percent of our children are overweight, and we lose
more people to obesity-related problems than we do to drugs,'' he
said. ``We need a national goal of weight management for life.''
</TEXT>
