<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoofCollapse     07-12 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roof Collapse,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy May Face Kidney Dysfunction as Result of Brownsville Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boy trapped for 20 hours under the
rubble of a collapsed department store may lose use of his kidneys,
doctors said.
   University of Texas Medical Branch physicians treating
9-year-old Jorge Mena of Merida, Mexico, said toxins from dead
muscle tissue apparently destroyed his body's ability to cleanse
his blood.
   However, doctors said Jorge's spunk may help him through the
critical first days of what may be a months-long stay at the
hospital.
   ``He's mad, and he's scared,'' said Jason Calhoun, an orthopedic
surgeon.
   Mena and a cousin who lost a leg in the accident in Brownsville
last week are receiving high-pressure oxygen treatments. Both are
in critical condition, officials said.
   ``He complains the whole time he is in the (hyperbaric)
chamber,'' said Dr. John Mader, who is overseeing Mena's treatment
at UTMB's Marine Biomedical Institute.
   ``But that's good,'' Mader said, ``because he's a fighter, and
that is what it takes.''
   Jorge's mother remained hospitalized in Brownsville and a
15-year-old sister, Mya, died in the accident, authorities said.
The boy's father, who like his son speaks no English, lies outside
the chamber window so he can look at the boy.
   ``They communicate over the telephone,'' Mader said. ``The
father gives the boy a lot of support. Otherwise, he'd be
unmanageable.''
   Jorge's cousin, Yvette Lire, 14, of Brownsville, has shown some
improvement since her right leg was amputated below the knee,
Calhoun said.
   Yvette's sister, Paloma, 12, died in the accident.
   The Amigo Store collapsed during heavy rain Friday, killing 14
people and injuring at least 47 others. Investigators have not
determined the cause.
</TEXT>
