<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BaseClosings     07-12 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Mechanism to Close Unneeded Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, trying to solve one of its toughest
political issues, voted 374-39 Tuesday to give the Pentagon a
chance to save money by shutting down unneeded military bases.
   The chamber passed a complicated plan that involves having an
independent commission decide which bases to close.
   ``For too many years, obsolete military bases have been treated
as sacred cows and the country cannot afford this anymore,'' Rep.
Chalmers Wylie, R-Ohio, told his colleagues. ``The time has come
for Congress to stiffen its backbone.''
   The Defense Department estimates that between $2 billion and $5
billion a year can be saved if the military is allowed to close
installations it says are obsolete.
   But bases mean jobs and since 1977 Congress has enacted a stiff
and complex series of laws that have prevented the Pentagon from
shutting down any of the 3,800 military installations in the
continental United States.
   The plan approved Tuesday calls for a nine-member commission,
which will makes its recommendations to President Reagan by next
Dec. 31. The president would then have until Jan. 16, four days
before leaving office, to either accept or reject the entire list.
He could not approve a partial list.
   Congress could block the closures by a majority vote in both the
House and Senate.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci backs the plan and has
already appointed a nine-member commission, which has been meeting
for the past month.
   The commission will also study the 1,900 military installations
maintained by the United States in foreign nations, but will not
have authority to recommend closures there.
   In approving the plan, the House rejected a different
base-closing proposal, which would have retained a few of the
current restrictions. The version approved Tuesday was first
adopted on a 223-186 vote shortly before the final passage.
   The House action sends the bill to a House-Senate conference
committee to resolve differences with a Senate-passed version. The
Senate measure was approved as an amendment to a Pentagon budget
bill, but was later dropped out of that legislation.
   In the decades after World War II, when the nation was winding
down from its large military structure, the Pentagon was usually
allowed to what it wanted on the issue, with the exception of a
handful of bases protected by key members. Between 1961 and 1977,
the Pentagon shut down 3,600 installations.
   But in 1975, the Air Force proposed shutting down Loring Air
Force Base in northern Maine. That state's legislators blocked the
move by requiring lengthy _ and costly _ environmental impact
studies for the Loring closure and all future closings.
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, chief sponsor of the base-closing
plan, said the House action ``will go a long way toward cutting fat
instead of muscle from our national defense.''
   Armey's plan was rejected a year ago, 199-192, but he offered
the proposal again because he argued that a lame-duck
administration might be willing to approve the unpopular cuts.
   Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., urged approval of the bill because he
said ``it's time to cut the pork out of the budget process ... it's
the right thing for the country.''
   Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., agreed, saying: ``This whole program of
bases is not a welfare program ... it's not an economic program. We
should have bases for one reason and one reason only _ because they
serve military needs.''
   In working through the bill, the House voted down, on a voice
vote, a proposed amendment that would have required the closure of
foreign bases before U.S. bases are shut down.
   The chamber also rejected, on another voice vote, a move that
would have added four members of Congress to the commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
