<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraArms     07-12 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Blasts Arms Indictment as Coverup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defendant in a Contra arms-smuggling indictment
blasted the charges against him Tuesday as a whitewash aimed at
covering up illegal activities of Oliver North and the Reagan
administration.
   Jack Terrell, a one-time mercenary who turned against the U.S.
Contra policy and then cooperated with investigators, said he was
informed Tuesday he has been charged in a Fort Lauderdale
indictment still sealed by the U.S. attorney's office here.
   The indictment handed up last month is believed to accuse a
small number of men with violating the U.S. Neutrality Act by
conspiring to aid the Contras to overthrow the Nicaraguan
government.
   ``I have some news for this administration,'' Terrell said in a
statement released in Washington. ``I won't take the fall for Rob
Owen, Ollie North or Ronald Reagan.''
   Terrell said the indictments were returned only because Congress
got wind that Miami's then-U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner was trying to
stop the investigation at the behest of Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   Congress investigated charges that the probe was sidetracked,
but did not reach any conclusion.
   ``Clearly, the only reason why the (U.S.) attorney's office
sought these indictments is to protect itself,'' said Terrell.
Kellner ``couldn't admit that his investigation was a farce, and
that he and his staff had participated in a coverup.''
   He said he had been cooperating with the U.S. attorney for two
years, giving information about high-level involvement in the
illegal supply network, but wound up being one of the few indicted.
   ``That's what I call shooting the messenger,'' he said.
   Kellner has quit the U.S. Attorney's office here and will be
practicing law in Washington. But he has previously denied charges
that he stonewalled the investigation, and said a congressional
committee that took testimony from prosecutors in his office failed
to find evidence that he slowed the investigation at Meese's
request.
   Terrell, who most recently worked for a liberal policy group in
Washington, became a vocal opponent of U.S. policy in Central
America. North eventually targeted him for his anti-Contra
activities, according to notes released during the Iran-Contra
affair.
   Until he changed his mind on aid to the Contras, Terrell aided
Civilian Materiel Assistance in its efforts to help the Nicaraguan
rebels.
   CMA's head Tom Posey has previously said he expects to be
indicted along with Terrell, and has also said he was working to
aid the Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
