<DOCNO> AP880712-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen-Hometown     07-12 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Hometown,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lloyd Bentsen's Family A Powerful Force In Home Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MISSION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen Jr.'s selection as the
Democratic vice presidential nominee sent local pride surging in
his hometown 10 miles from the Mexican border, where the family
name stands for wealth and power.
   ``Everybody knows the Bentsens in South Texas, just like the du
Ponts or Kennedys (in New England),'' said Justo Gonzalez, who owns
a barber shop in downtown Mission.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the certain Democratic
presidential nominee, announced in Boston on Tuesday that he had
designated Bentsen as his running mate.
   Gonzalez and other local boosters said the nomination will bring
recognition to the Lower Rio Grande Valley.
   ``It will put us on the map, and as chambers of commerce, we are
always interested in that sort of notoriety,'' said Benny
Benavides, executive vice president of the Mission Chamber of
Commerce.
   The city of 25,000 in Hidalgo County was settled by Europeans in
1824, when the Roman Catholic Oblate Fathers began occupying an
area three miles south of the current city. Its name comes from a
mission the Oblates later built there.
   It is the center of the subtropical Texas citrus producing area,
and nearly surrounded by grapefruit groves and other farming
operations.
   Mobile home and recreational vehicle parks mix dot the
landscape, and retirees from the Midwest and Canada inflate
Mission's population during the winter to more than 50,000.
   The Lower Rio Grande Valley, actually a delta of the Rio Grande,
also has some of the poorest residents of the United States. Some
local officials were angered during a campaign swing by Jesse
Jackson, when the candidate described an unincorporated rural
subdivision as a ``little Ethiopia.''
   Mission's population is about 85 percent Mexican American, a
figure that probably would be higher without the real estate
promotions and business ventures of Lloyd Bentsen Sr.
   The elder Bentsen at age 94 still oversees about 42,000 acres of
farms and six ranches scattered over South Texas, an empire he
started carving out of the brush country in 1920.
   ``My children all grew up learning how to work,'' Bentsen Sr.
said Tuesday.
   Lloyd Jr., like his two younger brothers and one sister, worked
``mostly in the nurseries and of course spraying the orchards, and
working on the ranches and working cattle, the whole thing,'' the
proud father said.
   ``Lloyd don't think he's a conservative; he thinks he's a
moderate,'' Bentsen said as geese swam by on the 27-acre lake
behind his family's sprawling ranch house south of Mission.
   ``I shouldn't show this to anyone. It makes the
environmentalists mad,'' Bentsen said, opening the door to a trophy
room that includes the skins of a tiger, polar bears, brown bears
and grizzlies, along with a bison's head and other game.
   ``I don't know that much about Dukakis. What I hear is he's
probably more liberal in his viewpoints than Lloyd is,'' the elder
Bentsen said. ``It will help to balance the ticket.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
