<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0738 07-12 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Presidential Candidate, Supporters Scuffle with Guards</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-12 UPDATE with Clouthier and loyalists
demonstrating, other. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Those results ... with
minor editing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition presidential candidate Manuel J.
Clouthier and about 150 supporters scuffled with presidential
guards on Tuesday in the heart of Mexico City, then staged a sit-in
to protest alleged electoral fraud.
   As President Miguel de la Madrid arrived at the Fine Arts Palace
for a speech to about 2,500 lawyers, Clouthier stood up, carrying a
sign that read, ``Mr. President, keep your word.'' The sit-in went
on while de la Madrid spoke inside.
   Results from last Wednesday's elections released by the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party showed its lowest
proportion of the vote since its founding 59 years ago. The party,
known by its Spanish initials PRI, generally wins the presidency
with at least 70 percent of the vote.
   The figures indicated, however, that this time the PRI will take
the presidency by only slightly more than 50 percent of the vote
and will pay little heed to opposition protests of election fraud.
   The white-bearded, heavy-set Clouthier, a businessman and
rancher, is the candidate of the conservative National Action
Party. He was running third in unofficial, partial returns from
last Wednesday's elections.
   Clouthier and the other top opposition candidate, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front, claim the
government is rigging the vote count in favor of the PRI's Carlos
Salinas de Gortari.
   De la Madrid had pledged clean elections. Government and party
officials are calling the vote the cleanest ever in Mexico.
   Clouthier vowed to lead sit-ins at every event where de la
Madrid or Salinas is scheduled to appear, as part of a national
civil disobedience campaign to protest the alleged fraud. He said
earlier he would file criminal charges against the head of the
National Electoral Registry.
   Carrying signs reading ``Punishment for electoral criminals''
and ``Total repudiation of the electoral fraud,'' the group pushed
past a line of about 50 plainclothes presidential guards who tried
to stop them.
   After a scuffle, the group sat down at the entrance to the
ornate, landmark building in downtown Mexico City.
   The Federal Election Commission, the only source of official
results, adjourned early Tuesday and said it would not meet again
until Wednesday night. Seven days after the elections, it was
releasing official results only on balloting for the Chamber of
Deputies, the lower house of Congress.
   With the vote count lagging, the PRI again released data it said
came from the federal commission.
   Those results showed Salinas de Gortari had 53.59 percent of the
votes counted. Cardenas was second with 26.08 percent and Clouthier
had 16.04 percent.
   Two candidates for small parties and null ballots accounted for
the remainder.
   Those results showed a turnout of 51.7 percent in the 235 of the
300 districts tallied, the government newspaper El Nacional said.
But original reports claimed an exceptionally high turnout.
Earlier, the government and the governing party had blamed the high
turnout for the slowness of the vote count.
   Turnout was officially placed at 75 percent in the last
presidential race in 1982. But strong candidates and active
campaigns on the left and right spurred voter interest in the July
6 race.
   Cardenas charged on Monday that the election officials were not
counting many of the votes that had been cast for opposition
candidates. Cardenas claims he won, based on figures he says came
from unidentified PRI officials.
   Cardenas, a former PRI senator and Michoacan state governor, led
a dissident movement within the governing party before breaking
away last year to accept the candidacy of other parties.
   Ballots are counted at polling places immediately after the
election, but according to law those for the Chamber of Deputies
and for the Senate must be processed before those for president in
an official count.
   The only returns released officially by the commission so far
gave 241 of the 500 seats in the chamber to the PRI, 32 to the
National Action Party and 10 to parties that support Cardenas. The
results were from 283 of the 300 electoral districts.
   Victories by parties supporting Cardenas were in the state of
Mexico, which surrounds Mexico City, and Michoacan. Victories for
the National Action Party were in the western state of Jalisco, the
Federal District, which is the core of the Mexico City metropolitan
area, and the northern border state of Chihuahua.
   The governing party has not lost a presidential, senate or
gubernatorial race since it was founded in 1929.
</TEXT>
