<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Billig     07-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Billig,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Tribunal Battles Pentagon Attempt to Investigate Bribe
Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military tribunal is fighting the Pentagon's
attempt to investigate an anonymous allegation that bribery
influenced its decision overturning a Navy heart surgeon's
convictions for the deaths of three patients.
   The Navy-Marine Corps Court of Military Review obtained an order
from the Court of Military Appeals temporarily barring the Defense
Department's inspector general from proceeding with the
investigation.
   The military appeals court, which originally granted the
temporary injunction June 30, extended the order Monday for 15 days
pending its final decision in the matter.
   At issue, says Patrick J. Carome, a lawyer appointed to
represent the tribunal, is the independence of military courts from
interference by the Pentagon's command hierarchy.
   ``The judges feel this is a situation in which command influence
or at least the appearance of it is being brought to bear'' on the
tribunal's unpopular decision to set aside the negligent homicide
and involuntary manslaughter convictions of Cmdr. Donal M. Billig,
Carome said.
   On April 13, the Navy-Marine Corps tribunal overturned Billig's
conviction and accused Navy prosecutors of waging a ``smear
campaign'' against the surgeon, who had practiced at the Bethesda
Naval Hospital outside Washington.
   At a hearing Monday, Lt. Cmdr. Lawrence W. Muschamp told the
military appeals court that Billig's conviction could not be
revived even if the bribery allegations were proven.
   But June Gibbs Brown, the Pentagon's inspector general, told the
military review tribunal June 23 that the investigation could
affect its Billig ruling ``if the decision was procured by bribery
or fraud,'' according to court papers.
   Brown told the court ``there is no indication of any criminal
misconduct'' by the judges or the court staff, according to a
summary of her remarks to the judges.
   The allegation, received from an anonymous tipster who called
the inspector general's hotline May 2, has not been detailed by
Pentagon authorities. The tipster has been interviewed several
times but Pentagon authorities have not identified the person,
according to court papers.
   At Monday's hearing, Muschamp said the investigation would
involve only whether there was an improper outside attempt to
influence the court. Investigators would be careful not to intrude
in the decision-making process of the court.
   But Carome argued that a special judicial commission, not the
Pentagon inspector general, should conduct any investigation to
preserve the independence of the military court.
   ``Allowing the inspector general mechanism to kick into high
gear and focus in on a court in a particular decision in a
particular case based on a simple anonymous tip and nothing more,
really sets up a situation in which disgruntled parties after a
case can utilize this mechanism to harass and interfere with the
judicial process,'' Carome said in a telephone interview.
   ``There are a lot of people at the Navy and the Pentagon who are
unhappy with the result'' in the Billig case, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
