<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SharpevilleSix     07-12 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Delays Hanging Of Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government postponed the
executions of the Sharpeville Six indefinitely Tuesday and Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain promised a new plea for
clemency by world leaders.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said the executions by hanging of
the six blacks were delayed so the Appellate Court, South Africa's
highest tribunal, can respond to their appeals.
   The last stay of execution for the five men and one woman was
until July 19. They were convicted in the mob killing of a town
council member in the Sharpeville black township, and originally
were scheduled to die in March. The six had originally been
sentenced to hang in March.
   Their convictions were based on the principle of ``common
purpose.'' They were part of a crowd that stoned and burned town
councilor Kuzwayo Dlamini to death in September 1984.
   Intense controversy surrounds the death sentences because the
six were cleared of directly causing victim's death, and because
violence against a town councilor who cooperated with South
Africa's apartheid policy of racial segregation is considered by
many to be a political crime.
   Many foreign leaders have asked President P.W. Botha to grant
clemency to the six: Francis Mokgesi, 31; Reid Mokoena, 24; Oupa
Moses Diniso, 32; Theresa Ramashamola, 27; Duma Joshua Khumalo, 28,
and Reginald Sefatsa, 32.
   Botha refused to intervene in March Supreme Court Judge Willem
Human of Transvaal province, who had sentenced them, granted a
temporary stay hours before the time of execution at Pretoria
Central Prison.
   Defense attorneys said the trial should be reopened because some
witnesses had said police forced them to give false testimony.
   One prosecution witness, Steve Manete, wrote to Botha last week
that he was assaulted and threatened by police to falsely identify
two of the accused as being at the scene of Dlamini's death. He
said other state witnesses also were ``unhappy with their
testimony'' against the Sharpeville Six and begged Botha to stop
the executions.
   Judge Human decided June 13 not to reopen the case because, he
said, the court had not relied solely on the suspect witnesses'
testimony. He added that allegations of police influence on other
prosecution witnesses were ``absurd.''
   He gave the defendants until July 19 to challenge the death
sentences in the Appellate Court, which had upheld his decision not
to reopen the trial.
   Some South African commentators have suggested the intense
international campaign on behalf of the defendants makes it more
difficult for Botha to grant clemency because he may appear to be
giving in to foreign pressure.
   Joyce Mokgesi, whose brother Francis is one of those condemned,
met with Mrs. Thatcher on Tuesday. She promised that to make
another appeal for clemency if the high court upholds the death
sentences.
   Mrs. Thatcher said leaders of the European Economic Community
and the world's seven major industrialized nations would join the
appeal.
   The defendants were convicted under laws passed by the South
African Parliament, which has no black representation, and
sentenced by a judicial system that excludes black judges.
   Botha added to the controversy by saying last March he could not
grant clemency because he did not want to interfere in the judicial
process. A few days later, however, he stopped the trial of six
South African soldiers accused of causing the death of a black
activist in South-West Africa, a territory controlled by South
Africa.
   In June, Justice Minister Coetsee told Parliament the president
had commuted 115 death sentences between 1983 and the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
