<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis'Decision 1stLd-Writethru a0680 07-12 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis' Decision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Mowed His Lawn, Then Chose Bentsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 25 grafs, picking up in 2nd graf pvs, As he</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was nearly midnight when Michael Dukakis asked
the four advisers at his kitchen table for recommendations on the
potential running mates they had been discussing. The unanimous
verdict: Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   ``That's my choice,'' said Dukakis.
   With that, the selection process that began June 8 ended.
Dukakis would ask the Democratic National Convention to nominate
Bentsen as his running mate in the effort to capture the White
House in November.
   A key figure at the table was Paul Brountas, the Boston lawyer
and former Harvard Law School classmate who headed Dukakis search.
After Bentsen's name was announced on Tuesday, Brountas described
what had happened.
   The decision made, it was decided to notify the Texas senator
immediately.
   ``We put a call in and there was no answer,'' said Brountas.
``We put a second call in around quarter to twelve and there was no
answer.''
   What they didn't know was that Bentsen was home but had turned
off his telephone because he had been getting so many late night
calls from reporters chasing the vice presidential selection story.
   At 6:30 on Tuesday morning, Bentsen was shaving when the
telephone rang. It was Dukakis offering him the No. 2 spot on the
Democratic ticket.
   Despite Bentsen's professed indifference to such an offer,
Brountas said that when he met with the senator in mid-June Bentsen
``indicated to me he would accept if asked.''
   The Dukakis adviser said that when he arrived at Dukakis'
Brookline home Monday night the decision was still open and that he
did not mislead Jesse Jackson when he told him Jackson still was
under consideration.
   Asked at a Washington news conference if he was angry, Jackson
replied: ``No, I'm too controlled, I'm too clear, I'm too mature to
be angry. I'm focused on what we must do to keep hope alive.''
   In Boston the night before, seated around the Dukakis kitchen
table along with Dukakis and Brountas were Kitty Dukakis, the
governor's wife; Susan Estrich, his campaign manager, and Jack
Corrigan, the deputy campaign manager
   During the primary season, Dukakis kept insisting he would not
begin thinking about a running mate until after he had clinched the
nomination.
   ``That was true,'' said Brountas, who said he tried to raise the
matter with Dukakis the night of June 7 _ the last night of the
primary season _ and was told to wait until breakfast the next
morning.
   Brountas presented Dukakis with a long memo outlining the
various considerations and then began the weeks of information
gathering.
   He said he gained the confidence of the 200 or so people he
consulted by describing himself as ``a committee of one'' who would
pass information only to Dukakis.
   He assembled a team of lawyers and tax accountants to
investigate the individuals who were the finalists for
consideration.
   Brountas refused to discuss the reasons any of the others were
not chosen over Bentsen except to say ``no one was eliminated from
consideration as a result of the background checks.''
   The day of the decision, Brountas flew to Washington to meet
with Jackson.
   His return flight was canceled by a thunderstorm, but he managed
to catch a later flight and arrived at Dukakis' home between 10:30
p.m. and 11 p.m.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis, looking unflappable, mowed his lawn in the
dark as he waited for his close friend and adviser to appear.
   As he methodically criss-crossed the yard with his push mower
night, the Massachusetts governor gave no hint how close he was to
ending the growing speculation over his choice for a running mate.
   But there were other signs that a decision was near.
   Newsmen clustered in front of the house on Perry Street saw
Estrich and Corrigan, join Dukakis inside the house.
   Meanwhile, Democrats were arriving in Atlanta to nominate
Dukakis for president, and the big topic of conversation was
speculation about his choice for a running mate.
   The name getting the most mention was that of Sen. John Glenn of
Ohio, the former astronaut who became a national hero when he was
the first American to orbit Earth.
   But the people who mattered the most weren't in Atlanta. They
were in Dukakis' home in Brookline.
   It was tight circle of five _ the governor, his most trusted
adviser Brountas, his two campaign aides, and his wife, Kitty.
   It had not been an easy day for Brountas, the Boston lawyer who
headed the vice presidential talent hunt.
   His principal order of business in Washington was a meeting with
Jesse Jackson, and according to one participant Brountas assured
Jackson he was ``under serious consideration.''
   As soon as their meeting ended, Jackson told reporters that if
offered the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket, ``I would accept
it.''
   But despite Brountas' assurances to the former civil rights
leader, one of the safest bets about the process was that Jackson
would not get that offer.
   In addition to Bentsen, Glenn and Jackson, the names on Dukakis'
list were Sens. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, and Bob Graham of
Florida and Reps. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Lee Hamilton of
Indiana.
   Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia remained a subject of speculation
despite his insistence he wasn't interested in the job.
   Each of the prospects had a moment or two in the sun when rumors
flared that they were gaining favor.
   But each time Dukakis was asked about the latest rumors he
brushed them aside saying that only he and Brountas were qualified
to speak authoritatively, and they weren't talking
</TEXT>
