<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Airliner     07-12 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Airliner,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Lacks Votes For Condemnation; U.S. And Iran Said To Agree On
Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Iran agreed to delay
a Security Council meeting on the downed Iranian airliner, largely
on Iran's initiative because it could not muster a majority for
condemnation, diplomats said Tuesday.
   A majority vote in the 15-nation council would force the United
States to use its veto to stop a resolution of condemnation. The
meeting, originally scheduled for Tuesday, has been postponed until
Thursday morning.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters told reporters he did not
believe Iran had the votes to condemn the United States for
shooting down the airliner July 3 in the Persian Gulf. All 290
people aboard were killed.
   Walters spoke after meeting with Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar, who later conferred with Foreign Minister Ali-Akbar
Velayati of Iran. Velayati left the building without speaking to
reporters.
   ``I don't think it (a resolution of condemnation) was a matter
of serious consideration because I don't think they can get the
votes for it,'' Walters said in answer to a question.
   ``Everyone knows perfectly well this was not a premedidated act.
Everybody knows the U.S. is investigating. Everybody knows the
United States is a completely transparent country in which the
findings of our investigation will become known in a very short
time.''
   Perez de Cuellar spent more than an hour each with Walters and
Velayati, prompting speculation about an attempt to bring the sides
together.
   The council meeting was postponed Monday night by Ambassador
Paulo Nogueira-Batista of Brazil, the president for July, after
consultations with the United States, Iran and other members.
   It is expected to hear speakers Thursday but the agenda is not
known.
   The official reason for the postponement was that more time was
needed for consultations and preparations.
   Officials also cited the International Civil Aviation
Organization meeting Wednesday in Montreal on the shooting down of
the airliner by the cruiser USS Vincennes fired a missile at the
civilian aircraft. The United States says the crew mistook the Iran
Air Airbus for an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   Diplomatic sources said privately both the United States and
Iran want to avoid a showdown in the council. They said plans for a
resolution apparently have been scrapped and delegates were working
on a milder letter from the council president that would be
approved by concensus.
   Iran had said it wants the council to condemn the U.S. military
action, demand withdrawal of all U.S. forces from the Persian Gulf
and call for reparations.
   The sources said the United States effectively preempted Iran in
the Security Council by offering compensation to families of the
victims and by expressing deep regret.
   Any resolution condemning the United States was expected to be
vetoed by the United States, Britain and France. The other two
permanent members of the council, who also have veto power, are the
Soviet Union and China.
   Current non-permanent members of the council are Algeria,
Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Japan, Nepal, Senegal, West Germany,
Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
