<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-Ancestor     07-12 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Ancestor,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen's Great-Great-Uncle Was Nation's 18th Vice President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texan Lloyd Bentsen said Tuesday that his
great-great-uncle Henry Wilson of Massachusetts did something that
``sounds like a good idea to me'' _ after serving many years in the
U.S. Senate, Wilson was elected vice president.
   ``I'm delighted to be back in a state where my great-great-uncle
was a senator from Massachusetts and became vice president of the
United States of America, and we're out to duplicate that record
today,'' Bentsen said after being picked by Democratic presidential
nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis as his vice presidential running mate.
   Wilson, who helped found the Republican Party, was the nation's
18th vice president; Bentsen wants to become the 44th.
   Bentsen, a Democratic senator from Texas since Jan. 3, 1971,
mentioned his Massachusetts relative in his remarks Tuesday but
didn't identify him. Bill Maddox, a spokesman for Bentsen,
confirmed that Bentsen was related to Wilson but did not know the
lineage.
   Wilson, a staunch abolitionist, was a Republican senator from
Massachusetts from Jan. 31, 1855, until he resigned March 3, 1873,
to become vice president during President Ulysses S. Grant's second
administration. Wilson, who had been elected in 1872 on the GOP
ticket with Grant, died in office on Nov. 22, 1875, in Washington,
D.C., at age 63.
   Wilson's portrait is in the state Senate's reading room. After
addressing the state Senate on Tuesday, Dukakis, the governor of
Massachusetts; Bentsen and Bentsen's wife, Beryl Ann, went into the
reading room to view the portrait.
   In remarks to the Massachusetts House, Bentsen noted his
great-great-uncle's many years of service in the U.S. Senate _ just
like Bentsen _ and that he went on to become vice president. He
said that ``sounds like a good idea to me.''
   Wilson was born Jeremiah Jones Colbaith in Farmington, N.H. in
1812, and later legally changed his name to Henry Wilson. He moved
to Natick, Mass., in 1833 and worked as a shoe manufacturer and
teacher before entering politics. He owned and edited a Boston
newspaper and served in the Massachusetts House and the state
Senate.
   He ran unsuccessfully for governor of Massachusetts in 1853 as a
free-soil candidate. In the U.S. Senate, Wilson was chairman of the
Military Affairs Committee during the Civil War. He was implicated
in the Credit Mobilier political scandal of 1872; Congress
reprimanded two congressmen in the case, but not Wilson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
