<DOCNO> AP880712-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviets-Afghan     07-12 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Afghan,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Pakistan Violating Accord on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSQOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry on Tuesday told the
U.S. ambassador and a Pakistani envoy that Pakistan's harboring of
a rival Afghan government violates the international agreement on
Afghanistan.
   Afghan rebel groups based in Pakistan announced last month the
creation of a government and demanded the ouster of President
Najib, the pro-Soviet Afghan leader.
   First Deputy Foreign Ministry Yuli M. Vorontsov called U.S.
Ambassador U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock and Pakistani Charge
d'Affairs Samuel T. Joshua to his offices for separate meetings,
ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev said. It was not a threat of
possible Soviet military retaliation, Perfilyev added.
   It was the latest in a series of statements by the Soviets
denouncing Pakistan, where most of the Moslem guerrillas fighting
Afghanistan's Marxist government have bases.
   Perfilyev said at a news briefing that the ministry's statement
is ``made for the sole purpose of showing to the government of
Pakistan and to public opinion the vital need to implement the
agreements.''
   The U.N.-mediated Afghan agreement, signed April 14 in Geneva,
commits the Soviet Union to begin withdrawing its more than 100,000
military personnel from Afghanistan. The Soviet withdrawal began
May 15 and is to be completed within 10 months.
   The accords also commit Pakistan and Afghanistan not to
interfere in each other's affairs. The United States and the Soviet
Union are listed as guarantors of the agreement. The Moslem rebels
did not sign the pact.
   In Afghanistan, reports said there was fighting around three
provincial cities.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
government battle the rebels, who have received support from
Pakistan and the United States.
   Perfilyev said Vorontsov told Joshua that the creation of a
transitional Afghan government on Pakistani soil is a violation of
the Geneva agreement. He reported Vorontsov as saying: ``The
consequences of the violations will be borne by the Pakistani side
totally.''
   Perfilyev added, ``Imagine the situation where somebody tried to
form an American government outside the territory of the United
States, for example, in Canada.''
   Mohammed Anwar, an employee at the Pakistani Mission, said
Joshua had been called to the Foreign Ministry by Vorontsov, but
Anwar said he could not disclose what happened at the meeting.
   Vorontsov also delivered a ``verbal note'' to Matlock in a
separate meeting, complaining of the ``new destructive action'' by
Pakistan, Perfilyev said.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Marguerite Squire said the meeting had
occurred but the embassy did not comment on diplomatic discussions.
   Perfilyev said Vorontsov told Matlock that Pakistani actions
violate the Afghan accords and the Kremlin hoped Washington would
do everything in its power ``to influence Pakistan to end its
interference in Afghan affairs and abide by its Geneva
obligations.''
   In an interview published Sunday, the Soviet commander in
Afghanistan said the withdrawal timetable for his troops could be
affected.
   ``We are prepared to continue to implement strictly and
faithfully the provisions of the Geneva agreements,'' Lt. Gen.
Boris Gromov told the Krasnaya Zvezda newspaper.
   ``Although I do not rule out that unceasing violations of the
provisions by Pakistan may lead ... to a situation when appropriate
conclusions will be made as regards the timetable of the troop
withdrawal,'' he was quoted as saying.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, Western diplomatic sources said fighting
continued for control of provincial and district capitals, but the
guerrillas were not occupying the cities because of retaliatory
bombings and shelling by Soviet and Afghan groops.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of one of the Afghan resistance
parties with headquarters in Pakistan said, ``We can keep the
cities but at the price of heavy casualties.''
   Rebel leaders reported their forces seized and then withdrew
from the capitals of Zabul and Wardak provinces. Afghanistan's
second largest city of Kandahar, 310 miles southwest of the capital
of Kabul, has been under siege for two months and Western diplomats
said the government is warning residents against cooperating with
the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
