<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Two-YearBudget     07-12 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Two-Year Budget,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bill Altering Budget Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
approved legislation Tuesday that would change the oft-criticized
federal budget process by putting it into a two-year cycle.
   The measure would appear to have lttle chance of being enacted
this year. The proposal is a controversial one, and Congress has a
short schedule this year because of the presidential and
congressional elections.
   Under the bill, which was approved by a 9-0 vote, the budget
resolution that charts the government's finances and the spending
and tax bills that flesh out those plans would cover two years.
Currently, those measures cover only one year.
   Congress would spend the second year of the new budget process
reviewing spending decisions.
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., the measure's sponsor, and his
supporters have argued that with the present single-year process,
Congress spends too much time bogged down on budget matters and not
enough time scrutinizing its fiscal decisions.
   ``It is not too much to ask that Congress and the executive
branch take one year in each Congress to ensure that abuse is
caught and dealt with before it becomes a public scandal,'' Ford
said in a written statement.
   Proponents also say that with Congress consistently passing
spending bills late _ well into the fiscal year for much of the
1980s _ federal agencies must operate in a state of confusion over
what their budgets will be. This makes planning for the agencies
difficult.
   Such legislation has been introduced in the past. It
consistently runs into opposition from lawmakers who argue that
two-year budgeting would be too inflexible, making it hard to
adjust to sudden emergencies or changes in the economy's
performance.
   Members of the Budget and Appropriations committees can be
expected to jealously guard their legislative turf against a bill
that would diminish their authority. The legislation now must be
considered by the budget panel.
   In addition, Democrats may want to wait to see how Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, should he become president, would feel about
such an alteration to the budget process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
