<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0825 07-12 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0825, a0815,0914</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ambassador Leaves; Embassy Denies Improper Behavior of Diplomats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: COMBINES a0825 and a0815; UPDATES with Melton statement;
embassy saying Melton headed toward El Salvador or Honduras and
that he left alone, other seven to leave Thursday. EDITS to TRIM.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton cited
Abraham Lincoln on tyranny as he left Nicaragua Tuesday, expelled
by the government with seven other American diplomats on charges of
fomenting domestic dissent.
   ``Lincoln taught us that tyranny never has moral
justification,'' Melton read from a prepared statement before
departing in a drizzle on a U.S. Air Force C-12 Turbo.
   ``It is my wish, and that of my government, that Nicaraguans
working together will find solutions to their problems which allow
them to fulfill their destiny living in peace as a free and
prosperous people in a democratic nation,'' he said.
   The U.S. Embassy said earlier that the expulsions were
``outrageous and completely without justification.''
   The embassy said Melton would travel to San Salvador or
Honduras, then take a commercial flight for the United States. The
embassy also said Melton traveled alone, not with five U.S.
diplomats as the state-run Voice of Nicaragua had reported, and
that the seven others will leave Thursday.
   The leftist Sandinista government on Monday expelled the eight
diplomats and told them they had 72 hours to leave the country. It
accused them of ``criminal acts against the Nicaraguan people.''
   According to the government, the eight were fomenting dissent
and helped organize a large anti-government demonstration last
Sunday that ended in violence.
   Some U.S. Embassy personnel attended the rally, but the embassy
said it was normal for its diplomats to maintain contact with
Nicaraguans.
   Also Monday, the government closed the Roman Catholic Church's
radio station, Radio Catolica, and shut down for 15 days the only
opposition newspaper, La Prensa. The actions marked a sharp setback
in democratic reforms made in recent months to comply with a
regional peace plan.
   In announcing Melton's departure, the Voice of Nicaragua said
sarcastically that ``many people of the Nicaraguan right and the
director of La Prensa, Violeta Chamorro, are crying at this time
because of the departure of their ambassador.''
   In Washington, President Reagan retaliated by ordering
Nicaragua's ambassador and seven other diplomats out of the United
States.
   The Nicaraguan government identified the other expelled
Americans as David Nolan, John Creamer, Hugh Simon Jr., Aubrey
Carlson, Delvin Junker, John Hope and Robert Murray.
   ``We are disposed to accept a new ambassador less addicted to
the psychopathic orientations of (Assistant Secretary of State for
Latin America) Elliot Abrams,'' Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto
said Monday.
   President Daniel Ortega said the decision was made so the United
States would ``learn to respect this country and its people.'' He
added Nicaragua was ``prepared to confront any type of American
escalation'' as a result.
   A U.S. Embassy statement said the ousters follow ``a series of
repressive actions directed against the political opposition, labor
and press in Nicaragua.''
   An Interior Ministry statement charged La Prensa with violating
internal security and national defense. It said the newspaper
incited violence and subverted public order.
   The headline of Monday's La Prensa was ``Sandinista Police Club
the People,'' reporting on Sunday's demonstration. It carried
another article headlined: ``Accounts of a Brutal Attack by the
Police.''
   The Sandinistas also claim La Prensa is the ``voice of the
CIA.'' The paper receives U.S. funding through the National
Endowment for Democracy.
   Radio Catolica's programming included Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo's homily in which he defended ``the right of the people to
civic protest.''
   Grumblings against U.S. Embassy involvement in internal
Nicaraguan affairs began last week. Sandinista officials said they
had discovered a ``Plan Melton'' that sought to create an internal
front of dissident.
   The Sandinistas said part of the U.S. plan to destabilize the
government was put into effect Sunday in Nandaime, a town 40 miles
south of the capital. Fighting broke out between security forces
and some of the estimated 10,000 demonstrators.
   Sandinista newspapers ran a picture of Murray, one of the U.S.
diplomats expelled, at the protest with his fist raised.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jan Hartman said the picture was taken as
Murray was summoning a group of Americans back to the cars to leave.
   The Embassy statement said U.S. diplomats ``maintain contact
with as wide a spectrum of Nicaraguan citizens as possible'' and
noted that such ``activities are the normal duties of U.S. Embassy
officials overseas.''
   The Sandinistas also have accused the United States of
responsibility for recent rebel attacks that violate the March 21
cease-fire. The government and the rebels, known as Contras, have
been at war for almost seven years. They signed the agreement to
seek a negotiated settlement to the war but the talks are at an
impasse.
   The Reagan administration has backed and trained the rebels
since 1981.
   The government had pushed ahead with a regional peace plan
outline signed last August by the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Guatemala, Costa Rica and Honduras. It called for
democratic liberties, cease-fires and an end to supporting
insurgencies in Nicaragua, Guatemala and El Salvador.
   As part of its compliance, the government had allowed the
reopening of Radio Catolica and La Prensa and permitted opposition
demonstrations, including the one last week.
</TEXT>
