<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Mars     07-12 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Mars,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Launch Second Satellite in Probe of Mars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN_THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Tuesday launched its second
spacecraft in a week toward Mars in an ambitious program to unlock
mysteries of the red planet and its largest moon, Phobos.
   Orange flames flared in the night sky over Soviet Central Asia
as a Proton booster rocket sent the unmanned Phobos II vehicle on a
111 million-mile voyage to Mars. Arrival is expected in January.
   Soviet television showed a recording during its evening news
broadcast of the launch of Phobos II at 9:01 p.m. Moscow time (1:01
p.m. EDT) from a pad at the Baikonur Cosmodrome on the steppes of
Central Asia.
   Phobos I was launched last Thursday and the media said its
on-board navigation systems were activated the next day.
   Television showed flags of more than dozen nations, including
the United States, flying at Baikonur. The countries are
participating in the mission that is designed to send the two space
probes close to the Phobos moon and drop instruments onto the
surface. Scientists said the mission might provide clues to how the
universe was formed.
   They have said that if Phobos is an asteroid trapped by Mars'
gravity, as many scientists believe, the probes will be able to
study matter that is little changed since the infancy of the solar
system billions of years ago.
   The two Soviet spacecraft are to enter the gravitational pull of
Mars in January and fall into orbit just behind Phobos for a
three-month study of the Martian surface, atmosphere and magnetic
field.
   In April, the two craft will drop out of their orbit and swoop
to within 100 feet of Phobos' surface and release two 100-pound
``landers.''
   In one experiment, a laser beam carried by a lander is designed
to split off a tiny piece of Phobos' rocky surface and trap it for
close examination.
   One of the landers is expected to operate for about a year in a
stationary position, sending back data. The other is planned to
bound like a superkangaroo about Phobos in 65-foot leaps, gathering
and analyzing soil samples.
   Soviet scientists have said the Phobos mission is an important
step toward a manned flight to Mars, which they believe may be
possible early in the 21st century.
   Officials have placed the cost of the Phobos mission at $480
million.
   In the United States, NASA's Deep Space Network will provide
radio-tracking data to help the spacecraft locate Phobos, which is
only about 17 miles in diameter.
</TEXT>
