<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PotShip     07-12 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pot Ship,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lieutenant: Coast Guard Knew When Ship Was Being Loaded With Pot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Coast Guard officer testified Tuesday that the
seized cargo ship Encounter Bay was loaded with 72 tons of
marijuana off Danang, Vietnam, in early June and that the
Vietnamese army was involved in the operation.
   Lt. Thomas Rogers, the law enforcement officer on the Coast
Guard cutter Boutwell, made the disclosure at a detention hearing
for the 18 crewmen of the Encounter Bay.
   The Coast Guard knew ``there was approximately 143,000 pounds of
high-grade Thai marijuana loaded off Danang, Vietnam, sometime
during the first 10 days of June,'' Rogers said.
   Asked by defense attorney Peter Mair what else he knew about the
loading, Rogers said, ``The only additional information I can
recall is that the Vietnamese army was involved.''
   Rogers disclosed the Vietnamese connection just before the
hearing was suspended for the day. U.S. Assistant Attorney Jerry
Diskin declined to comment on the disclosure after the hearing.
   ``I was shocked'' at the revelation, said Mair, attorney for
Anthony Gilbert Sayers, 53, of New Zealand, one of the crew.
   The Panamanian-registered ship was seized 500 miles off the
Washington coast on June 30 in what the Coast Guard said was the
largest maritime bust ever on the West Coast.
   The crew _ three Americans, one from England, one from New
Zealand and 13 from Indonesia, Thailand and Singapore _ have been
charged with intent to distribute marijuana.
   Defense lawyers have argued that the U.S. government can't prove
that the crew knew what the cargo was and that there wasn't
probable cause to stop the ship.
   The Encounter Bay carried documents showing it had left
Singapore on June 5 or 6, but Rogers said he didn't know whether
that was the vessel's last port of call.
   Rogers said he didn't know whether the crew got on board before
or after the vessel received its cargo, or whether documentation
found on board would answer the question.
   He also testified that he believed the crew members were read
their Miranda rights but that he didn't know whether the rights,
probably read in English, were understood by the crewmen from
Southeast Asia.
   U.S. Magistrate John Weinberg would not allow questions about
the Encounter Bay's destination, saying it was irrelevant to the
hearing, which was only to determine whether there was enough
evidence to schedule a trial.
   Attorney John Muenster, representing Terrance Albert Nolan, 36,
of the United States, said the question of destination was relevant
because the charges against the crew require the government to
prove that the ship either had left or was approaching a U.S. port,
or was in ``U.S. Customs territory,'' a term that neither he nor
Rogers could define.
   On Monday, Howard Weitzman, a Los Angeles attorney representing
crew member Samuel J. Colflesh, 31, of Philadelphia, said the ship
was in international waters when seized.
   ``A number of constitutional issues'' are at stake, including
``the right to go out and pirate a boat,'' he said.
   Also Monday, Muenster questioned whether intelligence collected
on the Encounter Bay had been acquired through wiretapping.
   ``We surmise there was wiretapping... and if the seizure of the
boat is based on wiretaps that were illegal, then the evidence ...
could not be introduced in federal court,'' Muenster said.
</TEXT>
