<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HelicopterEscape 1stLd-Writethru a0797 07-12 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helicopter Escape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0797,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District Attorney Files Charges Against Helicopter Pilot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf `The two...' with one graf to UPDATE with
appearance before magistrate. INSERTS one graf after 9th graf
`Carrol Bella...' to add background on Bella's movie experience.
Carrol is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of three inmates whisked by
helicopter from the state prison in a daring escape was back in
custody Tuesday, and so was the pilot of the chopper, who flew the
same aircraft in the movie ``Rambo III.''
   Convicted murderer Daniel Mahoney, 30, was captured in central
New Mexico Tuesday morning after a massive search in woods.
   The pilot of the helicopter, Charles Bella, originally had told
authorities a woman hijacked him in El Paso, Texas, and forced him
to fly to the prison south of Santa Fe.
   Santa Fe County District Attorney Chet Walter said Bella, 43,
and Beverly Shoemaker were charged Tuesday with three counts of
assisting escape and one count of conspiracy to commit escape.
   The two appeared later Tuesday before Magistrate Isaac
Archuleta, who set $100,000 cash bond for each. Bella pleaded
innocent and the judge automatically entered an innocent plea for
Shoemaker, who was not represented by an attorney. Walter also
filed complaints against the other two inmates who climbed aboard
the helicopter Monday morning, charging each with one count of
escape and one count of conspiracy.
   Bella was the pilot of the Aerospatiale Gazelle that swooped
into the prison yard, picked up the convicts and fled under a
fusillade of gunfire from guards in towers.
   Bella, Shoemaker and the three inmates all were arrested within
16 hours of the escape.
   Carrol Bella said her husband, who runs a charter flight
business catering mostly to television news crews and real estate
salespeople, told her and police he was hijacked at gunpoint by a
woman who had chartered the helicopter. She said her husband told
her the woman handcuffed his hand to the helicopter's controls and
forced him to pick up the three inmates.
   A close friend of Bella, Tony Mobley, told The Associated Press
in El Paso, Texas, that the pilot flew stunts in the movies ``Rambo
III'' and ``Extreme Prejudice.'' In ``Rambo III,'' the Gazelle,
modified to look like a Soviet Hind helicopter, is shot down by the
character played by Sylvester Stallone.
   ``It's a tough case,'' Walter said, adding there was probable
cause to believe Bella was involved in an escape plot.
   When the chopper was finally forced down at Albuquerque
International Airport, after a 20-mile aerial chase, Bella was
taken into custody while his story was checked out.
   Bella and Ms. Shoemaker, 41, were being held at the Santa Fe
County Detention Center. The inmates were returned to the state
prison.
   Moments after the helicopter left the prison Monday, a U.S.
Customs Service helicopter began pursuit.
   The fugitive helicopter landed briefly at a central New Mexico
airport about an hour after the escape, where Mahoney, Shoemaker
and Randy Mack Lackey jumped out. Lackey and the woman fled in
different directions, said Department of Public Safety spokesman
Dan Taylor.
   Police officers at the airport confronted Lackey as he tried to
get away in a stolen pickup truck, but officers shot him in the
shoulder and he was arrested, said Taylor. Ms. Shoemaker, who was
described by Taylor as Mahoney's girlfriend, was arrested later at
the airport.
   The helicopter, meanwhile, was involved in an up-and-down,
weaving chase through the skies over Albuquerque, from Los Lunas
south of the city to a small commuter airfield north of the city
and back south to the international airport.
   After some aerial jousting with the Customs Service helicopter
and a state police chopper flown by Maj. John Denko, Bella landed
at the Albuquerque airport. He was arrested there along with the
third prisoner, Francis Preston Mitchell, less than two hours after
the escape.
   Mahoney was serving a life sentence plus 60 years from
Hillsborough County, Fla., for second-degree murder and armed
robbery; Mitchell was serving a life sentence from Summit County,
Utah, for first-degree murder and Lackey was serving a nine-year
sentence for larceny from Curry County, N.M.
   Mitchell and Mahoney were being held in New Mexico under an
interstate compact that allows states to swap prisoners.
</TEXT>
