<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru a0716 07-12 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Meets Youth In Old Polish Capital Of Krakow</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 4 grafs after 11th `In a day' with details of visit
to church. PICKS up 12th pvs bgng, Activists with the ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CRA50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged a
rally of Polish and Soviet youth on Tuesday to return to the
lessons of Lenin and to join in Gorbachev's reform movement.
   Opposition activists claimed riot police attacked and arrested
steel workers in the southeastern town of Stalowa Wola. They said
the workers had threatened to strike during Gorbachev's visit. A
government spokesman confirmed a police incident but said there
were no major disturbances.
   Speaking at Krakow's Wawel Castle, the residence of Polish kings
and queens until the late 1500s, Gorbachev repeatedly emphasized
that Lenin, the founder of the Soviet Union, could serve as a model
in ``the era of the second world revolution since the birth of
socialism.''
   ``Lenin's life and struggle constitute a splendid example to be
followed by young people ... a lesson in pursuing one's goals and
being faithful to the ideal born out of love for people,'' he said.
   The speech was a vigorous defense of Communist ideology in a
country where fewer than 1 percent of people under the age of 35
have joined the party and where young people tend to long for the
material success of Western nations.
   Asking rhetorically, ``Has socialism fallen through?'' Gorbachev
answered ``No ... Not at all.''
   ``We have transformed backward Russia from top to bottom and
made a great power of it. And all that thanks to socialism. That
would have been impossible on a different road.''
   The rally came on the second day of Gorbachev's six-day trip to
Poland.
   The Soviet leader and his wife Raisa, who arrived in Warsaw on
Monday, flew to Krakow on Tuesday to tour the city, where Pope John
Paul II served as archbishop before he was named pope in 1979.
   Gorbachev visited a mountain home near Krakow where Lenin lived
in 1913 and 1914 while plotting the revolution that brought the
Bolsheviks to power in Russia in 1917. Gorbachev often cites
Lenin's pragmatic approach to economic reform as a precedent for
his own policies that encourage greater openness and
market-oriented reforms.
   In a day of sightseeing, he also went to the house where his
father, a Red Army soldier, was hospitalized during World War II,
visited one of the nation's most historic churches, St. Mary's, and
chatted with the people who were allowed onto Krakow's old market
square.
   Gorbachev's 20-minute sojourn in the 14th century Roman Catholic
church on the square was the first time in memory a head of the
officially atheist Soviet Communist Party went into a working
church.
   It reflected the lessening of the gulf between the party and
religion. In April, Gorbachev received the head of the Russian
Orthodox Church at the Kremlin, the first such meeting in at least
40 years and has promised a new law on relations between church and
state. Some churches have been reopened and confiscated church
property returned.
   Monsignor Jan Kosciolek of St. Mary's said: ``We went through
the main gate and we walked to the main altar. We talked about the
architecture and emphasized that it was the biggest altar north of
the Alps.''
   Kosciolek said Gorbachev signed the guest book. Reporters were
not allowed in the church during the visit.
   Activists with the banned Solidarity trade union movement said
police surrounded a church Tuesday where some workers took refuge
after the alleged attack Monday night in Stalowa Wola.
   They said an undetermined number of people were detained by
police and about 50 people had taken refuge in the church.
   A government spokesman, Ryszard Strauss, confirmed a
``conflict-prone situation'' at the church, but denied any
organized police attack. He said at least one person was detained,
and he could not rule out that some officers used clubs.
   The workers had threatened to strike during the Gorbachev visit
unless seven colleagues fired for leading a two-day strike in April
were reinstated.
   On Monday, Gorbachev told the Polish parliament, or Sejm, that
he is moving to set the record straight about Josef Stalin's rule,
including supporting a drive to erect a monument in Moscow to
Stalin's victims.
   But he indicated he is not yet prepared to accept Soviet
responsibility for the massacre of about 4,300 Polish military
officers in the Katyn forest near the Russian city of Smolensk
shortly after the outbreak of World War II.
   The Katyn massacre remains a festering sore in relations between
the Communist neighbors.
   The Soviet Union has never admitted responsibility for the
slaughter. Each officer was bound, killed with a single bullet
through the head and left to rot in a mass grave. The murdered
officers had been interned by the Soviets, who accused the Nazis of
the massacre.
   A joint study commission has been established to investigate
Katyn, but Gorbachev indicated Monday that he is not yet prepared
to draw any concuslions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
