<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-12 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Scattered from Texas to Delaware</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms scattered rain Tuesday from Texas to
the Chesapeake Bay, dumping several inches of rain on parts of
Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas and Delaware.
   Rain was diminishing across eastern Texas after storms dropped
up to 6 inches of rain in the northeast part of the state during
the night. Still, College Station received over an inch and a third
of rain in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Rain also spread into extreme southeast Oklahoma, much of
Arkansas and extreme northwest Louisiana. Overnight rainfall
measured just under 5 inches near Broken Bow, Okla., and over 4{
inches at DeQueen Lake, Ark.
   Showers and thunderstorms were widespread along a cold front
from southeast Missouri through Kentucky and the mid-Atlantic Coast
region, and from the Carolinas coast to southern Georgia and
central Alabama.
   Bridgeville, Del., received 2 inches of rain during the morning.
   Elsewhere, rainfall in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included over 1} inches at Hot Springs, Ark.; around 1{ inches at
Jonesboro and Blytheville, Ark., and Danville, Va.; and around
three quarters of an inch at New Bern, N.C., and Charleston, S.C.
   Early afternoon temperatures were in the 70s or 80s across much
of the nation. It was in the low 90s in eastern Colorado and
western Kansas, from southern and north-central Texas to central
Louisiana and southern Alabama, and across much of Florida, while
temperatures approached 100 in the desert Southwest.
   Cooler temperatures in the 50s and 60s prevailed over the
Pacific Northwest and the northern Plateau, and it stayed in the
60s in the eastern part of upper Michigan.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 56 degrees at Bremerton,
Wash., to 102 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The nation's low
Tuesday morning was 37 at Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms throughout much of the eastern half of the country
from the upper Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes to the
middle and southern Atlantic Coast and the eastern half of the Gulf
Coast. Thunderstorms were expected to be most numerous over the
upper Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes. Thunderstorms also
were expected to develop in the afternoon over the High Plains of
Colorado and Kansas.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 70s along the Pacific Coast and
across northern Washington and Idaho into much of Montana; near 100
degrees over southwest Kansas and the Rio Grande Valley; and
between 100 and 110 degrees in the valleys of California and
southwest Nevada and the desert Southwest. The rest of the nation
was expected to have highs in the 80s and 90s.
</TEXT>
