<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     07-12 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Inaugurates New West Bank Settlement, Vows More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Minister David Levy inaugurated a new
Jewish settlement in the West Bank on Tuesday and vowed others will
be built there despite the 7-month-old Palestinian uprising against
Israeli occupation.
   ``We hear the voices (of the uprising),'' Levy, a leader of the
right-wing Likud bloc, told Israel television. ``But we are the
ones who make the facts, and those are: Another settlement, another
highway, another house, another family.''
   These developments also occurred:
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, army bullets hit two
Palestinians in the legs during a demonstration protesting the
death of 17-year-old Sares Anabtawi, who was killed by army gunfire
Monday.
   At a courthouse in Arab east Jerusalem, officials said about 30
Palestinians attacked police officers taking a handcuffed Arab
detainee to his cell. The officials said six officers were injured
and four people arrested.
   Palestinian witnesses said armed Jewish settlers beat four Arabs
and smashed the windows of two vehicles in the West Bank village of
Ein Arik, apparently in retaliation for the stoning of an Israeli
bus.
   The new Jewish settlement of Shima, near Hebron, is designed to
house 250 families. The first 15 families were to arrive Wednesday
and live in mobile homes until permanent housing is built.
   It is the first settlement to be established since the uprising
began in December in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
According to U.N. figures, 220 Palestinians and four Israelis have
been killed in the insurrection in the territories captured by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Shima will be the sixth West Bank settlement to be built since
1984. Under a coalition agreement reached in 1984 between Likud and
the left-leaning Labor Party, which opposes a large-scale
settlement program, the number of new settlements was limited to
six.
   But the more than 100 existing settlements have been expanded
since 1984 at an overall rate of 1,500 housing units a year.
   Yosef Margalit, a Housing Ministry official, said fewer Israelis
are willing to move to the West Bank because of the violence.
   About 300 Palestinians gathered in Nablus' marketplace to
protest Anabtawi's death and hurled stones at soldiers, who
responded with gunfire and rubber bullets, according to witnesses.
   Officials at the Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said two
demonstrators, aged 22 and 23, were shot in the legs, two others
were injured by rubber bullets and two were treated for beating
injuries.
   Army officials confirmed the shootings and said two soldiers
were wounded by stones.
   The army later imposed a curfew on much of Nablus and two
adjacent refugee camps, confining 126,000 Palestinians to their
homes indefinitely.
   Police spokesman Alex Lapidot said the attack in Jerusalem
occurred as two policemen were taking a 25-year-old prisoner from
the courthouse to his cell.
   He said about 30 Palestinians tried to free the prisoner and
four other officers rushed to the scene to drive back the crowd.
One policeman suffered a broken hand and the others had minor
injuries, he said.
   ``Four of the attackers were finally subdued and arrested,''
Lapidot said. ``The others managed to escape.''
</TEXT>
