<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen-Polls 2ndLd-Writethru a0806 07-12 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Polls, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0806,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pollsters On Bentsen: Helps in Texas, Unknown Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New graf 3 with ABC-Post poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen will help the Democratic
ticket in Texas, but outside his home state he is virtually unknown
to most voters and may have little effect on the presidential race,
pollsters said Tuesday.
   Bentsen has scored low in polls on potential running mates for
Gov. Michael Dukakis. In a CBS News-New York Times survey last
week, only 3 percent of Democratic primary voters picked Bentsen
from seven choices.
   In an ABC News-Washington Post poll completed Monday, less than
one-half of 1 percent named Bentsen as their choice as a running
mate for Dukakis. The telephone survey of 1,100 registered voters
conducted July 6-11 had a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5
percentage points.
   But Dukakis' choice of Bentsen likely was based on a more
practical measure than name recognition, pollsters said. Bentsen
gives Dukakis a shot to win Texas and its 29 electoral votes,
third-largest of any state.
   ``It's a high-risk technique. You've got to beat George Bush in
his home state,'' said Claibourne Darden, an Atlanta-based
pollster. ``If Dukakis can do that, George Bush will be whupped.''
   A statewide poll in Texas in mid-June had Dukakis trailing Vice
President Bush, who maintains an apartment in Houston, by 23
points. But when Bentsen was proposed as Dukakis' running mate, the
Democrats trailed by just 5 points.
   Adding Bentsen ``makes Texas a competitive state,'' said Brad
Coker of Mason-Dixon Opinion Research, which did that poll. ``If
there's a drawback, it's that Bentsen doesn't guarantee Texas. That
makes it risky for Dukakis.''
   Outside his state, Bentsen is unlikely either to help or hurt
Dukakis, barring any damaging disclosures, political pollsters
said. In the absence of controversy about a running mate, they
said, voters tend to focus on the top of the ticket.
   That was backed up by a Florida poll by Mason-Dixon, conducted
during the weekend, putting Bush 10 points ahead of Dukakis in
Florida with Bentsen as well as without him. Only with Sen. Bob
Graham of Florida as a running mate did Dukakis draw even with Bush
there, WPLG-TV in Miami reported.
   Generally, other than in a running mate's home state,
``Everybody says the choice can hurt but not help,'' said Harry
O'Neill, a pollster for the Roper Organization and president of the
National Council on Public Polls. ``Unless there's something really
negative, I don't think the vice presidential candidate matters in
people's minds one way or the other.''
   Bentsen thus far barely is in the public's mind. In a national
Gallup poll in mid-May, 77 percent of respondents said they had not
heard enough about him to have an opinion of him. Of the rest, 15
percent rated him positively, 9 percent negatively.
   Similarly, in a Harris poll in early May, Bentsen ranked fifth
of eight choices for a vice presidential candidate, far behind
leaders Jesse Jackson and Sen. John Glenn of Ohio. In the Gallup
poll, a gauge that took negative ratings into account put Glenn and
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey on top.
   ``There are many other vice presidential possibilities that are
more popular than Bentsen,'' said Larry Hugick, a Gallup pollster.
``Basically the guy just does not have much name recognition on a
national scale.''
   Still, pollsters noted, many other vice presidential candidates
have been little-known _ Democrat Geraldine Ferraro in 1984,
Republican Spiro Agnew in 1968 and Republican William Miller in
1964, for example _ and Dukakis himself was unknown by 77 percent
of the public as recently as November.
   Where he is known, in Texas, Bentsen was rated favorably by 55
percent of respondents to the Mason-Dixon poll last month, and
unfavorably by 12 percent. Bush had the same favorable rating but
much higher unfavorables, 33 percent. Dukakis was rated favorably
by 39 percent, unfavorably by 29 percent.
   In his Senate re-election contest, Bentsen led Republican
challenger Rep. Beau Boulter by 60-27; even if Bentsen runs for
vice president and for the Senate at the same time, respondents
said, they would favor him by 58-27.
   Coker noted that the Texas numbers well may change, at least in
part because many Texans may not have taken the suggestion of
Bentsen for vice president seriously.
   Such apparently was the case with pollsters themselves. Hugick
noted that Gallup just completed a poll during the weekend that
tested two possible Dukakis running mates _ Glenn and Sen. Albert
Gore of Tennessee.
   ``We picked the wrong Southerner,'' he said.
</TEXT>
