<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Nicaragua 6thLd-Writethru a0839 07-12 1257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0839,1,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Expels Nicaraguans; May Call for Severing of Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 grafs before penultimate graf bgng, `The
Nicaragua,' to UPDATe with the names of the other diplomats being
expelled from US</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday ordered the
expulsion of Nicaragua's ambassador and seven of his diplomatic
colleagues in a ``return-the-favor reprisal'' for the ouster of
eight American envoys to Managua.
   At the same time, Reagan refused to rule out severing U.S.
relations with the leftist Sandinista government, saying it
``remains an option.''
   Reagan said the expulsion order would affect Nicaraguan
Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann and seven other diplomats.
   But Tunnermann also is Nicaragua's ambassador to the
Organization of American States and questions were raised as to
whether the United States, as host country, can legally expel OAS
envoys.
   At one point, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater indicated
that Tunnermann would be allowed to remain in the United States
when he said the envoy simply ``won't be ambassador'' to the United
States.
   But a State Department official said the administration has
every intention of revoking Tunnermann's visas and expelling him.
``He can scream all the way to the airport,'' said one official,
insisting on anonymity.
   Tunnermann went to the State Department for consultations late
Tuesday afternoon.
   Afterward, Tunnermann said the United States has no right to
expel a diplomat assigned to the OAS and said it was the first case
in OAS history in which a diplomat accredited to that body has been
ordered out of the country.
   But he stopped short of saying he would fight the expulsion
order, saying that he had to consult first with his government.
   Tunnermann said that Under Secretary of State Michael Armacost
had told him he had engaged in activities as OAS ambassador which
violate diplomatic norms.
   When Tunnermann demanded that Armacost present proof, he quoted
Armacost as saying, ``Well, some day.''
   Later, State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
that Tunnermann had engaged in an abuse of his ``privileges of
residence'' of residence in the United States.
   She said that Major Pedro Sampson Mendoza, Nicaragua's military
attache who also was on the list of those expelled, was guilty of
the same offense.
   Mrs. Oakley declined to specify what abuses Tunnermann and
Sampson Mendoza had committed. When reminded by reporters that
Reagan had described the expulsions as retaliation, she said the
diplomats were being ordered out both as a retaliatory measure and
for the alleged abuses.
   Meanwhile, House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., said
that in a meeting that he and other congressmen had with Reagan,
national security adviser Colin D. Powell said U.S. Ambassador
Richard Melton recommended against cutting off relations.
   The latest flare-up in mostly icy relations that have existed
since the Sandinistas overthrew dictator Anastasio Somoza in 1979
prompted White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater to brand Managua's
expulsion order and political crackdown as ``black eyes for the
peace process.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, traveling in the Far East,
called Nicaragua's ouster of Melton and the other U.S. diplomats
action an ``absolute outrage.''
   And the State Department listed a series of actions, capped by
Monday's closing of La Prensa and Radio Catolica, that it said are
``directed against the political opposition, labor and press in
Nicaragua.''
   The expulsions came amid growing indications of a softening of
opposition in Congress to a renewal of U.S. military aid to the
Contra rebels seeking to topple the Sandinistas.
   Reagan, asked whether he was putting off a new move to get
Congress to approve military aid for the Contras, replied, ``We're
not waiting. We're working on that.''
   ``Maybe, now, some of the congressional apologists will get on
board now and support the Contras,'' said Senate Republican leader
Bob Dole of Kansas.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., an opponent of
Contra aid, said, ``It's going to have a damaging effect on the
opinion of the Sandinistas' performance in the peace process in
Congress.''
   ``I wouldn't say now that the Congress is going to vote military
aid, but it certainly strengthens the hand of the administration if
it seeks to get military aid for the Contras,'' Foley said on
CBS-TV's ``This Morning'' program.
   Michel said he could not understand ``those who have been
supporting (Nicaraguan President Daniel) Ortega and the Sandinistas
in the Congress, or at least tipping the scales in their favor
whenever they can.''
   ``In my judgment, it weakens their position. It strengthens
ours, and we ought to call them to task for it,'' he said.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., a Contra aid opponent, said
that the Reagan administration decision to expel the Nicaraguan
diplomats ``just fans this problem and expands it.''
   ``The administration sees this situation as its best opportunity
in months to get back the military aid for the resistance in
Nicaragua,'' he said.
   Dodd said he was ``not surprised'' at Managua's decision to
expel the U.S. diplomats given the long hostility between the two
governments, but he termed the Sandinista government's closing of
La Prensa and the Catholic radio station ``a major setback.''
   ``I think it is a violation of the commitments they have made,''
said Dodd, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
Latin America. ``... I think it's a victory for extreme voices in
Nicaragua and in Washington.''
   Congress rejected a $36.2 million package, which included a
proposed $3.5 million for a military escrow account, in February.
   In late March, it approved a $48 million bill providing only
humanitarian aid through Sept. 30, and only $17 million of that was
earmarked for the Contras.
   Supporters of aid to the Contras in the Senate have said they
will seek an amendment to the Defense Department appropriations
bill as early as this week to renew military aid.
   Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto said Monday that
Melton and seven U.S. Embassy aides were ordered to leave the
country within 72 hours because they were engaged in ``activities
complementary to the state terrorism the administration of U.S.
President Ronald Reagan is carrying out against Nicaragua.''
   The Nicaraguans said embassy officials were at an opposition
demonstration in Nandaime, about 40 miles from Managua, on Sunday.
   But a State Department statement said the United States
``rejects the Sandinista pretext for these expulsions.''
   ``The ambassador and the embassy maintain contact with as wide a
spectrum of Nicaraguan citizens as possible, including labor
groups, the press and the internal political opposition,'' it said.
``These activities are the normal duties of U.S. officials
overseas.''
   Reagan disclosed the U.S. retaliatory order during an Oval
Office picture-taking session with Sheik Saad Al-Abudllah Al-Sabah,
the crown prince and prime minister of Kuwait.
   ``I have told the State Department to send their ambassador and
seven comrades back to Managua,'' he said.
   Asked if was going to sever relations with Managua, the
president replied, ``No,'' then added that ``the other is a
possibility always that we could do, but we'll just return those
individuals.''
   ``In other words, we're going to return the favor,'' Reagan
said. ``We're going to do to him what he did to us.''
   In addition to Tunnermann and Sampson Mendoza, the other
Nicaraguans being expelled are Maureen Sampson, Manuel Cordero,
Sofia Clark D'Escoto, Orlando Martin Vega Gutierrez, Zelmira Garcia
and Angel Arce.
   The Nicaraguan diplomats were being given 72 hours to leave the
country.
   The U.S. responded to the expulsion of three diplomats in 1983
by closing several Nicaraguan consulates in the United States. The
U.S. diplomats were accused of taking part in an alleged plot to
poison D'Escoto.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
