<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WildlifeRefuge     07-12 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildlife Refuge,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Hears Complaints Over Refuge Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Gerry E. Studds, D-Mass., Tuesday called
a dispute over the current expansion plan for the San Francisco Bay
Wildlife Refuge a ``tempest in a salt marsh'' and ordered further
examination of the proposal.
   Studds' comments came at a hearing of the Subcommittee on
Fisheries and Wildlife Conservation and the Environment which
examined a proposal to double the size of the refuge.
   The 21,662 acre tract of land and water was set aside by
Congress 16 years ago to protect remnant tidal wetlands and their
indigenous species at the south end of San Francisco Bay in
northern California.
   Last December President Reagan signed into law, legislation
authorizing additional appropriations to complete acquisition of
the original bondaries of the refuge.
   But administration officials Tuesday opposed the purchase of
20,850 acres of ``seasonal wetlands'' and ``salt ponds.''
   The administration ``does not believe additional land purchases
are warranted at this time,'' especially in light of the $13.1
million already spent on land acquisition, said William F. Hartwig
of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   Paul Shepherd, vice president and land manager of Leslie Salt,
which owns 85 percent of the land slated for purchase, argued that
landowners were not told of the proposed annexation until they saw
their property on a map.
   Although the legislation states that additions to the refuge may
only be acquired from willing sellers, Shepherd said this type of
notice was ``tantamount to having a federal lein on the property.''
   But Mayor Gus Morrison of Fremont, Calif. supported the
legislation saying the so-called ``condemnation'' clause which
outlines how the land purchases must be made solves many of the
problems cited by opponents.
   However Newark, N.J. Mayor David W. Smith noted that the
expansion plans would absorb almost half of his city's land,
including a section earmarked for industrial development by city
planners.
   ``Newark's residential development is virtually in place. We
need additional industrial development to complement it,'' he said.
``One section (scheduled for purchased) is 44 percent of my city.
   ``Anytime the federal government draws a line on a map and says
this is what we designate as a refuge,'' Smith added, ``that land
becomes holy ground and it becomes impossible to develop it for any
other prupose in the San Francisco Bay area.''
   ``I think he's wrong,'' Morrision said of Smith. ``I just have
failed in convincing him, and I don't know why. If he keeps rigid
control over how the land is used he won't have any trouble.
   ``Like the chairman said, it's just a tempest in a salt marsh,''
Morrison said.
</TEXT>
