<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-ShipAttack 3rdLd-Writethru   07-12 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Ship Attack, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0836,1035</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Terrorists May Have Intended to Hijack Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede and INSERTS 1 graf after 8th pvs, A senior
officer..., to RESTORE reference and quote with official saying
terrorists could have been trying to hijack ship. PICKS up 9th graf
pvs bgng, Anastasios Sehiotis ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ATH1,2,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Tuesday the terrorists
who attacked a Greek cruise ship may have been pro-Iranian Arabs
trying to hijack it, and released photographs of three men and a
woman allegedly involved.
   The terrorists, who apparently boarded as passengers, fired
automatic weapons and hurled grenades Monday on the City of Poros,
which was taking 471 foreign tourists on a one-day cruise through
the Greek islands.
   City coroner Manolis Nonas reported 10 people dead and harbor
officials said another body had been found, but the Merchant Marine
Ministry put the toll at nine dead and 98 injured. There was no
explanation for the discrepancies in the death count.
   Several survivors and a harbor official said Tuesday the
attackers joined fleeing passengers in jumping from the ship and
were picked up with them by vessels that rushed to aid the City of
Poros.
   Two French survivors, not identified, appeared on state
television and one said: ``We saw them jumping out of the ship, and
a number of other passengers said they saw the terrorists aboard
the rescue boats going to Piraeus.''
   Police had said Monday night the terrorists escaped on a waiting
speedboat. Police officials would not comment about the reports
Tuesday.
   Officials also made conflicting statements about the number of
people involved in the attack, for which no group has claimed
responsibility.
   A senior officer of the Piraeus Harbor Authority said the attack
might be linked to the trial in Piraeus, scheduled for this week,
of Mohammed Rashid, a Palestinian wanted by the United States in
the 1982 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Hawaii. The officer spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``We theorize they were going to seize the ship together with
the people who died in the car explosion, maybe to force the
freeing of the Palestinian on trial'' the officer said.
   Anastasios Sehiotis, minister of public order, released the
photos and told reporters: ``These pictures are being circulated to
all airports, harbors and border entry points. These people were
involved with yesterday's attack.''
   Sehiotis also indicated an explosion earlier Monday that killed
two men in a car was linked to the ship attack. The car blew up
near the Trocadero Marina, home dock of the City of Poros, and the
ship was attacked about six hours later, at 8:40 p.m.
   The minister would give no further information except for the
names of ``two Lebanese men being sought as involved in this
attack.''
   He identified them as Hamoud Abdul Hamid, 36, who rented the
car, and Mohammed Zozad, 21, thought to be one of the men on the
ship. Sehiotis said both had been in Greece since May.
   The two other men were not identified and it was not clear
whether they were on the ship. The woman in the photo was not
identified, but the picture appeared to have been taken aboard the
vessel.
   Survivors said they saw three attackers, one masked with a
stocking, fire at people on the ship and hurl several hand
grenades. The explosions started a fire that brought the sun deck
crashing down on passengers in the lounge below.
   But the Piraeus Harbor Authority officer said he believed the
attack was carried out by two men and two women who boarded the
cruise ship when it called at the island of Aegina.
   He said survivors identified Zozad in one of the photographs and
recognized the young woman in the other photograph released by the
ministry.
   ``One woman, we think, had a Moroccan passport and the other a
French passport. We think they found out about the car explosion
and decided to shoot up the ship,'' the officer said.
   In Paris, a woman was quoted as saying she was the mother of the
French woman identified in one photograph.
   The woman, who identified herself only as Mrs. Bismuth, called
the Agence France-Presse news agency and said she saw the picture
on the Tuesday evening news. She was quoted as saying her daughter,
Isabelle, 21, was a secretary vacationing in Greece and not a
terrorist. Mrs. Bismuth said she hasn't heard from her daughter
since the attack, the agency reported.
   A spokesman for the Merchant Marine Ministry said 23 people
remained hospitalized Tuesday.
   Seven Americans were on the cruise, but none was among the
injured, the spokesman said. Greek state-run TV said an American
identified as Carl Johns was killed, but the U.S. Embassy said they
were unaware of any such person.
   Palestinian terrorists hijacked the Italian cruise ship Achille
Lauro during a Mediterranean cruise in October 1985 and killed a
69-year-old American passenger, Leon Klinghoffer. Italian courts
convicted seven Palestinians.
   Rashid, 34, was scheduled for trial Wednesday on charges of
entering the country with a forged passport, but prison officials
said it would be postponed because of a nationwide work slowdown by
prison guards. The government says it is considering a U.S.
extradition request for Rashid.
   U.S. officials say Rashid put a bomb on a Pan Am plane that
exploded on a Tokyo-Honolulu flight in April 1982, killing a
Japanese teen-ager and wounding 15 people. He was arrested at the
Athens airport June 1.
   Police said the car that exploded contained automatic weapons,
hand grenades and ammunition and a large amount of explosives.
   A police spokesman, speaking privately, said an Iranian magazine
also was found in the wreckage. He said a Beretta automatic pistol
and fragments of Soviet-made hand grenades found on the City of
Poros ``were identical with weapons recovered from the car
wreckage.''
   The Merchant Marine Ministry said only two of the bodies had
been identified _ Antonis Demaizis, 45, the ship's first mate, and
Klaus Johan Grabas, a 33-year-old Danish tourist. The ship carried
22 crew members.
</TEXT>
