<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Deserter     07-12 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Deserter,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Army Deserter Is Pardoned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet soldier who deserted in Afghanistan five
years ago, went to the United States and was jailed when he
returned to the Soviet Union, has been freed, Tass reported Tuesday.
   The state-run news agency said Nikolai Ryzhkov was released from
a labor camp under an amnesty announced on July 4 for soldiers who
turned against their country during the Soviet army's 8{-year
intervention in Afghanistan.
   In a January 1985 dispatch, Tass said that after Ryzhkov
deserted, he was drugged, nearly starved and visited by lovers of
both sexes with CIA links in an attempt to get him to make
anti-Soviet statements.
   Tass said at that time that Ryzhkov left a military construction
unit in Afghanistan in June 1983, was brought to Pakistan by rebels
and given three choices: slander the Soviet Union in the West; be
executed, or be sent to the Soviet Union where, as a deserter he
was told, no mercy would be shown.
   At a New York news conference in 1984, Ryzhkov said he deserted
because he was tired of the ``dirty war'' in Afghanistan, where
Soviet troops battled anti-Marxist rebels.
   In December 1984, he went to the Soviet Embassy and asked to go
home. His request was granted. Tass did not say then what became of
Ryzhkov, but on Tuesday it quoted a report in the weekly newspaper
Literaturnaya Gazeta that he was in a labor camp.
   Ryzhkov told the newspaper ``he felt much easier in a (labor)
colony than in alien America, that he felt calm,'' according to
Tass.
   The newspaper wrote that Ryzhkov's release shows fear of
punishment should not deter Soviet deserters from returning home.
   Soviet solders entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced
one pro-Soviet government with another and stayed in the country to
help fight Islamic insurgents. The troops began withdrawing May 15.
</TEXT>
