<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mummy-Children     07-12 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mummy-Children,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Tended Husband's Corpse Regains Custody of Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was accused of child neglect
after authorities discovered she had been tending her husband's
corpse nearly nine years has regained custody of her children.
   Knox County Judge Richard Porter restored Carole Stevens'
parental rights following a review of several psychological
examinations conducted on the children, a 17-year-old girl and a
14-year-old boy.
   Porter said the children could return to their mother's home,
where the mummified corpse of Carl L. Stevens was found Jan. 29 _
nearly nine years after his death.
   An autopsy revealed that Stevens, who was a diabetic, died May
12, 1979, at age 39. His brown and shriveled corpse was discovered
in the family home where Mrs. Stevens, 42, had kept it bathed and
clothed.
   Mrs. Stevens, a registered nurse, had tended the corpse with the
help of her two children and a house guest, Richard G. Kunce.
   Authorities said the family's beliefs in a holistic health cult
led them to believe they could communicate with Stevens through the
body and that he would return to life.
   On Feb. 1, Mrs. Stevens and Kunce both pleaded guilty in Knox
County Court to a charge of failing to report the death. Kunce
later changed his plea to innocent. They also were charged with
felony forgery.
   Mrs. Stevens was accused of fabricating a power of attorney for
her dead husband in 1984 and using it to refinance a home mortgage.
Kunce was charged with forgery for signing his name to the document
as a witness.
   Mrs. Stevens pleaded guilty to the forgery charge and was
granted probation. She was ordered to submit to psychiatric
treatment.
   In a separate civil case, Mrs. Stevens admitted she was guilty
of child neglect for allowing her children to live with the corpse.
The children were placed in foster care upon discovery of the body.
</TEXT>
