<HEAD>Iran Says Attack on Cruise Ship Carried Out by CIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greece-Ship Attack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Tuesday the terrorist attack on
a Greek cruise ship in the Aegean Sea may have been carried out by
the CIA to ``whitewash'' the U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner
last week.
   An Iranian Foreign Ministry statement, broadcast by Tehran
Radio, said the United States ``is confronted with a major
difficulty in the face of world public opinion and political and
international circles'' after its Navy shot down the Iran Air A300
Airbus on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard.
   ``In view of the nature of imperialism and its inhuman attitude,
it can be predicted that the American espionage network, the CIA,
and its agents may commit such unpleasant incidents in various
parts of the world in order to whitewash the disaster of the attack
on the Iranian passenger airliner,'' the statement said.
   Eleven people were killed and 98 wounded when three terrorists
opened fire with automatic weapons and hurled grenades aboard the
Greek cruise ship, City of Poros.
   Greek authorities on Tuesday speculated the ship attack may have
been carried out by pro-Iranian Arab terrorists.
   Iran's ambassador to Greece, Habibullah Biazar, denied the
speculation as ``a pack of lies.'' He spoke in an interview in
Athens with Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, quoted him as saying: ``We
categorically condemn such acts of terrorism against innocent
people which damage the interests of a friendly and peace-loving
country like Greece.''
   He denied that an Iranian magazine was found near the site of a
car bomb explosion Monday, six hours before the attack on the ship.
Two people were killed in the blast near Trocadero Marina near
Athens.
   He claimed the magazine was ``an Arabic one.''
</TEXT>
