<2ND_LINE>AM-Andrew Young,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Mayor Addresses Largest Black Sorority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young told the largest
black sorority on Tuesday that America's $152 billion trade deficit
can be blamed on the nation's failure to cooperate with business
people of different races around the globe.
   ``We have a trade deficit because we in big business are still
uncomfortable if the environment is dominated by people of color,''
Young told about 4,000 members of Delta Sigma Theta Sorority.
   ``If we are going to end the trade deficit without death and
conflict, it will be when blacks and whites, male and female, young
and old, Protestant, Catholic and Jew are able to work together,''
said Young.
   The ambassador to the United Nations during the Carter
administration urged members of the world's largest organization of
college-educated black women to extend the ``sisterhood and
teamwork you enjoy in this sorority to the sisters organizing mine
workers and domestic servants in South Africa.''
   Delta was founded at Howard University in 1913 and has about
125,000 members. It's holding its 75th anniversary through
Wednesday at the Civic Auditorium.
</TEXT>
