<DOCNO> AP880712-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-SouthernAfrica     07-12 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Southern Africa,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Official Says Talks Progressing Rapidly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African official on Tuesday
reported rapid progress in meetings with Angolan, Cuban and U.S.
officials on a withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola and ending
South African rule over neighboring Namibia.
   As he boarded a ferry Tuesday morning for a second day of
private talks on Governors Island in New York's harbor, Neil van
Heerden, the head of the South African delegation, was asked about
the progress of the meetings.
   He replied they had developed ``further than Cairo and London,''
the sites of the previous four-party discussions.
   South Africa has said it would accept a U.N. Security Council
resolution calling Namibia's independence under black majority rule
once the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops pull out. Cuban troops are
fighting alongside Angolan government forces against U.S.-backed
anti-communist rebels.
   The head of the Angolan delegation, Gen. Antonio dos Santos
Franca, said of Monday's talks: ``It went well.'' He made the brief
comment while returning to his hotel.
   A news conference is expected Wednesday, according to officials
involved in the talks.
   The four parties first met in London in early May and then
reconvened late last month in Cairo, Egypt. South African and
Angolan officials held a separate meeting in May in Brazzaville,
Congo.
   The timetable for the withdrawal of the Cubans is probably the
most difficult unresolved issue, U.S. officials have said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. goal is a full Cuban troop withdrawal in one year, the
same time span that the U.N. resolution sets for granting
independence to Namibia, also called South-West Africa.
   Angola and Cuba have insisted that the Cuban withdrawal should
take place over four years, but the U.S. officials believe that is
an opening bargaining position that is subject to change as peace
talks proceed.
   Angola has been convulsed by civil war since it gained
independence from Portugal in 1975.
   South Africa has repeatedly sent troops across the border from
Namibia into Angola to support the rebel forces known as UNITA, or
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, in their
clashes with Cuban and Angolan forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     07-12 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz Appeals For Public Support of Stringent Economic Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's Communist Party and
government leader, Karoly Grosz, appealed on Tuesday for public
support of a stringent economic program and harshly criticized the
work of his government over the past year.
   ``What lies ahead are sacrifices for the sake of the future,''
Grosz said on an evening televisoin interview. He said it could
take 10 to 15 years for his program to show results.
   It was the first time a Hungarian government chief has evaluated
his first year in office.
   Grosz said he was ``very dissatisfied'' with the achievements of
the last 12 months despite the efforts to implement a program of
austerity measures and economic restructuring introduced last year.
   Grosz said the government, economic experts and individual
citizens ``have not been working efficiently enough.''
   The 20-minute interview was conducted on the eve of a meeting of
the party Central Committee that is to discuss two alternative
economic programs.
   One would push through radical reforms towards a more
market-oriented economy. This, however, could lead to 80,000 to
100,000 unemployed and result in greater social tensions. The
second would introduce changes more gradually.
   The party newspaper Nepszabadsag published details of the
proposals on Saturday, the first time the agenda of a Central
Committee meeting was published in advance in such detail.
   Grosz said economic restructuring would mean hard times for
Hungarians, as it aims to stop the growth of Hungary's foreign
debt, now totaling $18 billion, by 1990.
   The government this year introduced East Europe's first
value-added and personal income tax as part of its austerity
program. A value-added tax is a form of indirect sales tax.
   ``Parliament and the people are increasingly impatient, and
there is increasing social pressure on the government to do
better,'' Grosz said.
   He appealed to Hungarians to ``understand the need'' for the
program which will include curbs on imports, cuts in subsidies to
loss-making firms and bankruptcy proceedings for those companies
which continue to lose money. Unemployment already is to affect
about 50,000 people this year.
   Grosz said the leadership planned to push ahead with its program
``and is ready to face any tensions that might be involved.'' He
said steps will be taken that ``will strike hard at some sections
of society,'' but that he could ``not afford to be indulgent.''
   He said more attention should be devoted to industries with a
future, such as telecommunications and tourism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
