<DOCNO> AP880712-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnderageGambling     07-12 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Underage Gambling,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Casino Agrees To $100,000 Settlement In Underage Gambling
Complaint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caesars Hotel Casino agreed Tuesday
to donate $100,000 to two state hospitals as a precedent-setting
settlement in a case involving civil charges that the gaming hall
allowed a teen-age girl to gamble.
   Caesars will donate $50,000 each to the John F. Kennedy Medical
Center in Edison and Marlboro State Hospital in Marlboro, both of
which have facilities to treat compulsive gambling.
   The settlement involved a complaint that the gaming hall treated
a 16-year-old girl as a high roller, offering her complimentary
drinks, a hotel room, meals and show tickets.
   Debra Kim Cohen, now 18, pleaded guilty in January to underage
gambling and agreed to attend Gamblers Anonymous meetings as part
of a one-year probationary sentence.
   State Administrative Law Judge Stephen Thompson accepted the
settlement on Tuesday, calling it ``novel and creative.''
   Anthony J. Parrillo, director of the state Division of Gaming
Enforcement, said he was satisfied with the outcome of the
complaint, which also was filed against Caesars and four other
casinos. Elsinore's Atlantis, Resorts International, Harrah's
Marina and Trump Plaza casino hotels are expected to settle their
complaints by the end of this week, he said.
   The $100,000 settlement is the largest that a casino has ever
paid in an underage gambling offense. Prior to Tuesday's agreement,
casinos paid an average of $2,000 per incident, Parrillo said.
   Before the complaints were filed, Parrillo said, ``The problem
of juvenile gambling in this state went largely unnoticed, much
less treated and remedied.''
   ``Not only did the DGE complaint serve to elevate the industry's
consciousness of this serious problem,'' he said, ``but the
settlement we have struck today hopes to achieve some social good
by dedicating substantial monies to mental health facilities in
this state where compulsive gambling and other disorders may be
treated.''
   Lloyd D. Levenson, an attorney for Caesars, said the casino
acknowledged that in Miss Cohen's case, ``our security force broke
down ... which we have since tightened up.''
   Levenson said he was hired to attend municipal court hearings to
push for stiff penalties against underage gamblers who slip past
the casino's security guards.
   ``We want to send a message out to other young people,''
Levenson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
