<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-LowFlights     07-12 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Low Flights,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Rules Out Halt To Low-level Military Training
Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Rupert Scholz ruled
out a ban on low-level NATO training flights Tuesday, despite
growing calls that such flights be drastically reduced or
eliminated after recent accidents.
   ``Low-level flights are necessary to maintain military security
and readiness,'' Scholz was quoted as saying in the illustrated
magazine Quick.
   Citizens groups have charged that in addition to being
dangerous, noise from low level-flights makes life in heavily
affected areas unbearable.
   Last week, the parliament of Rhineland Palatinate state approved
a non-binding resolution calling for an end to the flights.
   Scholz was quoted as saying he is looking for ways to sharply
reduce the number of military training flights within West Germany.
He said one alternative could be to require that pilots spend more
time in flight simulators.
   Another solution could be to expand the flight areas ``outside
the country.'' The Quick article did not elaborate.
   A military expert belonging to Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
governing Christian Democrat Party was quoted as saying other
options include asking NATO pilots to copy West German training
methods of descending to a low altitude only just before the
aircraft reaches its training target.
   Willy Wimmer also was quoted as saying in an interview with the
Augusburg Allgemein newspaper Tuesday that planners are considering
allowing fighters to use now-restricted airspace along the border
with East Germany.
   Wimmer said the restricted area, now 18 miles wide along the
western side of the border, could be reduced.
   Last week, a West German Air Force F-4 Phantom fighter jet
crashed and exploded in a field.
   Two weeks ago, three U.S. Air Force F-16s crashed in one day in
two separate accidents. One pilot was killed when two jets collided
in flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
