<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Duarte     07-12 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Terminally Ill Duarte Returns To Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
resumed work Tuesday at his residence after returning from
treatments in the United States for terminal cancer, aides reported.
   ``The president is working at home,'' said an aide who spoke
with the condition she not be identified. She declined further
comment.
   Duarte, 62, returned Monday from Washington. He had been there
since May 31, undergoing medical evaluations and treatment.
   He was driven to the presidential residence after a brief
welcoming ceremony at the airport. Doctors have said he is
undergoing chemotherapy for cancer of the liver and his life
expectancy is 6-18 months.
   In a statement at the airport, Duarte said, ``I am here now to
reassume the presidency, in order to continue working for what I
most love _ democracy.''
   He vowed to continue the fight against leftist rebels ``in order
to bring peace to my people ... in that way I will make it to the
first of June and hand power over to the one who is elected by the
people.''
   Duarte's five-year term expires June 1, 1989.
   He is the leader of the centrist Christian Democrats, now
divided by two factions that have nominated candidates for the
presidency.
   His party's major opposition is the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance that won a majority of municipal and
legislative elections in March.
   Duarte is to return to the Walter Reed Medical Center in
Washington next month for additional treatment. Salvadoran
officials have said subsequent treatments could be carried out in
El Salvador.
</TEXT>
