<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-ShipBlast     07-12 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Ship Blast,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Says Her Vacationing Daughter Pictured as Accomplice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greece-Ship Attack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French woman said Tuesday her daughter is the
young woman identified as a possible accomplice of terrorists who
attacked a Greek cruise ship, but she denied her daughter was
involved in any terrorism.
   The woman, identifying herself only as Mrs. Bismuth, called the
French news agency Agence France-Presse to say she was certain a
photo she saw on the evening news showing a woman playing cards
with a young man aboard the boat was her daughter. The picture was
distributed by Greek authorities as that of a woman wanted for
possible involvement in the assault.
   She said she had not heard from her daughter since the Monday
attack. Three gunmen on the crowded ship tossed grenades and fired
on passengers, killing 11 and injuring about 100.
   Mrs. Bismuth said her daughter, Isabelle, 21, was a secretary
vacationing in Greece since Saturday and not a terrorist.
   ``I saw the photos of terrorists and I identified my daughter as
the young woman playing cards on the boat with a young man,'' Mrs.
Bismuth said. She added that she was ``sure without a doubt'' this
was her daughter ``and she has no ties with terrorists.''
   The woman said she received a call Tuesday from Isabelle's
traveling companion who told her that ``she lost all trace of my
daughter at the moment of the commando attack. Since then there is
no news of her.''
   Meanwhile, a special plane carrying three French citizens
wounded in the attack arrived in Paris Tuesday night. A second
plane carrying four more seriously wounded French citizens was
expected later.
   The plane was met at Le Bourget airport by Edwige Avice, a
deputy minister attached to the Foreign Affairs Ministry, and by
Greece's ambassador to France.
</TEXT>
