<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PresserFuneral     07-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presser Funeral,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presser Mourned Amid Union Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Teamsters president Jackie
Presser was eulogized at his burial Tuesday as a loyal friend of
the labor movement who was willing to face public scrutiny.
   Presser, who molded a large Teamsters local in Cleveland and
rose to the top job in the 1.6 million-member union, was buried the
same day a federal judge had set for his trial on labor
racketeering and embezzlement charges.
   Presser, 61, died Saturday night in Lakewood Hospital, near
Cleveland. Cardiac arrest was listed as the immediate cause of
death. He had undergone surgery for brain cancer in Phoenix in May.
   The entire executive committee of the International Brotherhood
of Teamsters, including acting president Weldon L. Mathis, attended
the traditional Jewish memorial service and funeral along with at
least 800 of Presser's relatives, friends and admirers.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a ranking member of the Senate Labor
and Human Resources Committee, commended Presser for being the
first Teamsters president to appear before a Senate committee.
   ``He wanted people to know that there were people in the
Teamsters willing to stand up and face the public,'' Hatch said.
``He believed in the labor movement, and he wasn't afraid to stand
up and say so. ... I chaired those hearings, and I know what he
went through.''
   Hatch described Presser as a powerful labor leader whose
accomplishments included bringing the Teamsters back into the
AFL-CIO.
   ``Like the rest of us, Jackie Presser made some mistakes, and
given the option to relive his life he would probably make some
changes. But wouldn't we all?'' Hatch said. ``I hope he will be
remembered for what he accomplished.''
   Cleveland Mayor George V. Voinovich, a Republican senatorial
candidate in Ohio, eulogized Presser as a major civic force.
   ``I will remember Jackie Presser as a man who cared about his
city. I will miss him and pray for him,'' Voinovich said.
   Presser was named as a defendant, along with the union's
executive board, in a lawsuit filed two weeks ago by the U.S.
government that seeks to place the union under the supervision of a
court-appointed trustee. A federal judge last week rejected a
Justice Department request to have a monitor police the union's
operations.
   At the time of his death, Presser was awaiting trial on felony
charges that he participated in a $700,000 payroll-padding scheme
at Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland, a 5,000-member local created
in the 1960s. Presser remained as secretary-treasurer of the local
while running the national union from Washington D.C.
   His trial was to have begun Tuesday, but was delayed because of
his failing health. Co-defendants Harold Friedman, a Teamsters vice
president and Local 507 president, and Anthony Hughes, the local's
recording secretary, are to face trial Oct. 12.
   Presser claimed he was an FBI informant and that the FBI
authorized the hiring of ``ghost employees'' at Local 507.
   Mathis, the union's secretary-treasurer, indicated the executive
committee will meet Friday to discuss who should fill out the
remainder of Presser's term as president, which runs until 1991.
</TEXT>
