<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Jews     07-12 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jews,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader Wants ``No Strings Attached'' East German
Reparations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edgar M. Bronfman, head of the World Jewish
Congress, said Tuesday a ``good chance'' exists of reaching
agreement this fall on East German reparations to Holocaust
survivors.
   But he expressed some reservations about the East German
proposal during a visit to Berlin, and said payments must be on a
``no strings attached'' basis.
   He also called on Austrians to face up to their country's Nazi
past.
   Bronfman is on a three-day visit to West Berlin and West Germany
that includes a meeting with Chancellor Helmut Kohl in Bonn.
   In 1952, West Germany agreed with the New York-based World
Jewish Congress to compensate victims of the Nazi Holocaust. Since
then officials in Bonn have paid out more than $48 billion to
survivors and their families.
   The Communist East German government had argued that because
East Germany came into existence as a nation in 1949, it had no
legal responsibility for the atrocities of Adolf Hitler's regime.
   More than 6 million Jews were killed during Hitler's Third Reich.
   Diplomatic sources at the United Nations, speaking on condition
of anonymity, have said East Germany's refusal to pay reparations
or accept legal responsibility for war crimes has been a major
stumbling block in improving relations with the United States.
   Then on June 8 the East German government announced it was
willing to provide ``humanitarian aid'' to Jewish survivors.
   The amount being discussed is up to $100 million, according to
West Berlin Jewish leaders. Details of the plan have not been made
public.
   Bronfman said of the plan Tuesday: ``We'll have to see what it's
hooked up to. ... It's not clear to me that it's as open-handed as
it might be. I just want to make sure that there are no strings
attached.''
   Asked if he doubted the East Germans' good faith, Bronfman
replied: ``No.''
   He confirmed he was invited to visit Communist East German
leader Erich Honecker and said he assumed the trip would take place
in the fall.
   Asked if he would conclude a reparations agreement with the East
Germans in the autumn, Bronfman said: ``There's a good chance.''
   The head of the World Jewish Congress praised West Germany for
its efforts to face up to the Nazi past, saying: ``It's a pleasure
to come to a country where you see what West German governments
since (Chancellor Konrad) Adenauer have done to discuss the
Holocaust and teach children about it.''
   He added, ``Austria sits there as if they never took part in it
(the Holocaust) at all. It talks about itself as the first victim.
That's all such nonsense and that has to be changed.''
   About 36,500 Jews still live in West Berlin and West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
