<DOCNO> AP880712-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     07-12 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guild Sues Producers for Allegedly Interfering with Independents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The striking Writers Guild of
America sued over a dozen leading producers Tuesday, claiming they
are interfering illegally with guild efforts to sign contracts with
independent producers.
   The guild's antitrust lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court,
named 19 defendants, including the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers, the three television networks and several
Hollywood studios, including Disney, Universal and Colombia.
   Guild attorneys said the defendants had ``refused to deal'' with
some of the 151 independents that have signed interim contracts
with the WGA.
   The suit alleges that such conduct is anti-competitive. It seeks
a court declaration that the defendants violated federal antitrust
statutes and that they be ordered to halt such alleged activity.
   ``I think it is appropriate that we respond in this way,'' WGA
West Executive Director Brian Walton said at a news conference at
guild headquarters.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said the allegations in the
suit ``have no merit.
   ``The action only diverts attention from the real issue, which
is resolving the strike,'' Steinberg said.
   Representatives of independent film companies have complained to
the guild of pressure to reject interim agreements, union officials
said.
   All three networks have vowed publicly to refuse programming
produced by the independents during the strike, now in its 19th
week. The strike already has forced the networks to delay the start
of their fall programming season.
   The producers' behavior ``is sad and lacks compassion,'' guild
president George Kirgo said.
   ``That the alliance continues to refuse to compromise wreaks
enough havoc. To conspire to prevent others from making a fair deal
which would employee men and women in this industry is
unconscionable.''
   The producers alliance has said that its last contract offer,
which the WGA rejected by a 3-1 margin on June 22, is final. The
two sides are divided over payments for reruns of one-hour shows
domestically and all programs overseas. The strike has resulted in
sweeping layoffs throughout the entertainment industry.
   A spokesman for a dissident group of scriptwriters called the
Writers Coalition reacted negatively to the lawsuit.
   ``We are tremendously distressed that (at this point) in the
strike, recourse is being left to the courts. It seems to indicate
a lack of urgency,'' he said.
   The coalition, which claims to include over 300 of the WGA's
9,000 members, believes talks between the union and the producers
are stalled and plans to meet Thursday night in Santa Monica to
discuss writers' ``options,'' the spokesman said. He declined to
say what those options might be.
   ``There comes a point in time where working members can no
longer take the losses,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
