<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-US     07-12 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-US,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Approves First Extradition Since 1961</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry announced Tuesday that
Mexico has approved a U.S.-requested extradition for a West German
woman wanted in connection with a major 1984 drug trafficking case.
   A U.S. Embassy official said it was the first time in 27 years
that Mexico has permitted such an extradition.
   The official, said speaking on condition of anonymity. said U.S.
marshals will arrive next week to escort Veronica Kiera-Wahl to
Atlanta, where the case is pending in federal court.
   The Foreign Ministry said the government's decision to grant the
request ``confirms its decision to cooperate in the sanctioning of
all types of crimes of (an) international (nature) and, in this
particular case, those that signify the fight against drug
trafficking.''
   U.S. Ambassador Charles J. Pilliod Jr. was recalled to
Washington for consultations last month after Mexico released
Puerto Rican separatist William Morales from jail and let him fly
to Cuba. The United States wants Morales as a terrorist bomber and
the State Department expressed ``outrage'' at his release.
   A ministry statement said Mexico approved the Kiera-Wahl
extradition on June 30. It said Ms. Kiera-Wahl, reportedly born in
Breslau, Germany, in 1942, took part in a shipment of approximately
13,000 pounds of cocaine from Colombia to the United States between
March and September 1982.
   The U.S. Embassy official said Ms. Kiera-Wahl is wanted in
connection with a 1984 Tampa, Fla., cocaine case involving Harold
Joseph Rosenthal.
   Rosenthal, a former Atlanta bail bondsman, was sentenced to life
in prison without parole and fined $425,000 after being convicted
in October 1984 on charges stemming from what prosecutors at the
time called the largest cocaine ring in the United States.
   Prosecutors said the ring imported $3.8 billion worth of cocaine
into the United States during a 14-month period ending in 1984,
using airplanes to fly in the drugs from South America and from the
Caribbean.
   Rosenthal said he was working for the CIA and ran the drug
operation as part of his duties.
   Also convicted were Robert Edward Dunleavy of Coral Springs,
Fla.; George Lombardi of Margate, Fla.; Garland Hubert Watson of
Rockwood, Tenn.; Larry Roger Stewart of Dalton, Ga.; and Rose Marie
Junker and Joseph Junker, both of Philadelphia.
   The Mexican statement said the United States asked for Ms.
Kiera-Wahl's extradition on Sept. 8, 1987.
   It said the first district federal judge in Yucatan state,
Francisco Javier Patino Perez, on May 20 ruled against a petition
by Ms. Kiera-Wahl that sought her exclusion from the provisions of
the extradition treaty. Ms. Kiera-Wahl did not appeal the decision,
the statement said.
   The embassy official said the Foreign Ministry advised that it
had no objection to the extradition request for Ms. Kiera-Wahl.
   Mexican authorities took her into custody on the Yucatan
peninsula at the West German government's request, the embassy
official said.
   About a dozen U.S. extradition cases are pending with the
Mexican government, the official said.
   In the Morales case, Morales, 37, got time off for good behavior
and was released after serving five years of an eight-year sentence
for his role in the murder of a Mexican policeman.
   The Foreign Ministry decided the case was not covered by the
U.S.-Mexican extradition treaty.
</TEXT>
