<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Strike     07-12 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Strike,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Disperse Peasants Supporting Striking Electrical Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops used tear gas and clubs
Tuesday to disperse peasants delivering food to striking electrical
workers.
   Marco Tulio Lima, president of the independent Confederation of
Cooperative Associations, told reporters two people were beaten by
soldiers and two were detained.
   The armed forces press office issued a statement saying the
electrical workers and peasants provoked a confrontation by
damaging vehicles and that air force troops were sent to the scene
``to insure order.''
   It said two troopers were struck by demonstrators and one union
member, identified as Fidel Angel Quintanilla, was arrested.
   Lima and witnesses said about 100 members of the agricultural
cooperatives went to a plant of the state-owned CEL electrical
utility in the San Salvador suburb of Soyapango and delivered sacks
of rice, beans and other foodstuffs to the electrical workers.
   They said a truck carrying about 30 soldiers arrived and the
troopers fired tear gas at the peasants and then attacked with
clubs.
   CEL repair workers have been reporting to work but refusing to
carry out their duties.
   About 3,500 CEL repair and maintenance workers went on strike
June 15 demanding salary increases and improved vacation and
life-insurance benefits.
   They are asking for pay boosts averaging $60 a month, $4 per day
for job-related travel expenses and $10,000 in personal life
insurance. They said mines planted near utility towers by leftist
guerrillas battling the U.S.-backed government make their jobs
hazardous.
   Rene Rodriguez, president of the CEL Employees' Association,
said on July 2 that five technicians have been killed and five
disabled by exploding mines.
   CEL officials have refused to negotiate with the strikers,
saying the association has no legal standing. The union was legally
dissolved after a strike in 1980 that the company said was
organized by leftists.
   Average salaries for the maintenance and repair workers range
from $140 to $200 per month.
   On July 3, strike leaders sent emergency crews to repair damage
from guerrilla sabotage that blacked out most of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
