<NOTE>For Release Friday, July 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts in next-to-last graf psychiatrist Karl Menninger is
95 on July 22. `Cleaveland'' in 6th graf cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, July 22, the 204th day of 1988. There are 162
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 22, 1934, bank robber John Dillinger was shot to death
by federal agents outside Chicago's Biograph Theater, where he had
just seen the Clark Gable movie ``Manhattan Melodrama.''
Dillinger's violent end capped a 14-month crime spree that earned
him celebrity as well as notoriety.
   On this date:
   In 1587, a second English colony _ also fated to vanish under
mysterious circumstances _ was established on Roanoke Island off
North Carolina.
   In 1796, Cleveland, Ohio, was founded by Gen. Moses Cleaveland.
   In 1812, English troops under the Duke of Wellington defeated
the French at the Battle of Salamanca in Spain.
   In 1844, Anglican clergyman William Archibald Spooner was born
in London. Spooner, who became warden of New College, Oxford,
gained a reputation for transposing words or parts of words while
speaking _ errors that came to be known as ``spoonerisms.''
   In 1916, a bomb went off during a Preparedness Day parade in San
Francisco, killing 10 people.
   In 1933, American aviator Wiley Post completed the first solo
flight around the world in seven days, 18} hours.
   In 1937, the Senate rejected President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
proposal to enlarge the Supreme Court.
   In 1942, gasoline rationing began in the United States during
World War II.
   In 1943, Allied forces captured Palermo, Sicily.
   In 1975, the House of Representatives joined the Senate in
voting to restore the American citizenship of Confederate Gen.
Robert E. Lee, more than a century after his death.
   In 1981, Turkish terrorist Mehmet Ali Agca was sentenced in a
Rome court to life in prison for shooting Pope John Paul II.
   In 1986, for the first time in half a century, the House of
Representatives impeached a federal official. Judge Harry E.
Claiborne was later convicted by the Senate of tax evasion and
bringing disrepute on the federal courts.
   Ten years ago: President Anwar Sadat of Egypt delivered a speech
in which he said the only obstacle to Middle East peace was what he
termed the ``expansionist ambitions'' of Israeli Prime Minister
Menachem Begin.
   Five years ago: Clicking her heels like Dorothy in ``The Wizard
of Oz'' and sighing, ``There's no place like home,'' Samanatha
Smith returned with her parents to their house in Manchester,
Maine, having completed a whirlwind, two-week tour of the Soviet
Union.
   One year ago: The United States began its policy of escorting
re-flagged Kuwaiti tankers up and down the Persian Gulf to protect
them from possible attack by Iran.
   Today's birthdays: Rose Kennedy is 98. Psychiatrist Karl
Menninger is 95. Sen. William Roth, R.-Del., is 67. Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole, R.-Kan., is 65. Singer Margaret Whiting is 64.
Actor-comedian Orson Bean is 60. Fashion designer Oscar de la Renta
is 56. Actor Terence Stamp is 48. Game show host Alex Trebek is 48.
Actor-singer Bobby Sherman is 43. Actor-comedian-director Albert
Brooks is 41.
   Thought for today: ``There are as many nights as days, and the
one is just as long as the other in the year's course. Even a happy
life cannot be without a measure of darkness, and the word `happy'
would lose its meaning if it were not balanced by sadness.'' _ Dr.
Carl Jung, Swiss psychiatrist (1875-1961).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
