<2ND_LINE>BC-Delegate Profile, Adv 17,0566</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Typical Democratic Delegate: White, Middle-Aged, Well-Educated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer than a dozen politicians are among the
delegates to the 1988 Democratic National Convention, the party's
biggest political event.
   At least that's how many own up to being politicians.
   An Associated Pess survey of more than 3,200 of the 4,161
delegates to the convention found that while nearly 1,000 of them
hold elected offices _ including hundreds of members of Congress
and dozens of governors and mayors _ only a handful list their
occupation as ``politician.''
   To be exact, there are nine of them.
   They join nearly 300 lawyers, 100 retired people, an actor, a
cook and a casket manufacturer this week as they cram into the
cramped auditorium of the Omni to nominate Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis for president.
   Of the delegates _ who hail from all 50 states, the District of
Columbia, and five U.S. territories _ the typical convention-goer
is white, middle-aged and college-educated. Almost two-thirds of
them have not been delegates before, the AP survey found.
   Their average age is 47, some 67 percent went to college and 69
percent are white. Twenty-one percent are black and almost 5
percent are Hispanic.
   Under Democratic Party rules, the delegate seats are divided
equally among men and women, and while there are no firm quotas,
state parties were encouraged to recruit enough minorities so the
racial mix of the delegation roughly parallels that of the state's
Democratic voters.
   Still, there was some irritation at the party's affirmative
action program.
   ``We went from unfair to more unfair,'' said Morton Povman, a
Dukakis delegate from New York. ``Under the rules, a person can get
the most votes and be elected by the people and yet not be selected
as a delegate, not because Dukakis doesn't want you, but because if
you're a white Catholic and they have enough white Catholics,
they'll pick a black whatever.''
   While no floor fights are expected over the presidential
nomination, credentials challenges or changes to the rules, the
delegates come to town with a lot weighing on their minds.
   A sampling of those surveyed by the AP found that about a third
of them are worried about the federal budget deficit, unemployment,
foreign trade or the economy in general. Next on the list is
combatting the flow of illegal drugs into the United States,
followed by education and the twin issues of world peace and
nuclear arms control.
   ``I have a son who would be of age to go into service,'' said
Hilda Bourg, a Dukakis delegate from Mississippi. ``I want to keep
the nation at peace.''
   Asked his opinion of the nation's No. 1 issue, Charles Logsdon,
a sheriff from Elizabethtown, Ky., replied: ``As someone in law
enforcement, drugs. I think we need to quit calling it a war and
make it one.''
   Even with few issues to be fought out and so few self-confessed
politicians in attendance, politics _ that nasty business _ found
its way into the process.
   Asked if she thought the Democrats had devised a fair way of
picking delegates, Cyrel Foote, a Jackson delegate from Kansas,
complained: ``No, there's a lot of politics involved.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
