<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in moderate European trading
early today amid signs of renewed intervention by central banks to
prevent its advance. Gold prices fell.
   Dealers in Rome said the West German and Belgian central banks
were rumored to have sold dollars on the open market, but they said
other central banks had not been sighted in early trading.
   Some dealers said they expected the dollar to settle within a
narrow range before Friday's release of U.S. merchandise trade
figures for May.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.63 Japanese yen to a closing 132.70 yen.
Later, in London, it edged back to 132.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.8392 West German marks, down from 1.8460;
1.5273 Swiss francs, down from 1.5350; 6.1937 French francs, down
from 6.2080; 2.0737 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0750; 1,363.50
Italian lire, down from 1,364.50; 1.2067 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2080.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6922 from $1.6900.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $435.50 a troy ounce, up
from $435.10 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $434.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $434.30, down from $435.50 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.41 to close at a bid $437.63.
   Silver bullion eased in London to a bid price of $6.93 a troy
ounce, down from $6.94 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
