<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Trade     07-12 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Continues to Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus shrank 16 percent during the
first half of 1988 as booming imports outstripped a moderate
increase in exports, the Finance Ministry reported Tuesday.
   Analysts said the United States was a major beneficiary of the
increased imports.
   The ministry said in its preliminary report Japan's trade
surplus during the first six months of the year was $33.7 billion,
or $6.4 billion less than in the first half of 1987.
   In June, the country had a surplus of $5.92 billion, down $668.3
million from the same month last year.
   Japan's surplus with the United States dipped 14.9 percent, from
$24.6 billion to $20.9 billion for the first half of this year
compared with the same period in 1987.
   The ministry attributed the rapid decline in Japan's trade
surplus to the steep increase in imports, fueled by the nearly 100
percent rise in the value of the Japanese yen against the U.S.
dollar in the last three years.
   The stronger yen made foreign products cheaper in Japan and
Japanese products more expensive abroad.
   The rising yen boosted the country's imports by 34.3 percent to
$91.8 billion for the first six months of 1988 on a custom-cleared
basis, while exports rose 15.7 percent to $125.4 billion.
   The statistics showed American exporters, bolstered by the weak
dollar, are increasing their sales in Japan faster than European
and Asian exporters. The United States is Japan's largest trading
partner.
   Sumio Hoga, director of the ministry's export department, said
Americans sold more office equipment, aircraft and capital goods to
Japanese while Japanese automobile exports to the United States
continued its downward trend.
   ``The United States is clearly a beneficiary of the yen
appreciation,'' said David Gerstenhaber, a senior economist with
Morgan Stanley International in Tokyo. ``American exports to Japan
is clearly outstripping its imports from Japan ... and the trend is
very unlikely to change.''
   Analysts see the decline in Japan's surplus and its increase in
imports as the beginning of a long trend.
   ``The figures for the first six months confirmed that Japan is
streadily heading the way to becoming an importing country,'' said
Josen Takahashi, a chief analyst at Mitsubishi Research Institute,
a Tokyo think tank.
   ``Imports are growing at much faster pace than we expected. It
seems like a matter of time until Japan's account marks a
deficit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
