<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-InsiderTrading-Sturm 1stLd-Writethru   07-12 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Sturm, 1st Ld-Writethru,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Omaha Executive Settles Insider Trading Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: REWRITES throughout to show Sturm was allegedly tipped by
daughter who worked for Drexel Burnham Lambert.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald L. Sturm, a top executive of Peter Kiewit
Sons Inc., has settled civil charges he helped a friend trade on
inside information that Sturm received from his daughter, then
employed by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Sturm, 56, vice chairman of the Omaha, Neb.-based construction
and manufacturing company, signed an agreement Monday to settle a
civil insider trading lawsuit filed the same day by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
   Under the agreement, which doesn't include an admission of
guilt, Sturm will pay the government more than $282,000 in illegal
profit and penalties.
   Sturm also issued a statement denying any wrongdoing and
asserting he chose to settle the suit to halt a protracted battle.
   The SEC's complaint accused Sturm of getting non-public
information from a relative then employed by an unidentified
investment bank about the corporate takeover of a North Carolina
air cargo service.
   Sturm allegedly passed the information to an unidentified friend
who bought 30,000 shares of stock with money loaned by Sturm and
made $128,412 in trading profits, the SEC stated.
   The SEC did not allege t95  +.45
 Mon.'s sales 6,097.               
 Mon.'s open int 17,142, off 214.      
</TEXT>
