<2ND_LINE>BC-Allegheny International,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sale Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said Tuesday it
intends to sell its semiconductor equipment business to Silicon
Valley Group Inc. for undisclosed terms.
   The parties signed a letter of intent today and will attempt to
negotiate a definitive agreement and win the approval of both
boards of directors, government regulators and the federal
bankruptcy judge overseeing Allegheny International's Chapter 11
reorganization.
   The unit, Thermco Systems Inc., employs about 450 people in
Orange, Cerritos and Hayward, California, making equipment used in
the manufacture of semiconductors. Thermco also has small offices
in West Germany, England and Hong Kong.
   Silicon Valley Group, headquartered in San Jose, Calif., makes
production equipment for the semiconductor industry. It employs
about 390 people.
   Allegheny International is restructuring to concentrate on
consumer products in North America. It intends to change its name
to Sunbeam, reflecting its Sunbeam appliance subsidiary.
</TEXT>
