<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed To Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed to higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, recovering slightly from
Monday's steep losses in cautious trading ahead of an eagerly
awaited crop report.
   The Agriculture Department report, due out after the close, was
to include revised production estimates for wheat, corn and
soybeans.
   The USDA normally does not revise its springtime production
estimates until August. But government experts decided to revise
the figures in today's report to reflect the effects of the drought.
   Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in
Chicago, predicted the USDA would be conservative in estimating
drought damage.
   ``This report will be based on computer models,'' he said.
``Once you get into the August report, you have extension agents
going out in the fields and doing some sample surveys.''
   Prices for grain and soybean futures fell sharply Monday in
reaction to weekend rains in the Corn Belt and forecasts for more
showers this week.
   In early trading, wheat was 3} cents to 5\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.72 a bushel; corn was 1} cents
lower to 7} cents higher with July at $2.96 a bushel; oats were 5{
cents lower to 11 cents higher with July at $2.77 a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents lower to 14 cents higher with July at $8.72 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .37 cent lower to .25 cent higher with
August at 66.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .55
cent lower with August at 75.70 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent
lower to .57 cent higher with July at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .08 cent to .55 cent higher with July at 33.10
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Monday while pork
futures were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
