   The stock market drifted lower today as
investors showed concern over interest rates and trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 12.63 points to
2,098.68 by noon on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers 12 to 5 in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 369 up, 890 down and 541
unchanged.
   Stock market investors have dwelled lately on the possibility
that the Federal Reserve will push up interest rates as a way to
cool the economy and stave off inflation.
   Concerns about rising interest rates have dampened the stock
market because more attractive yields on bonds could siphon money
away from stocks. Also, high rates could hurt stock prices by
slowing economic growth.
   ``This is a market that's back-pedaling,'' said Alan Ackerman,
an investment strategist for Gruntal & Co. ``Anxiety over higher
interest rates is keeping players on the sidelines as well as
stalling some of the summer sizzle that appears to lie ahead.''
   Traders also appeared cautious in advance of Friday's release of
figures on the May merchandise trade deficit.
   The heaviest trading was related to dividend-capture strategies.
Centerior Energy had more than 9 million shares change hands in
early trading. Puget Sound Power & Light and New York State
Electric & Gas each had more than 4 million shares traded.
   Coleco Industries was unchanged at 1~. The company announced it
had sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
Bankruptcy Code.
   Xidex rose 1] to 9 in over-the-counter trading. The maker of
computer disk drives said it agreed to be acquired by Anacomp for
$10 a share in cash. Anacomp was off } to 10\ on the NYSE.
   Among other over-the-counter stocks, Intel was up ~ to 35{ after
reporting its earnings nearly tripled in the latest quarter. Micron
Technology was off } to 23[ on news that two top officers resigned.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.88 to 152.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index fell 0.91 to 307.67.
   Volume on the Big Board, swelled by dividend-related trading,
came to 84.17 million shares as of noon on Wall Street, against
64.32 million shares at the same time Monday.
