<DOCNO> AP880712-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EnergyEfficiency     07-12 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Energy Efficiency,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Group Urges New Push For Efficiency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next administration should push for new
gains in energy efficiency, and without sacrifice for conscientious
consumers, an advocacy group said Tuesday.
   Such a goal should incorporate an auto fuel-economy requirement
of 45 miles per gallon, a 50-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax increase
and a high ``gas-guzzler'' tax to be rebated to buyers of fuel
efficient cars, said the American Council for an Energy-Efficient
Economy.
   The report, produced by a panel of environmentalists, academics
and business executives, argued that abundant opportunities for
efficiency gains are the best way to counter several threats at
once _ acid rain, excessive dependence on imported oil,
international competition and the ``greenhouse'' warming of the
earth by man-made gases, notably the carbon dioxide produced by
burning fossil fuels.
   Also Tuesday, a related report was issued by the Safe Energy
Communications Council, an advocacy group supported by several
environmental organizations and others, arguing that nuclear power
has had virtually no effect in holding down oil use ``and cannot
have any substantial impact in the foreseeable future.''
   The communications council also argued for a 45 mpg fuel-economy
standard, to be raised to 60 mpg in the year 2008.
   Unlike many reports advocating the pursuit of efficiency, the
study by the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy
explicitly argued that efficiency should be pursued only as long as
it's cost-effective _ with environmental and balance-of-trade costs
taken into account.
   Some of the authors told a news conference that point is a long
way away.
   ``The opportunities are proliferating ... the marketing folks
haven't been able to keep up with the engineers,'' said Howard
Geller, associate director of the council.
   Asked which party was more likely to be receptive to the
recommendations, Geller said, ``We would hope any administration
would accept this agenda and push it forward.''
   ``It's been a great disaster that conservation has been
associated with sitting in the dark,'' said another author, Robert
Socolow, director of the Center for Energy and Environmental
Studies at Princeton University.
   The report listed 10 improvements it considered still possible,
the largest being transmissions with continuously variable gear
ratios, estimated to improve efficiency by 12 percent. The second
best improvement, at 8 percent, would be engines with four valves
per cylinder. That design already has been incorporated in several
models in the past two or three years.
   Cars currently must get 26 mpg, and buyers will not demand
mileage above about 30 mpg because annual savings are small, the
authors said. The higher standards could mean cars would cost $200
to $800 more initially, but this would be recovered over the
lifetime of the car in reductions in operating costs, they said.
   A 50-cent tax would make sure ``consumers are given a price
signal that better reflects the real cost of the resource and
encourages conservation,'' and some of the $40 billion to $60
billion raised each year could be returned to the poor through
income tax provisions.
   The tax should be imposed in increments of 10 cents per year for
five years, the report said. If oil prices double, the tax should
be held to 30 cents. If fuel efficiency gains are disappointing,
the tax could climb higher.
   The gas-guzzler tax, which currently can exceed $2,000 for
certain luxury cars, should be broadened to raise funds for
rebates, perhaps $1,000, on fuel-efficent cars, the report said.
   The rebates could apply to models 50 percent better than today's
best, the report said. This would imply payments for cars getting
about 75 mpg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0269 </DOCNO>
