<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0028 07-12 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell Tuesday on the London Stock
Exchange in a spiritless session without market-moving news before
the release of U.S. and British economic data later in the week.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 18.3
points, or 0.1 percent, lower at 1,858.5.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 12.80
points at 2,098.51 as London trading drew to a close, after opening
about 4 points higher. London traders said Wall Street's wobbly
performance punctuated an already declining British stock market.
   Dealers said the London market lacked a sense of direction and
there was a lack of news to spur share prices.
   ``There's really so little going on,'' said Roger Charlesworth,
senior dealer at Chase Manhattan Securities in London, adding: ``a
lethargy is beginning to creep into this market.''
   Economic data due for release later in the week kept players
cautious and sidelined. Of particular concern was Thursday's spate
of British corporate earnings reports and figures on British
unemployment, average earnings and industrial output, as well as
Friday's release of U.S. trade data for May and the British retail
price index for June.
   Lower crude oil prices weighed down oil company shares, as
takeover hopes within the sector were dashed, analysts said. Weak
oil prices were beginning to ``take the steam out'' of the rampant
takeover talk that has permeated the sector over recent weeks, said
Chris Chaitow, a technical stock analyst with Morgan Grenfell
Securities in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
