<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-12 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed moderately
higher Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in cautious trading
ahead of an eagerly awaited crop report.
   ``Overall, by recent standards, it was a fairly dull session,''
said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst in New York with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co.
   The rally was basically a technical rebound after three days of
sharply lower prices, Spilka said.
   He said gains probably were limited by edginess over the
Agriculture Department crop report, which was released after the
close.
   News that the report's revised production estimates for corn,
soybeans and spring wheat would be based on conditions as of
Tuesday instead of July 1 prompted a buying flurry early in the
session, Spilka said.
   In the report, the agency estimated 1988 soybean production at
1.65 billion bushels, compared with a June estimate of 1.88 billion
and 1987 production of 1.9 billion bushels.
   This year's corn harvest was estimated at 5.2 billion bushels,
compared with the June estimate of 7.3 billion and year-ago
production of 7.1 billion.
   Production of all U.S. wheat this year was estimated at 1.84
billion bushels, compared with the June estimate of 2.12 billion
and 1987 production of 2.1 billion.
   At the close, wheat was 9\ cents to 12} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.79 a bushel; corn was 12\ cents
to 17\ cents higher with July at $3.05{ a bushel; oats were 1{
cents to 18 cents higher with July at $2.84 a bushel; soybeans were
10{ cents to 26 cents higher with July at $8.84 a bushel.
</TEXT>
