<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-Bonds     07-12 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Bonds,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela Postpones Payments on Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela has unilaterally postponed
payments on as much as $850 million in Republic of Venezuela bonds
scheduled to mature this year, the Finance Ministry said Tuesday.
   The five-year bonds, issued in 1983, will be paid between May
1990 and June 1992, according to the government's Official Gazette
of June 14. The bonds had originally been scheduled to mature in
June of this year.
   The notes subject to postponement are held by Venezuelan
government entities, and their non-payment should not affect the
nation's credit rating, foreign bankers in Caracas said.
   The government paid off another $100 million in Republic of
Venezuela bonds maturing this year that were held by private
investors, a Finance Ministry source said.
   The payment delay comes as the government attempts to safeguard
its reserves of foreign currencies in the face of declining oil
income. Finance Minister Hector Hurtado has estimated that
Venezuela will have a balance-of-payments deficit this year of
around $4 billion.
   Hurtado is in Washington this week for meetings with the world
banking community, the ministry said. He is scheduled to meet with
officials of the World Bank and the InterAmerican Development Bank,
and will sign a $71.6 million IADB credit for road repair.
</TEXT>
