<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Brokers     07-12 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Brokers,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merrill Lynch Net Off 36 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch & Co. on Tuesday said lower
financial activity contributed to a 36 percent drop in its
second-quarter profit.
   Merrill Lynch, one of the nation's largest investment houses,
said net income totaled $53.5 million, or 47 cents a share, in the
second quarter, compared with earnings of $83.3 million, or 75
cents a share, a year ago.
   Revenue during the quarter rose 8 percent, to $2.5 billion from
$2.3 billion in the second quarter of 1987.
   William Schreyer, chairman and chief executive officer, said the
results were ``reasonable considering the difficult business
environment experienced during the quarter.''
   He said the period was marked by ``a relatively lower level of
activity in the financial markets.''
   Commission revenues in the second quarter declined 35 percent to
$393 million ``due to reduced stock market activity,'' the company
said in a statement.
   Investment banking revenue also declined _ down 13 percent to
$256 million _reflecting a lower level of mergers and acqusitions
closings.
   But record fixed-income activity drove principal transaction
revenue to $388 million, compared with a loss of $133 million a
year ago.
   Insurance revenues of $85 million and asset management and
custodial fee revenues of $122 million were little changed from the
previous year.
   Daniel Tully, president and chief operating officer, said the
company is confident ``the cost-control and productivity
improvement measures put into place during the first half are on
course.''
   For the first six months of 1988, net earnings totaled $122
million, or $1.08, off 36 percent from $192 million, or $1.72 a
share in the first half of 1987.
   Revenue for the first six months totaled $4.9 billion, up 1
percent from $4.8 billion in the year-ago period.
</TEXT>
