<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern-Pilots 1stLd-Writethru   07-12 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Pilots, 1st Ld-Writethru,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Rejects Pilots' Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 5 new final grafs to UPDATE with additional pilot
reaction; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines management was unimpressed with a
four-year contract offer from its pilots, who claim they are
offering $51.5 million a year in cost savings to the airline, an
Eastern spokesman said Tuesday.
   ``The arithmetic they (the pilots) used totally distorts the
proposal,'' Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said. ``The main point
(is) they've hit us with a proposal that would increase our costs.''
   He said Eastern's calculations have found that the pilots'
proposal would increase the airline's costs by $116 million
annually. Matell added that overall, cumulative increases in the
pilots' offer would raise Eastern's costs by 33 percent.
   The pilots contended that the 5 percent increases in pay, along
with stock, they are requesting would be more than offset by
money-saving concessions in productivity rules and vacations.
   ``It would give (Eastern) some form of economic relief and at
the same time, protect our pilots,'' said spokesman J.B. Stokes of
the Air Line Pilots Association local representing about 3,500
Eastern pilots. ``We think it's very fair.''
   Eastern, losing an estimated $1 million daily, has said it must
have wage and work-rule concessions from its three unions to cut
labor costs by around 30 percent overall. The pilots' current
contract became amendable this month.
   Eastern has been in federal mediation with its largest union,
the 12,000-member Machinists, for nearly seven months.
   The pilots' proposal was designed to halt a ``downsizing'' of
Eastern that's seen a steady reduction in the number of flights.
The pilots estimate that by summer's end, nearly 1,000 Eastern
pilots will have left the airline since the 1986 takeover by giant
Texas Air Corp. _ many because of tense labor-management relations
and uncertainty about the carrier's future.
   The pilots' proposal would include a ``fence agreement'' keeping
Eastern separate from Continental Airlines, a nonunion carrier also
owned by Houston-based Texas Air. Eastern unions say Texas Air
wants to strip Eastern of its assets.
   The pilots' offer also calls for three 5 percent pay increases
and one 3 percent raise, plus shares in Texas Air stock, over the
life of the proposed four-year contract.
   One of the most critical proposals involves payment of an
unspecified amount of money to pilots who have yet to take a
vacation this year, the pilots said. Pilots would receive five days
of vacation and be compensated for the rest. Those pilots who have
taken a vacation this year would receive an unspecified amount of
cash for any remaining vacation time due them.
   This proposal alone would save Eastern $11 million, according to
ALPA.
   But Matell said it would be cheaper to hire new pilots.
   ``The pilot shortage thing is a myth. We have enough pilots to
fly the schedule we intend to operate,'' Matell said.
   Under the present contract, a pilot can fly 84 hours per month.
Under the proposal, that would rise to 88 hours and go as high as
90 hours under a so-called buffer provision.
   That provision, according to ALPA, would save the airline
another $9.5 millon annually. But Matell said the pilots want
time-and-a-half for the extra hours.
   A third element that would make more efficient use of the pilots
would save the company another $31 million yearly, ALPA said.
Matell said Eastern calculated the savings at only $6.7 million.
   Stokes, after hearing of Matell's remarks, said ALPA stands by
its calculations.
   ``That's certainly not the way it prints out,'' Stokes said of
Eastern's figures.
   ``We felt and still do that it's a very positive approach that
would save the company some money,'' Stokes said, adding that the
pilots' other priorities include maintaining Eastern as a large,
separate airline.
   He said Eastern management hasn't presented its own offer.
   ``They have not made a formal proposal as yet. That's just
delaying the negotiations,'' said Stokes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880712-0278 </DOCNO>
