<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Amoco-ChemicalPlants     07-12 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amoco-Chemical Plants,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amoco to Build Two Chemical Plants in Southeast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp.'s chemical subsidiary will spend
about $150 million to build a research center near Atlanta and a
high-performance carbon-fiber plant in Greenville, S.C., the energy
company said Tuesday.
   The 235,000-square-foot research-and-development center in
Georgia initially will employ about 300 people and is slated for
completion by late 1990, Amoco said in a statement.
   Scientists and engineers at the center will work on product
development and conduct research in carbon fibers, engineering
polymers and advanced composite materials, the company said.
   At Greenville, Amoco will expand its existing polyacrylonitrile
(PAN) and pitch carbon-fiber plant to expand production of PAN
carbon fibers. Demand for the fibers _ used to reinforce
lightweight synthetic materials _ is increasing in the aerospace,
industrial and sporting-goods industries, Amoco said.
   The first of three new production lines at the Greenville plant
is scheduled for start-up in early 1990, the company said. The
expansion is expected to boost employment at the plant from 430 to
nearly 650 over five years, said spokesman Richard Judy.
   Both projects will be handled by Amoco Performance Products
Inc., a unit of Amoco Chemical Co.
   ``A total investment in these two projects of more than $150
million is part of Amoco Chemical's long-term strategy to improve
our already excellent profitability through product innovation,
high-technology research and expansion of capacity to sustain our
competitive advantage,'' said Robert D. Cadieux, president of Amoco
Chemical.
</TEXT>
