<HEAD>Varig of Brazil Orders Five Advanced 737s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Varig of Brazil has placed an order worth $140
million for five technologically advanced 737-300s, Boeing
Commerical Airplanes announced Tuesday.
   Deliveries of the medium-range, twinjet planes will begin later
this year with one delivery in November and another in December,
followed by two deliveries in January and the final plane in
February 1989, the company said.
   Varig, Brazil's major airline, flies every Boeing model except
the 757 on routes throughout the Western Hemisphere, Europe, Africa
and Japan.
   The 737-300s will be equipped with CFM56-3B2 engines built by
CFM International, which is jointly owned by Snecma of France and
General Electric.
   The order brings to 760 the number of 737-300s sold by Boeing.
Total orders for 737s amount to 2,143.
