<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-A&P     07-12 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-A&P,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A&P Reports 25 Percent Sales Increase In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTVALE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co. Inc.
reported a 25 percent increase in its first-quarter earnings over
last year, a gain the company attributed to strict cost controls
and a better product mix.
   The surpermarket giant reported net income of $38 million, or $1
a share, for the quarter ended June 18, compared to $30.4 million,
or 80 cents a share, for the same period in 1987.
   Sales for the latest quarter rose 3.5 percent to $3 billion from
$2.9 billion in the same quarter last year.
   The growth resulted from ``strict cost controls and improving
profit margins through better product mix in more efficient
stores,'' said James Wood, A&P's chairman and chief executive.
   ``We continue to make market share progress in most of our major
operational areas, except the South,'' he said. A&P has closed a
number of stores in the South because ``depressed economic
conditions'' have hurt their sales, Wood said.
   Under a $200 million 1988 capital spending program, five new
stores have opened during the quarter and 20 stores have been
enlarged or remodeled, he said. The company plans a total of 36 new
stores and 100 remodelings in 1988.
</TEXT>
