<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0458</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell under the weight of worries
about inflation and higher interest rates Tuesday as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials closed below 2,100 for the first time in
three weeks.
   The indicator fell 18.67 points to 2,092.64. It last closed
below 2,100 on June 20, at 2,083.93.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by about 7-to-3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
442 issues up, 1,039 down and 481 unchanged.
   A rebound in corn, soybean and gold prices renewed inflation
fears. That hurt the bond market, and weakness in the bond market
carried over to stocks, said William LeFevre, a market strategist
for Advest Inc.
   ``The market remains tricky and treacherous,'' said Alan
Ackerman, an investment strategist for Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   Major computer stocks performed poorly. International Business
Machines fell 2 to 124~ and Digital Equipment sank 3[ to 109.
   Polaroid rose 1| to 31]. The company announced plans to cut up
to 8 percent of its U.S. work force, repurchase up to $300 million
of its shares, and enter the conventional film business worldwide.
   Coleco Industries sank { to 1]. The toymaker announced it had
sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy
Code.
   Xidex rose 1] to 9 in heavy over-the-counter trading of more
than 3.8 million shares. The maker of computer disk drives said it
agreed to be acquired by Anacomp for $10 a share in cash. Anacomp
fell 1[ to 9~ on the NYSE in heavy trading.
   Among other over-the-counter stocks, Intel rose 1[ to 35} on
heavy trading after reporting its earnings nearly tripled in the
latest quarter. Micron Technology fell | to 23\ on news that two
top officers resigned.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE, swollen by dividend-related
trading, came to 161.65 million shares, up from 123.20 million in
the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in
NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on
the over-the-counter market, totaled 184.79 million shares.
   Three issues involved in dividend-capture strategies together
accounted for 17 million shares of the volume on the NYSE floor.
   The NYSE index fell 1.40 to 151.62.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 3.14 to 309.67,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 2.70 to 267.85.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.27
to 307.31. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market fell 0.63 to 393.52.
   The value of all U.S. stocks fell $22.1 billion, or 0.82
percent, to $2.68 trillion, according to Wilshire Associates of
Santa Monica, Calif.
