<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-12 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped Tuesday, as profit-taking
pushed the currency lower against all major currencies except the
Canadian dollar.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank in New York
quoted a late bid for gold of $436.25 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from
Monday's late bid of $434.50.
   Traders said they had expected a slight sell-off of the dollar,
which rose to recent highs against several major currencies on
Monday despite concerted central bank intervention.
   Concern that the central banks might step in again to sell
dollars may have kept the currency from climbing, analysts said.
   The dollar's slow, measured decline began early in Tokyo and
then continued when trading shifted to Europe. In New York, the
currency settled at the lows of the day.
   But traders said bullish sentiment surrounding the U.S. currency
remains intact. ``The dollar hasn't dropped very far _ there's
still very good demand in the market,'' said Stephen Flanagan, an
assistant vice president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   ``People are re-examining what's ahead of us and squaring up
their positions,'' he said, referring to the government's report on
the nation's May trade deficit, which is due out Friday.
   The consensus is that the May report will register about $11
billion, up from the $9.9 billion deficit reported for April, which
was the lowest imbalance in three years.
   In the past, the dollar has plunged in response to an unexpected
widening of the trade gap and soared when it narrowed.
   But Craig Sloane, a currency analyst at Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co., noted that the trade numbers were more of an obsession
earlier in the year.
   ``The dollar has made big moves without the trade numbers, and
the trend to a much stronger dollar has become much more visible in
the last few months,'' he said.
   Sloane said the dollar might be influenced by comments by
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who is scheduled to
testify before the Senate Banking Committee on monetary policy
Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.63 Japanese yen to a closing 132.70 yen.
Later in London, it was slightly lower at 132.63 yen. In New York,
the dollar closed at 132.51 yen, down from 133.07 yen on Monday.
   In London, the British pound closed at $1.6960, up from $1.6900
late Monday. In New York, it cost $1.6970 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Monday's $1.6925.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.8365 West German marks, down from 1.8423;
1.5187 Swiss francs, down from 1.5305; 6.1970 French francs, down
from 6.2065; 1,361.75 Italian lire, down from 1,367.25, and 1.2103
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2072.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8376 West German marks, down from 1.8460; 1.5235 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5350; 6.1940 French francs, down from 6.2080; 2.0745
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0750; 1,363.25 Italian lire, down from
1,364.50, and 1.2100 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2080.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, one troy ounce of gold cost
$437, up from $434.60 on Monday.
   In Europe, gold closed in London at a late bid of $436.50 a troy
ounce, up from $435.10 late Monday. But in Zurich, gold fell $2 to
a bid of $433.50 a troy ounce. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell
$4.41 to close at a bid $437.63.
   Silver bullion rose on New York's Comex to $6.974 a troy ounce
from $6.937 on Monday. In London the metal finished at a bid price
of $6.91 a troy ounce, down from $6.94 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
