<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-12 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Prices Rise in Advance of Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices moved moderately higher Tuesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade in cautious dealings ahead of the
Agriculture Department's eagerly awaited monthly crop report.
   Analysts said the report, released after trading ended and
forecasting a 24 percent decline in overall U.S. grain production,
should send prices higher when trading resumes on Wednesday.
   But they say weather forecasts will continue to dominate the
markets.
   On other markets, livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy
futures were mixed; precious metals were higher and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Grain analysts called the crop report bullish for soybean
prices, bearish for corn and slightly bearish for wheat. But the
anticipated strength in soybeans was expected to offset the
weakness in the grains, ultimately pulling all the grain markets
higher Wednesday _ at least for a few minutes.
   ``After about three minutes of trading, they'll have worked off
their report anxiety and we'll be looking at Friday's, Saturday's
and Sunday's weather, which we see as hot, hot, hot,'' said Walter
Spilka, a grain analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham
& Co.
   ``I don't think the market's going to dwell on this report too
long,'' agreed Joel Karlin, chief research analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Based on conditions as of Tuesday, the USDA predicted a 27
percent drop in corn production from 1987, a 14 percent drop in
soybean production, and a wheat crop 13 percent smaller than that
harvested last year.
   The corn harvest was estimated at 5.2 billion bushels, compared
with the June estimate of 7.3 billion and year-ago production of
7.06 billion.
   The USDA estimated 1988 soybean production at 1.65 billion
bushels, compared with a June estimate of 1.88 billion and 1987
production of 1.9 billion bushels.
   Production of all U.S. wheat was projected at 1.84 billion
bushels, compared with the June estimate of 2.12 billion and 1987
production of 2.1 billion.
   Analysts called the corn and wheat estimates conservative.
   ``This just confirms everybody's opinion that there's some crop
damage out there, and the USDA is looking at a bit more of a
problem in soybeans than the trade had anticipated,'' Spilka said.
   This year's planted soybean acreage, estimated by the USDA at
58.52 million acres, was about 700,000 acres below market
expectations. Planted corn acreage, estimated at 67.52 million
acres, was about 500,000 acres more than expected.
   Grain and soybean futures advanced moderately ahead of the
report, which was issued after the markets closed.
   Wheat settled 8} cents to 13\ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.81\ a bushel; corn was 8\ cents to 17} cents
higher with July at $3.06 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents lower to 15
cents higher with July at $2.79 a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to
21{ cents higher with July at $8.79{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures finished mixed while some pork futures advanced
their daily limits on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in reaction
to the rise in feed grain prices, said Dale Durchholz, a
pork-market analyst with AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington,
Ill.
   Traders expect livestock and meat prices to rise sharply next
year after falling in the near term due to widespread producer
selling of animals this summer because of the drought-driven rise
in feed prices, he said.
   The USDA also reported the worst July 1 pasture conditions in
history, which should encourage further drought-pattern trading on
the livestock markets, said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling
Analytical Services Inc. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Live cattle settled .70 cent lower to .17 cent higher with
August at 65.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .60
cent lower with August at 75.72 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent
to the limit 1.50 cents higher with July at 45.67 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with
July at 33.10 cents a pound.
   Crude oil prices weakened in volatile trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, but unleaded gasoline strengthened because of
tight supplies and speculation about higher U.S. demand, analysts
said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 17 cents
lower with August at $14.72 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent to
.68 cent lower with August at 40.65 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .06 cent lower to 1.35 cents higher with August at
53.48 cents a gallon.
   Precious metals futures posted modest gains on New York's
Commodity Exchange due to the inflationary implications of higher
grain prices and a weaker dollar.
   Gold settled $2 to $2.30 higher with August at $438.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.7 cents to 3.8 cents higher with July at $6.974
a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 3.10 points lower at 269.35.
</TEXT>
