<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CullumBuyout     07-12 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cullum Buyout,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management-Led Group Proposes Taking Cullum Cos. Private</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cullum Cos., a Dallas-based food and drug
retailer, said Tuesday a management-led investor group was offering
to take the company private in a $361 million leveraged buyout.
   Cullum said the investor group, Cullum Acquisition Corp., which
includes the investment banker Morgan Stanley & Co., was offering
$22 a share for Cullum's 16.4 million outstanding shares, or a
total of $361 million.
   In a statement, the retailer said major Cullum stockholders,
including management and Cullum family members, were granting
Cullum Acquisition an option to purchase their shares for $22 each.
   Cullum stock closed at $21.75 Tuesday in over-the-counter
trading, up $1.25 a share.
   The leveraged buyout must be approved by the Cullum board and
was subject to execution of a definitive agreement, the statement
said. In a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy out a
company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash
flow or the sale of its assets.
   Cullum Acquisition said it had commitments for the financing
required for the buyout.
   Cullum Cos. operates 83 retail outlets, including supermarkets
and Hypermart USA, a Garland, Texas hypermarket run as a joint
venture with Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</TEXT>
