<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Xidex-Anacomp     07-12 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Xidex-Anacomp,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Companies Announce Merger Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anacomp Inc., an Indiana-based
computer services company, has signed a letter of intent to
purchase the disk-drive maker Xidex Corp. for about $415 million in
cash, the companies announced Tuesday.
   Indianapolis-based Anacomp, the third largest supplier of
micrographics products in the United States behind 3M Corp. and
Eastman Kodak Co., said it will pay $10 for each of Xidex's 41.5
million outstanding shares.
   The transaction, which requires the approval of both boards of
directors, will result in a company with annual sales of about $1
billion. A definitive agreement is expected to be reached by the
end of the month, the companies said in a statement.
   A spokeswoman for Anacomp, which is a customer of Xidex, said
the Santa Clara company is well managed and makes a good fit.
   ``Anacomp generally looks for a repetitive revenue base in
making such acquisitions,'' said spokeswoman Jo McKee. ``We think
we have a very solid marketing and distribution network that can
maybe boost some of their other businesses.''
   She said it is too soon to comment on whether layoffs would
follow the merger.
   Xidex climbed $1.37{ a share to $9 in the over-the-counter
trading, while Anacomp fell $1.12{ a share to close at $9.87{ on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Xidex, which has posted losses for two straight years due to
writeoffs on acquisitions, is a leading manufacturer of computer
data storage. It controls 25 percent of the world floppy disk
market and also makes computer output microfilm, microfilm readers
and reader printers.
   An analyst who follows both companies called the announcement a
``very attractive'' deal for both sides.
   ``The combined company will have $1 billion worth of annual
sales, a capital base of around $800 million and very strong cash
flows,'' said Mark Obenzinger of Wood, Gundy & Associates in New
York.
   ``You have a strong company in place as far as the competition
is concerned,'' he added.
   Xidex spokesman Steve Bennion said Chief Executive Officer Bert
L. Zaccaria had no comment.
   Anacomp, which employs more than 3,000 people, is a supplier and
manufacturer of services and products based on micro-imaging
technology known as micrographics.
   For the six months ended in March, Anacomp reported net income
of $22.8 million, or 59 cents a share, on revenues of $200.9
million. Obenzinger estimated the company's profits will reach
$45.5 million on revenues of about $400 million in the current
fiscal year.
   Xidex has 7,000 employees worldwide, about half in the San
Francisco Bay area at factories in Santa Clara, Sunnyvale and
Fremont. It also operates factories in Irvine; Omaha, Neb.; Iron
Ridge, Wis.; and Wales, Britain.
   For the nine months ended March 31, the company had a net loss
of $74 million on sales of $467 million.
</TEXT>
