<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Gould-MartinMarietta     07-12 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gould-Martin Marietta,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gould To Sell Anti-Sub Unit to Martin Marietta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLEN BURNIE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. will buy
Illinois-based Gould Inc.'s antisubmarine warfare unit for an
undisclosed sum, the companies announced Tuesday.
   The companies said they expect the purchase of the Ocean Systems
Division, which employs 1,300 workers, to be completed within 30 to
90 days.
   The Glen Burnie plant, with revenues of about $100 million in
1987, is the latest Gould defense operation to be sold under a
wide-ranging restructuring begun two years ago when Gould decided
to get out of the defense business.
   In January, Gould said it would sell its 1,200-worker
heavyweight torpedo operation in Cleveland to Westinghouse Electric
Corp. for about $100 million.
   The company last year sold three other smaller defense
operations. One last unit, NavCom Systems Division in El Monte,
Calif., is still up for sale.
   Originally known as Chesapeake Instrument Corp., the Glen Burnie
operation was purchased by Gould in 1974. It specializes in
antisubmarine warfare, especially towed sonar arrays, which are
underwater listening devices towed behind Navy ships submarines and
used to listen for enemy submarines.
   The Glen Burnie operation also makes array handling equipment,
marine navigation equipment and other kinds of sensors.
   Martin Marietta's 4,500-worker Aero and Naval Systems operation
in Middle River is already involved in some antisubmarine warfare
work, company officials said.
   Gould is based in Rolling Meadow, Ill.; Martin Marietta is
headquartered in Bethesda, Md.
</TEXT>
