<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OrangeJuiceTruce     07-12 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orange Juice Truce,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropicana Announces Juice Truce With Coca-Cola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropicana Products, Inc. announced
Tuesday a truce in its orange juice war with the Coca-Cola Co.
   A settlement between the companies resolves a court dispute over
Tropicana's challenge of Coke's claim that its Minute Maid
``Premium Choice'' orange juice was ``straight from the orange.''
   Tropicana filed a request for an injunction July 1 at federal
court in New York, charging Minute Maid's claim on its package was
false and deceptive based on a 1982 U.S. Court of Appeals decision
about advertising pasteurized orange juice.
   ``Not until Tropicana filed suit did Coca-Cola agree to modify
its advertising and labeling to delete that claim,'' Tropicana said
in a prepared statement.
   Coca-Cola confirmed it has agreed to change its package label.
   ``Under the settlement, Coca-Cola Foods has agreed to
voluntarily remove the phrase `straight from the orange' on its
future packaging,'' Coke said in a prepared statement.
   ``We are extremely pleased with the outcome of this suit,'' said
Pierre Ferrari, a Coca-Cola senior vice president.
   ``Tropicana places a great deal of importance upon truthful
consumer communications, and we are pleased that The Coca-Cola Co.
has recognized its responsiblity to the consumer and has agreed to
those changes in its Minute Maid advertising and labeling,'' said
Martin J. Gutfreund, a Tropicana vice president.
</TEXT>
