<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LotusSoftware     07-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotus Software,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lotus Announces New Agenda Personal Management Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotus Development Corp. on Tuesday
announced the release of its Lotus Agenda software designed to help
people manage personal information.
   The company said the software allows users to organize personal
minutiae such as ideas, notes, lists, messages, telephone numbers,
addresses and schedules in a variety of categories.
   Development of the software began about 10 months ago, but the
idea belonged to Lotus founder Mitchell D. Kapor, who would
scribble notes and stuff them in his shirt pocket, only to lose
them.
   Lotus said its development program included more than 150
corporate and individual testers. Agenda is being credited as
creating a new category of applications software called personal
information management.
   The company said Agenda allows users to enter information ``on
the fly,'' assign it to different categories as desired and observe
it from multiple perspectives.
   Categories might include tasks, departments, people, issues.
Lotus Agenda can be used to manage sales accounts, projects and
calendars, examine news clips or just keep a list, the company said.
   Lotus Agenda is priced at $395 and is available immediately.
   The software runs under DOS 2.0 or higher on IBM PC, XT, AT and
PS-2 or compatible personal computers.
</TEXT>
