<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Bentsen-Labor     07-12 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Labor,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Receives Praise from Labor Despite Poor Union Rating</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also mocving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen has the worst lifetime
voting record on labor issues of any of the running mates Michael
Dukakis was considering, according to an AFL-CIO rating.
Nevertheless, union lobbyists on Tuesday were quick to praise the
Democratic choice.
   The Texas Democrat was hailed for his role in salvaging labor's
top legislative priority this year _ making companies give workers
60 days advance notice before closing their plants or laying them
off.
   ``Bentsen was extremely helpful in recognizing that the two _
plant closing notices and the trade bill _ were compatible,'' said
Robert McGlotten, the 14.1-million-member labor federation's
legislative director. ``And he let his colleagues know how he
felt.''
   The Senate last week passed with a veto-proof 72-vote majority
legislation requiring companies to provide 60 days advance notice
of plant closings or layoffs involving more than 50 people. The
House is expected to follow suit on Wednesday.
   Labor leaders demanded enactment of the mandatory layoff notices
as the price for maintaining their support for a massive
overhauling of the nation's trade laws that Bentsen was a key
player in crafting as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
   Reagan vetoed the trade bill in May, citing the layoff notices
that were then a part of it as his primary reason.
   James Booe, secretary-treasurer of the Communications Workers of
America, and a member of the Democrats' platform-drafting
committee, acknowledged that Bentsen was not labor's main spear
carrier on the trade and plant closing issues.
   ``But he didn't do a lot of the things that he could have done
to mess us up, and there were a lot of other people urging him
to,'' said Booe. ``I don't think you can call him a labor hero, but
he's been on our side more than he's been against us.''
   As a three-term senator from a right-to-work state where less
than 12 percent of the workers belong to unions, Bentsen has always
walked a fine line between conservative businessmen and labor
activists in the Democratic Party.
   Despite a lifetime voting record of only 51 percent on labor
issues, according to the AFL-CIO's Committee on Political
Education, Texas labor leaders endorsed his re-election in 1982.
   All of the five other members of Congress who Dukakis was
considering as possible running mates have stronger COPE voting
records. Another southerner, Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee, had the
highest _ 88 percent.
   But Bentsen was listed as voting ``right'' on eight of 10 issues
in 1987 that the AFL-CIO considered in compiling its rankings,
shoring up his support among labor leaders.
   Bentsen's only wrong votes were on raising the threshold on
government construction contracts for which union-scale wages must
be paid and giving employers who hire illegal aliens extensions
before fining them.
   ``He's been all over the map,'' said Steve Kerekes, a spokesman
for the National Right to Work Committee, a group that advocates
state laws like the one in Texas which outlaws labor contracts that
require non-members to pay dues to unions that represent them.
   Earlier this year, Bentsen came out against a so-called
double-breasting bill that is the top priority of construction
unions. The bill would prohibit unionized companies from operating
non-union subsidiaries as a means of getting around wage and other
provisions of labor contracts they've signed.
   But last month he voted against a measure to make violence on
picket lines a federal crime, a reversal of his vote two years ago
favoring such legislation.
   AFL-CIO members hold 751 of the 4,161 delegates at the
Democratic convention opening next week in Atlanta. Combined with
the National Education Associations' 280 delegates, about
one-fourth of total that will nominate Dukakis and Bentsen come
from the labor movement.
   ``Obviously, we would like to see somebody who had a 100 percent
voting record,'' said McGlotten. ``But as you review things, a COPE
record becomes less important than whether someone's door is open
to us and understands our problems. He understands our problems.''
</TEXT>
