<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Drought-Steel     07-12 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Steel,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steelmakers' Costs Up Because of Drought, But Orders May Be Cut
Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The steel industry faces a possible reduction
in orders as the drought reduces harvests and cuts the demand for
new farm equipment, industry representatives said Tuesday.
   The drought also has increased operating costs by forcing
steelmakers to contract for smaller, lighter ore barge loads that
can navigate shallower waters near the Minnesota ore ranges.
   Steelmakers add, however, the drought likely will not harm the
industry's recovery and the generally strong market for steel.
   USX Corp.'s Gary Works produces tin-plated steel, among other
products, for the canning industry, and Inland Steel Corp., which
operates a facility in East Chicago, supplies steel to farm
machinery manufacturers.
   ``There's some talk that canners, if the crops are lower, will
be canning less, and that could have an effect on shipment,'' said
USX spokesman George Kuebler. ``Harvest time is still down the road
for a lot of crops yet, so we don't see any impact.''
   An Inland newsletter said the company anticipates some customers
might cut back on orders if the drought continues.
   ``Farm equipment manufacturers, in particular, may be hurt by
declining sales of tractors and combines,'' the newsletter said.
   Inland spokesman George Nekvasil said some companies that depend
on river traffic stalled by drought-lowered waters may reduce steel
orders if they can't move their own finished products to market.
   Kuebler said smaller ore loads increase shipping costs by about
10 percent. That has not yet translated into an increase in steel
prices, he said.
   Nevertheless, orders for steel remain strong, said Nekvasil.
   ``We continue to see business conditions strong,'' he said. ``I
certainly wouldn't see anything that would threaten recovery or
profitability. There's a very strong market for steel today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
