<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drought-Congress 1stLd-Writethru f0242 07-12 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0242,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Unveil Disaster Bill as Lyng Warns of `Mammoth' Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs bgng, `A 50 cent,' with 1 graf to CLARIFY
that reduction was per hundredweight</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers unveiled a wide-ranging relief bill
for America's drought-stricken farmers Tuesday, promising payments
of up to $100,000 to keep them on the land despite the withering
heat and lack of rain.
   The legislation is expected to move quickly through Congress.
The chairmen of both the House and Senate Agriculture committees
vowed to move as rapidly as possible and Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng said that because of the extent of the drought, the
Reagan administration will overlook minor flaws in the bill and
support the measure.
   ``This is the largest drought that our nation has ever
experienced,'' Lyng declared as senators met to start committee
action on the disaster legislation.
   ``I think history will show that it's truly more mammoth than
any of us has ever experienced,'' Lyng said. He said a recurrence
next year would ``suggest that we've done something wrong and the
Gods are against us.''
   Lawmakers did not give an estimate of the cost of the relief
legislation but expressed their resolve not to allow drought to set
off a rash of bankruptcies in the countryside, just as the farm
economy is shaking off the painful stagnation of the early 1980s.
   ``We're not going to allow their lives as farmers and ranchers
to end because of a freak of nature,'' Senate Agriculture Committee
Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said.
   Both the Senate and House Agriculture committees opened hearings
on the bill on Tuesday.
   The chairman of the House panel, Rep. E. ``Kika'' de la Garza,
D-Texas, said it ``would send the wrong signal'' to leave the job
unfinished in August when lawmakers flee Washington's heat. He
added that he was hopeful the panel could dispense with any parade
of witnesses from farm lobbies and instead act this week on any
changes congressmen want to make in the draft bill.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., also called for ``quick
action'' on the legislation because the ``American farmer needs
help. It's that simple.''
   ``We must make certain that our relief package is targeted to
those who need the help,'' Dole said in a statement. ``There can be
no windfalls for any individual or group. We owe that much to the
farmers and the taxpayers.''
   Lyng was briefing House members on the long, hot dry spell when
aides arrived from the Agriculture Department five blocks away with
a fresh forecast that the drought would cut this year's corn output
to around 5.2 billion bushels, down from 7.06 billion last year.
   Under the proposed legislation, disaster payments would be
capped at $100,000 for each individual farmer. Payments would
represent 65 percent of pre-drought expected earnings, whether from
target prices, price-support loans or market prices. But they would
apply only to losses in excess of 35 percent of the crop.
   A 50 cent reduction per hundredweight in dairy price supports
scheduled to start next year would be canceled under the
legislation. Dairymen say such an action is warranted by
skyrocketing feed costs, although it was one of their prime goals
long before the drought set in.
   Government emergency feed programs already in effect would be
overhauled and made available to a broader range of farmers. The
drought has burned away a considerable amount of hay and thus put
feed at a premium.
   Wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice producers would not be
required to refund to the government any deficiency payments they
have received in advance. The income-support payments represent the
difference between the market value of their harvest and its value
at higher, so-called target prices set by Congress under the 1985
farm program and adjusted annually by the secretary of agriculture.
   Market prices have climbed steadily closer to target prices in
anticipation of a diminished harvest, and thus the drought has
reduced federal income-support payments as well. The drying up of
these subsidies at a time when farmers have fewer crops to take to
market threatens to hurt some of them.
   To complicate matters, many farmers have received 40 percent of
their deficiency payments from the Department of Agriculture in
advance and will have to refund a portion of them unless rescued by
relief legislation.
   Another key provision would help farmers convert from production
of corn, cotton and a variety of other crops to soybean production
without paying certain financial penalties under the farm program.
   The provision is being closely watched in the farm and segments
of the financial communities because soybeans are expected to be in
short supply as a result of the drought and prices already are
soaring.
</TEXT>
