<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Caterpillar     07-12 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Caterpillar,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 23 Percent Profit Gain in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc. posted a second-quarter
profit of $145 million on Tuesday, a 23 percent increase over the
same period a year earlier.
   The $145 million profit for second-quarter amounted to $1.44 a
share, compared with a profit of $118 million, or $1.20 a share, in
the same period last year.
   Second-quarter sales rose to $2.6 billion, up 26 percent from
$2.1 billion a year earlier.
   For the first half of the year, Caterpillar earned $263 million,
or $2.60 a share, compared to $34 million, or 35 cents per share,
for the first half of 1987.
   First-half revenue rose to $4.98 billion from $3.74 billion a
year earlier.
   Polzin said Caterpillar achieved record sales and robust profit
levels despite higher costs for materials such as steel, and
problems caused by a weakening of the U.S. dollar overseas.
   The world's largest manufacturer of earth-moving equipment
finished in the black for the fifth consecutive quarter and said it
expects company sales for the year will ``substantially exceed
sales in 1987.''
   Caterpillar spokesman Mark Polzin said 1987 sales of $8.18
billion represented the company's best performance since 1981, when
it had record sales of $9.15 billion.
   Only three months ago, the company said its sales would match
the growth which occurred in 1987.
   ``Economic growth will be faster this year than assumed
earlier,'' Polzin said. ``And replacement demand will be stronger
than expected.''
   Polzin said Caterpillar also is commanding higher prices than
expected for its products and pleased with the acceptance of
several recently introduced models.
   Caterpillar is rebuilding from a market collapse in 1981 which
led to three years of losses that amounted to $950 million.
   A general overcapacity in the industry and fierce competition at
home and abroad combined during the early 1980s to hurt Caterpillar.
   The company has fought back to financial health with a
cost-cutting program. Savings were made by closing plants and
massive layoffs, including slashing its Peoria-area workforce in
half, eliminating about 18,000 positions.
</TEXT>
