<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USG-MerrillLynch     07-12 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG-Merrill Lynch,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Settles Lawsuit Against Merrill Lynch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. said Tuesday it had reached an
out-of-court settlement of its 2-month-old lawsuit charging Merrill
Lynch & Co. with attempting to profit from the illegal use of
confidential information.
   USG, the country's leading producer of gypsum wallboard and
other building materials, would not reveal the terms of the
agreement.
   The lawsuit, filed May 3 in U.S. District Court in Chicago,
stemmed from Merrill Lynch's involvement in an attempted hostile
takeover of USG by Desert Partners L.P., a partnership headed by
oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown of Midland, Texas.
   USG had accused the New York investment house of providing
Desert Partners with confidential information acquired while
Merrill Lynch served as USG's financial adviser in prior business
deals.
   Merrill Lynch denied any conflict in its involvement with Desert
Partners, which withdrew its takeover bid on June 9 after losing a
proxy fight for six seats on USG's board of directors.
   Merrill Lynch was one of Desert Partners' financial advisers in
its takeover attempt and had committed $200 million of its own
money to assist in the proposed takeover.
</TEXT>
